(1, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo0NzgyMDoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Small plant, about six inches in height, with roots \"half the size of a mans finger\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65);', '1. Grows in dry prairies (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: roots boiled and eaten with sugar. \"keeshikeehaukee is the root of a small plant growing in the dry prairies, about six inches in height. The roots are half the size of a mans finger and grow in a cluster. They are boiled and generally eaten with sugar\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1825', '1825', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(2, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODQxNToy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Prairie grass', 'Poaceae (Grass)', '(mahkihkiwi)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: prairie plants (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. (MEDICINAL):  (LeBoullenger 1714-1744); 3. MEDICINAL: used for medicine: \"I take some of this medicine\" (Gravier ca. 1700:021.11, \"makiki8i nini, de cette medecine, jen prend\");', NULL, NULL, '1. A medicine called \'maskiki\' is used by Ojibwe (000?), the Shawnee word for a leaf is \'msiski\' (000?), and the Fox word for blade of grass is \'masiskiwi\' (000?). These references together indicate that a prairie grass blade is probably used for a medicinal purpose by all of these cultural groups (Author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1700', '-1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, ' ', '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(3, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NjozODc0NDoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Medicine tree', NULL, '(neenasionki)', '1. \'Neenasionki\' \"is a tall tree of the southwest of the United States which attains a height of 50 to 80 feet.\" \". . . resembling a pecan tree, with few limbs only, trunk straight, and resembling closely the white oak. It bears nuts and the wood is good for burning.\" (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria);', '1. \"My informant saw it nowhere but around the council-house of the Seneca Indians, Quapaw Reservation, Indian Territory.\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MEDICINAL: roots used for medicinal purposes. \". . . the Peoria name . . . means the \"unrecognized one.\" \"The roots are called \"great medicine\" by the untutored natives of western prairies. My informant saw it nowhere but around the council-house of the Seneca Indians, Quapaw Reservation, Indian Territory.\" (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria); 2. TECHNOLOGY: firewood. \"It bears nuts and the wood is good for burning\" (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria);', NULL, NULL, '1. Not necessarily the same tree species, but the Peoria account of this \'medicine tree\' by Dunn is reminiscent of a Shawnee account of a tree with impressive medicinal properties, whose fruits produced a pain-numbing effect in humans as powerful as opium  (Eckert 1967:605, notes, from Galloway, W.A., 1934, Old Chillicothe, Xenia, pp. 281-283);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(4, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NDI2Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Prairie dandelion', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', '(peehkateeki)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. \'Peehkateeki\' could refer to any one of a number of prairie dwelling dandelion species, including the dwarf dandelion, Krigia dandelion, (perhaps K. virginica, although it is only listed as growing in sandy places), or one of the false dandelions, Agoseris glauca, or Pyrrhopappus carolinianus (Nomenclature from Gleason and Cronquist, 1991, used, and Small (1903), Coulter (1899) used to narrow down species possibilities. No mention of a prairie dandelion in Bogue (1900) (Author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(5, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTEyNzoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Wild potato', NULL, '(wiikapaahkwaahkani≈°a)', NULL, '1. Found in abundance in wet prairies (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: tubers eaten. \"These are found in abundance in the wet prairies throughout the country and are gathered in \"hoeing time\" (June). They are easily boiled and when they wish to change colour the Indians throw into the kettle a few leaves of the soft maple, which turns them black\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63-64); 2. (FOOD): but refers to adding leaves of soft maple to a batch of boiling wild potatoes to turn them black (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. FOOD: the Miami-Illinois term \'ahpena\' means potatoes, and indicated a number of species growing in the western prairies. \"This \"pomme blance\" as named by the \"coureurs des bois\" look dark and are sweeter than our Irish potatoes. They cook in six hours and are usually called by these Indians nalau\'xki pa<\'nacki\" or nalaaohki ahpena, wild potato (em p 359); 4. FOOD: \"I found some roots, potatoes, for example digging with a stick etc.\" (Gravier ca.1700:291.15, \"j ay trouve  des racines, pommes de terre, 8g fouissant avec un boic &c.\"); 5. FOOD: tubers cooked. \"waap-\", \"It is easily cooked and is considered very good\", resembling the cultivated potato in appearance and taste, found growing in the low prairies (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65)[may refer to a different species]; 6. FOOD: tubers boiled in water by a slow fire, and then eaten. :\"That country [lands around Lake Michigan] also produces potatoes, some are as large as an egg, others have the size of one\'s fist, or a little more. They boil these in water by a slow fire during twenty-four hours, when they are thoroughly cooked, you will find in them an excellent flavor, much resembling that of prunes\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:117, Perrot\'s description may refer to Psoralea esculenta, Helianthus tuberosa or another species producing sizeable tubers, this ref. also published by Dunn ca. 1900);', '1. These wild potatoes are gathered in hoeing time [June] (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63);', NULL, '1. The Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993); 2. Dunn noted the terms for potato as ahpeniiki also (Dunn ca. 1900:3786dw, 3787dw, Gatschet ca. 1895:1809); 3. Dunn recorded the following sentence in his word list: \"meeshimi\'narkee peeta\'rweeloa paanarkee [potatoes] misa\'u aupo\'oshee\" which means \"Bring the apples, potatoes, bread ad wood\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3788dw); 4. Topeka means \"a place to find small or wild potatoes\" in the Kaw language, and in the swamp or dry lake near the Shawnee hills exist (location of the Indianola ferry of the past) many wild potatoes grow and are eaten by wild hogs (Aatotankiki myaamiaki 1(2):2, originally from Moore 1908);', 'FALSE', 'aphpeniiki (Trowbridge, Dunn, Gat)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1825', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(6, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2NzUwOjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Mushroom', 'Basiodiomycetes (Mushrooms)', 'waapantwa', NULL, '1. Found growing out of year-old or more horse manure in horse pasture (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: (Gatschet ca. 1895, Miami); 2. FOOD: picked and eaten. Lots of types picked, mostly the ones that grew in pasture fields where there were horses--the mushrooms growing out of the manure that was at least one year old and had been worked into the ground. There were spring mushrooms and fall mushrooms. The fall mushrooms were the same as the ones that were bought in the store, pink underneath and good tasting [Agaricus sp.]. Some were poisonous so they stuck to eating the ones they knew (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 3. FOOD: \" . . . Godfroy\'s belief was that they did not use poke, mushrooms, or wild lettuce, until they learned to eat them from the whites. He was probably wrong as to this, as the instruction concerning the use of native plants came the other way\" (Dunn 1919);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'wilinankwia', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(7, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MTQxNDoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Prairie lilies', NULL, '..akk..g..l..yia?', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. (UKNOWN/NONE): (unknown source list);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(8, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4NjQ1Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Onions', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Found in prairies (Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: gathered and stored. \"They also store up onions, as big as Jerusalem artichokes, which they find in the prairies, and which I find better than all the other roots. They are sugary and pleasing to the palate. They are cooked like macopines\" (Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721, \"Elles amassent aussi des oignons gros comme des Topiniamboures, qu\'elles trouvent dans les prairies que je trouve meilleures que toutes les autres Racines, ils sont sucre et font plaisir a manger on les fait cuire comme les Macopines,\" translation from French to English by Pease);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, 'oignons', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1721', '1721', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(9, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4OTE5OjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Roots (various species)', NULL, '(aciipihki)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: root used to cure rattlesnake bite. \". . . they have an admirable root, which, as soon as it is applied to the wound, softens the swelling so that by the next day one is cured. This root is found in the prairies and is shaped like an onion. The stem grows two feet high, the leaves are very narrow and somewhat resemble those of the sumac. It forms large buds in which the seed is lodged. I have made a point of hunting for it in this country, but have never been able to find any. I have been told that they had still another kind, but I have not become acquainted with it.\" (Pease 1934:372, Deliette 1721, \"qu\'ils ont d\'une Racine admirable, sitot qu\'on en a mis sur la playe elle fait amolir L\'enflure et le Lendemain on est guery, cette Racine se trouve dans Les prairies et est faitte comme unoignon,La tige vient de deux pieds de deux pieds de haut, La feuille fort etroitte qui aproche celle des Vinaigriers, Il se forme de gros Boutons dans quoy est la graine, je me suis attachez a en chercher dans ce pays mais je n\'en ay jamais pu trouver, on ma dit qu\'il y en avoit encore d\'une autre sorte, mais je ne la connois point,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. FOOD: \"sweet roots\" and vegetables were usually cultivated or gathered in large quantities. Mentioned by Trowbridge in the context of wedding gifts, a series of reciprocities, where sweet roots and vegetables being given by the older women in-laws of the bride  in return for the meat given by the bride\'s brother (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:43); 3. MEDICINAL: emetics. \"The most common medicines are emetics . . . composed of roots, which are pounded and mixed with water.\" \"There are many roots and weeds used by them for emetics, the most common of which is the root of the Buckeye.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:48); 4. MEDICINAL: treatment for rheumatism is to apply pounded roots and weeds with a bandage to affected areas.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:48); 5. MEDICINAL: a kind of homeopathic medicine using roots. Some medicine men used the same root that \'conveys\' the disease to cure it.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:49); 6. MEDICINAL: special medicine men could cure a patient of a disease originating from a poison. The medicine man coughs up a white substance, places it in his hand. If it goes through the medicine man\'s hand, the patient will die, if it does not, he will live. Before this is known, the medicine man give the patient a small supply of roots and tells him to have good faith, then leaves. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:55); 7. FOOD: keeshikeehaukee is a small plant growing in the dry prairies, and is about six inches in height, with small roots about an inch long growing in a cluster. These are boiled and eaten with sugar. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65); 8. FOOD: waukeepaaneekee is a plant growing in the bottom lands that is similar to the onion in root and shape. It is boiled 12 hours before eaten. It is not a popular food because it causes constipation. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65);', '1. Village location sometimes was chosen for its nearness to an abundance of root crops (Pease 1934:350, Deliette 1721, \"y en a une si grande quantite dans la Riviere et principalement dans le Lac au bout duquel les Illiois sont Etablis du coste du nord a cause de la quantite de Racine qu\'il,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. A digging stick was used for gathering roots or potatoes. \"I have found some roots, potatoes, for example digging with a stick etc.\" (Gravier ca.1700:291.15, \"nimic8ah8aki,\" \"j ay trouve des racines, pommes de terre, 8g fouissant avec un bois &c,\" translation from French to English by Masthay 000?); 3. The Old Illinois term \'nimic8picahan\' translates to modern French as \"je l ay cherche dans l eau avec un baston et je la ay trouve,\" meaning \"I looked for it in the water with a stick and I found it\" (Gravier ca.1700:292.25). Since this directly follows the entry for macopines, it proably refers to a harvesting methods of this, and other edible aquatic roots (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'mamakipeniki (Gr)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1677', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(10, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4MzQ4OjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Melepikan', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: eaten as greens (Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978);', NULL, NULL, '1. Melipikan is indian name for the plant (Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978); 2. Possibly related to this word: \'pekan\' is a French-Canadian word for an animal called a Fisher, Mustela pennanti, similar to a Marten or Mink. Its fur was highly sought after by fur trappers (Blair 1911:113);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1978', '1978', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(11, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo4ODg4Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Wood', 'Wood', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. CUSTOMS: funeral. Timber from an old canoe was used to laid dead body on and to act as walls to hold the earth in place along the sides of the graves. Favorite items were placed with the body in the grave, regardless of status, including a little kettle or pot, tobacco, corn, a calumet, bow and arrows. A forked stick is placed a foot from the deceased head and feet and stakes are set around to keep the animals out (Pease 1934:357-358, Deliette 1721, \"Ils couppent ordinairement deux fourches de dix pieds et un travers creusent la terre de la Longueur de la personne, et un peu plus Large mettent une planche de leurs Vieux Canots ou pirogues et posent le mort dedans en mettant une a chaque coste . . . Une petite chaudiere ou pot de terre, Environ une jointee de Bled, un Caumet, une pincee de Tabac un arc et des fleches, et Ensuite ils replantent une de ces fourches a un pied de ses pieds et l\'autre a la meme distance de sa teste, Le travers dessus et ensuitent posent leurs pieux en des d\'asne de chaque coste et ont le soin de bien fermer les bouts de maniere que les animequx n\'y puissent entrer,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. CUSTOMS: funeral. Deceased placed into coffin-like enclosures made of bark. Prior to the burial there was singing and danced for about 24 hours, and dancers had gourd rattles. After this 24 hour period, the body was buried with \"indian wheat\" (Joutel) and a pot to cook it in so the person would not be hungry during the journey (Joutel\'s journal of LaSalle\'s last voyage down the Mississippi (?), Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 3(1):3, 2000); 3. CUSTOMS: funeral. Body buried in the halves of a hollowed out tree, one half held the body, the other was put on top. The two halves were bound together with rope or anchored to the ground with crosspieces (Robertson 1879, Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):3, 2000); 5. CUSTOMS: funeral. \"If the deceased has been a chief of war parties that have brought in prisoners they plant a tree forty or fifty feet long, which several men go to fetch at the request of the relatives, who give a feast. From this tree they peel the bark and color it with the shades of red and black and make pictures of the chief and the prisoners he has taken, tie a bundle of small logs representing as many persons as he has killed, which they also fasten to the stake and then they plant it beside the tomb\" (Pease 1934:357-358, Deliette 1721, \"Si c\'est un chef de partis, qui ayent amene des prisonniers, ils plantent une arbres que plusrs. Hommes vont chercher sur la demande que leur en font les parents par un festin de quarente ou cinqte. Pieds de long, duquel ils levent l\'ecorce, Et y font des nuances de Rouge et de noir et dessinent son portraits, et les prissonniers qu\'il amene Lie un tas de Buchettes d\'autant de personnes qu\'il a tue qu\'il attachent encore au poteau et ensuitte ils le plantent a coste du tombeau,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 6. CUSTOMS: war death song. Honoring those killed in battle after victory. \"These [warriors] sing their death song, holding in one hand a stick ten or twelve feet long, filled with feathers from all the kinds of birds that the warriors killed on the road\" (Pease 1934:383, Deliette 1721, \"qui chantent leurs chansons de mort, ayant dans une main un baston de dix ou douze pieds de Long, rempli de plumes de toutes les sortes d\'oyseaux que les guerriers ont Tuez dans la Route,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 7. CUSTOMS: funeral. Story about a coffin made for a soldier that died on the Peoria reservation. \"They marked a hickory tree at the head of the grave with marks three feet from the ground and a chinquapin oak at the foot of the grave near the ground.\"(Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 8. CUSTOMS: funeral. \"Four persons, not related to the deceased are appointed by the relatives to carry the body to the grave. This is prepared by digging to the depth of two and a half or three feet, and is lined with planks or b ?;', '1. \"In the spring, when the nation returns from its winter sojourn, which is at the end of March, or at the beginning of April, they busy themselves gathering wood so as to be able to do their planting at the beginning of May without interruption, for, although in this country the snow is not over four fingers deep and does not lie on the ground a week, and although the rivers are all open at the beginning of March, there are cold spells in May as severe as those of winter.\" (Pease 1934:339, Deliette 1721, \"le printemps que la nation revient de L\'hivernement qui est a la fin de mars ou au commencementd\'avril, elles s\'occupent a amasser du bois pour pouvoir faire leur semences au commencement de may sans ce detourner, car quoy que dans ce pays la, il n\'y ait pas plus de quatre doigts de neige que meme elle ne dure pas huit jours sur la terre, et que les Rivieres soient toutes deprises au commencement de mars il vient que d\'estre au mois de may, des froids qui sont aussy rudes qu\'en hiver,\" translation from French to English by pease); 2. The Miami-Illinois term \"kipinhsi\" means to cut wood or brush (Dunn ca. 1900:876); 3. The Miami-Illinois phrase \"nila sakusamani kipintha\" means \'I burn down the bushes\" (Gastchet ca. 1895:2022);', NULL, '1. The women are in charge of cutitng the wood with an axe, carrying it to the lodge, making the fire and cooking the food (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:46); 2. Charlevoix notes a procedure by which the Potawatomi (\"Outagamies\") determined the fate of prisoner. \"Some time ago, a Frenchman having been taken by the Outagamies, these barbarians held a council on their march to determine what they should do with him. The result of their deliberation was to throw a stick upon a tree, and if it remained there to burn the prisoner, but not to throw it above a certain number of times. Happily for the captive, the stick fell always to the ground, though the tree was extremely bushy\" (Charlevoix 1683-1761:204, from Kellogg 1923:189); 3. Perrot described the creation story of Algonquians, including a large raft made of wood, carrying all the animals that existed at the time of creation. \"They believe that before the earth was created there was nothing but water, that upon this vast extent of water floated a great wooden raft, upon which were all the animals, of various kinds, which exist on earth, and the chief of these, they say, was the Great Hare\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:31-32); 4. Perrot described the making of bow and arrow by the first men, in the creation story, using wood, bark and nettle cordage. \"These first men, I say, whom hunger had weakened, inspired by the Great Hare with an intuitive idea, broke off a branch from a small tree, made a cord with the fibers of the nettle, scraped the bark from a piece of a bough with a sharp stone, and armed its end with another sharp stone, to serve them as an arrow, and thus they formed a bow [and arrows] with which they killed small birds\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:38); 5. Perrot described the use of \'soft wood\' for making fires, in the Algonquian creation story. \". . .they tried to make fire, in order to cook their meat, and, trying to get it, they took for that purpose hard wood, but without success, and [finally] they used softer wood, which yielded them fire\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:38); 6. Algonquian women, in general, were responsible for gathering firewood and making bark dishes. The men made the wooden dishes. \"The obligations of women are to . . . furnish firewood . . . They apply themselves to fashioning dishes of bark, and their husbands make the wooden dishes\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:75-76); 7. Algonquians use a light piece of wood to make a cradleboard Perrot (1680-1718, from Blair 1911:77); 8. Algonquians use of wooden scaffolds on which to place the deceased (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:89); 9. Algonquians play a game called crosse, played with a wooden ball and racket with a netted end, like a tennis racket. \"There is among them a certain game, called crosse, which has much likenes to our game of long tennis . . . You will see them all equipped with the crosse--which is a light club, having at one end a broad flat part that is netted like a racket, the ball that they use in playing is of wood, and shaped very nearly like a turkey\'s egg\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:93); 10. Algonquians use a wooden bowl in the dice game. \"The savages have also a certain game of dice,in which the dice-box is a wooden dish, quite round, empty, and very smooth on both sides\" (Perrot 1680-1718, fro Blair 1911:101); 11. Father Gravier (ca. 1700) listed the term \"katookwakami?i\" (106.08) for the wood of an unknown tree and \"cat8c8acamina\" (106.07) for the fruit of an unknown tree\" but it is unclear whether these terms are to indicate ANY unknown wood of fruit, or one particular tree that was unknown to the speaker; 12. The Miami term \"pakianakgi\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1767) or \"pa\'kianakki\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3111), mean the limb of a tree or bush;', 'FALSE', 'pakianakg (branch, Gat), rel info 11; katookwakami?i  (Grav.), rel info 10', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1673', '1997', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(12, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3MjUwMToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Bark', 'Bark', NULL, 'alakiihkwi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. MATERIAL: bark peeled for unknown purpose [reason not noted, but this was a buffalo hunting camp and their actions were probably related to making camp during the buffalo hunt] (Pease 1934:313, Deliette 1721, \"plusrs. feemes qui estoient aux Environs a lever des ecorces vinrent au coup de fusil,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. MATERIAL: \"They use the same term for bark boards, and two of these apacoyas, one on top of the other, protect one from the rain as well as the best blanket. These are the cabins which they use in autumn and winter, even if they leave their canoes, the women carry these on their backs (Pease 1934:340-341, Deliette 1721, \"ils disent de mesme pour des planches escorces, et deux de ces apacoya L\'un sur l\'autre, metent aussi bien a la pluye que la meilleure couverture, se sont les Cabanes don??t ils se servent l\'automne et l\'hiver, quoy quils quittent leurs pirogues, les femmes les portent sur leurs dos,\"translation from French to English by Pease); 3. FOOD: used in cooking macopines (white water lily rhizome) in a pit, roots placed on aquatic grass which was laid over hot rocks in a pit, then roots covered with dry grass and bark (Pease 1934:346, Deliette 1721, \"chaque Cabanes met ses Racines en un Endroit les couvrent d\'herbes seches et des Ecorces par dessus et ensuite de la terre,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 4. CUSTOMS: funeral. \"If the deceased has been a chief of war parties that have brought in prisoners they plant a tree forty or fifty feet long, which several men go to fetch at the request of the relatives, who give a feast. From this tree they peel the bark and color it with the shades of red and black and make pictures of the chief and the prisoners he has taken, tie a bundle of small logs representing as many persons as he has killed, which they also fasten to the stake and then they plant it beside the tomb\" (Pease 1934:358, Deliette 1721, \"Si c\'est un chef de partis, qui ayent amene des prisonniers, ils plantent une arbres que plusrs. Hommes vont chercer sur la demande que leur en font les parents par un festin de quarente ou cinqte. pieds de long, duquel ils levent l\'ecorce, Et y font des nuances de Rouge et de noir et dessinent son portraits, et les prissoniers qu\'il a amene Lie un tas de Buchettes d\'autant de personnes qu\'il a tue qu\'il attachent encore au poteau et ensuitte ils le plantent a coste du tombeau,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 5. MATERIAL: shingles made of bark for the houses, fastened to rafters by wooden pins (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 6. MATERIAL: spring shelter made of logs covered with bark. \"The respective bands assemble together in the spring at their several ordinary places of resort, where some have rude cabins, made of small logs, covered with bark, but, more commonly, some poles stuck in the ground and tied together with pliant slips of bark, and covered with large sheets of bark, or a kind of mats made of flags\" (Dillon 1859:16-17, from a letter written by an Indian Agent, Benjamin F. Stickney to Thomas L. McKinley, Superintendent of Indian Affairs, 8/27/1817); 7. TECHNOLOGY: bark used as a hand-held torch. Trowbridge describes its use in courtship, where a young man would go secretly into the lodge of the parents of the girl of his interest, us?;1', NULL, NULL, '1. Peoria observation of Nez Perces when they were held in Miami--\"In the spring, when the bark would slip easily, they would select their tree and cut it and then carefully remove the bark and sew the ends together. This was waterproofed and across the center to hold the sides apart they would put a hole to make it as wide as they wanted.\"(Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. During hunting, women collect poles and bark and makes a lodge as soon the man has prepared a place for the kettle (two poles to support a cross-piece of wood) and gone off to hunt (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:47); 3. Algonquians use bark to fill in the wound made from an awl, during ear-piercing which is part of a ritual for five or six month old children. \"After he [the juggler] has ended his pouch a flat bodkin made a bone, and a stout awl, and with the former pierces both ears of the child, and with the awl its nose. He fills the wounds in the ears with little rolls of bark, and in the nose he places the end of a small quill, and leaves it there until the wound is healed by a certain ointment with which he dresses it. When it has healed, he places in the aperture some down of the swan or the wild goose\" Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:77); 4. Upon the death of a man\'s brother Algonquians, neighbors to the surviving brother offer the deceased two gifts in order to remove the tears of his relatives, a mat to lie on and a piece of bark to shelter the corpse from the weather. \"In the speech which they [neighbors] accompany this gift they declare that it is made in order to wipe away the tears of his relatives, and that the mat which they give him is for him to lie on, or [that they give--Blair\'s note] a piece of bark to shelter his corpse from the injurious effects of the weather\" (1680-1718, from Blair 1911:80);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1673', '1909', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(13, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1ODgzOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Grass', 'Dried Grass, weeds, stalks', 'Poaceae (Grass)', '(miitakatwi)', NULL, '1. Dry grass: occurs in open areas, meadows, prairies, etc. throughout eastern and western Miami lands (author\'s note); 2. Wet grass occurs in wetlands, ponds and slow moving streams (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: dry, very fine grass was crushed and used as kindling to catch sparks from fire started with wooden stick and board (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:317-318, \"ils mettent ce morceau de bois sur du bois poury, ou sur de l\'herbe bien seche et bien fine, apres qu\'ils ont eu le soin de la bien ecraser dans leurs mains,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. UNKNOWN: word for dry grass (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. MATERIAL: tall grasses used to cover sheds made for drying corn and other foods. \"I think she said when they first come from Indiana there was a tall grass [e.g. tall prairie grasses, like Big bluestem (Andropogon gerardii), Indian grass (Sorghastrum nutans), Switch grass (Panicum virgatum), and Canada wild rye (Elymus canadensis)] that they covered their dry sheds with . . . To dry their corn or somethin\' like that. They tied it down with poles. Now that\'s amazing to me how that would turn [repel] water\" (Interview with Rose Carver by J.W. Tyner, Miami, OK, 9/9/1968, in MTO Archives); 4. UNKNOWN: \"mitakatwa, grass, hay, wheat and other cereals, straw of all kinds, is a collective noun\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1264); 5. UNKNOWN: \"tauhkautwee, grass\" (tw 000:tw);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1721', '1968', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(14, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo1NzQ5Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Straw', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. MATERIAL: game with bean-seeds and straws. \"At night most of the men, seated like dogs on mats of round reeds, play with straws. For markers they use the little beans which I have mentioned, which grow on the thorny trees. The game is usually of 200 straws of the length of a foot. The one who can best deceive is the best player, so they are always on the lookout against being deceived. They mark with their beans one or two, according to the wish of the one whose turn it is to mark, then three, and so in regard to the other players up to six, which is the game. One of them takes the straws in both hands and forces his thumb into the middle. The other, if he so desires, does the same thing, and afterwards counts the straws by sixes, if he happens to have one left, and one bean is marked the first, he has the head, if the other gets two which are marked next, it is what they call the neck which comes after the head, so he loses, if he gets one like the other, they begin over again. They have perhaps five or six hundred of these beans, some of which they stake on each play, and when one player has them all before him, they gain what they have staked. They are addicted to this game in a degree that cannot be exceeded [more on their actions regarding the game] (Pease 1934:351-352 , Deliette 1721, \"et la nuit comme des Chiens la plus part assis sur des nattes de joncs ronds jouent avec des pailles, pour leurs marques ils se servent de ces petites fevves don??t je viens de parler que ces arbres charges d\'epines raportent, le jeu est ordinairement de 200. pailles de la Longueur d\'un pied, celuy quy scait mieux tromper est le plus habile joueur, ainsi i\" sont toujours sur le qui vive a prendre garde si ils ne ce trompent ils marquent avec leurs graines, un ou deux selon la volonte de celuy a qui s\'est a marquer ensuite trois ainsy des autres jusq\'au nombre de six qui est le jeu un prend les pailles dans ses deux mains et foure le poulce dans le milieu, si c\'est sa volonte L\'autre fait le meme chose et apres compte par six les pailles, si il arrive qu\'il aye un de Reste et qu\'une fevve soit marquee la premiere il a la teste, si l\'autre amenne deux qui seront marquees ensuitte, c\'est ce ce qu\'ils appellent le col qui est apres la teste ainsy ils perd, si il amenne un comme l\'autre ils recommancent, ils ont peut estre 5. ou 600. de ces fevves don??t ils mettent une partie a chaque coup, et quand un les a toutes devant Luy ils gagnet ce qu\'ils ont mis au jeu, Ils y sont adonnes il ne se peut d\'avantage,\"translation from French to English by Pease); 2. CUSTOMS: killing prisoners of war. \"When he [prisoner of war] is condemned to die, it is always by fire. I have never seen any other kind of torment used by this nation. They plant a little tree in the earth, which they make him clasp, they tie his two wrists, and with torches of straw of firebrands they burn him, sometimes for six hours.\" (Pease 1934:385, Deliette 1721, \"Quand il est condamne a la mort c\'est toujours par le feu, Je n\'ay jamais vu d\'autres genres de suplices chez cette nation. On plante un petit Arbre dans la terre qu\'on luy fait em', NULL, NULL, '1. The Algonquian game of straws utilizes stems, or straws, from a special plant with stems of thickness smaller than the cordage for a salmon-net. \"They take for this sport a certain number of straws, or of the stems of a special plant, which is not so thick as the cord for a salmon-net, and with these they make little sticks all alike in length and thickness, the length is about eleven inches, and the number is uneven\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:96);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1682', '1721', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(15, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo2Mzc0Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Trees', 'Tree', NULL, 'ahtawaani', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. CUSTOMS: war preparations. \"They also mark places for joining each other in case they are obliged to go by several different routes, and in such cases those who arrive first take a little of what they have left, if they need it, and leave their marks, which they never mistake. They paint a portrait of themselves for this purpose on the nearest tree. Although several of them have heads of hair that look just alike, the mark of their name identifies them.\" (Pease 1934:378, Deliette 1721, \"ils marquent aussy des Lieux pour se rejoindre s\'ils sont obligez de faire plusrs. Routes, et en ce cas ceux qui arrivent Les premiers, prennent un peu de ce qu\'ils ont laissez s\'ils en ont besoin et Laissent leurs marques, en quoy ils ne se trompent Jamais ils se depeignent pour cela a l\'arbe Le plus proche, quoy que plusieurs ayent la Chevelure faite de meme, la marque de Leur nom les font connoistre,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. CUSTOMS: killing prisoners of war.  \"When he [prisoner of war] is condemned to die, it is always by fire. I have never seen any other kind of torment used by this nation. They plant a little tree in the earth, which they make him clasp, they tie his two wrists, and with torches of straw of firebrands they burn him, sometimes for six hours.\" (Pease 1934:385, Deliette 1721, \"Quand il est condamne a la mort c\'est toujours par le feu, Je n\'ay jamais vu d\'autres genres de suplices chez cette nation. On plante un petit Arbre dans la terre qu\'on luy fait embrasser, on luy lie les deux poignets Et avec des Torches de pailles out tisons ou le Brule qulquefois pendant six heurs,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 3. TECHNOLOGY:  \"I paint him, make his portrait on a tree, or on a war-club\" (Gravier ca.1700:253.10, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter); 4. CUSTOMS: identifying mark drawn on tree during warring/burning prisoner of war on a tree. Gabriel Godfroy relayed the story of Kaapia, in Miami, to Dunn, which included the description of some Miami men on their way to get revenge for an act of war, following a trail in pursuit of a Kickapoo enemy named Buck . \". . . after a while we saw a buck drawn on a tree. My companions said: \'Its useless. Buck is a real Kickapoo warrior. We\'ll never catch him.\' . . . \'We\'ll keep following him.\' They caught up with him and burned him while tied to a tree\" (Dunn 1909); 5. CUSTOMS: tree branches used to come out of water in creation story. \"They came from the \'Coming out Place\'. The first ones came from out of the water. \"Grab ahold of tree-limbs\" they told each other\" (Dunn 1909, from Gabriel Godfroy, in Miami); 6. TECHNOLOGY: small tree cut off and hatchet head placed into slit. When tree had grown around hatchet head sufficiently, the tree was cut and a hatchet with firmly held hatchet head was ready for use (Charlevoix 1682-1761:126, from Kellogg 1923:117); 7. TECHNOLOGY: fortifications around villages made with interwoven tree branches. \"The piles of which they [palidade fortifications] are composed, are interwoven with branches of trees, without any void space between\" (Charlevoix 1682-1761:128, from Kellogg 1923:118); 8. TECHNOLOGY: canoes made from single tree trunks. \"A Pirogue . . . This is a long sort of boat made of the trunk of a single tree. Canoes of bark are seldom made use of in these parts\" (Charlevoix 1683-1761:202, from Kellogg 1923:187); 9. CUSTOMS: the dead are wrapped in skins and hung from the tops of trees. \"Their custom is not to bury the dead, but to wrap them in skins, and to attach them by the head and feet to the tops of trees\" (Shea 1903:155, footnote to Membre\'s narrative, quoting F. Rale, also an explorer, from Kip\'s Jesuit Relations, p. 38); 10. CUSTOMS: Illinois hung their deceased, wrapped in skins, in the tops of trees. \"The Illinois did not inter their dead. The corpse, carefully wrapped in skins was attached by the head and feet to the upper part of trees\" (Tailhan 1864, footnote in Blair 1911:83);', NULL, NULL, '1. Algonquians believe that the soul of the deceased, while travelling in a beautiful country on its way to the country of the dead, crosses a fast river which can only be crossed by one slender tree-trunk as a bridge. \"They believe, furthermore, that as soon as the soul has left the body it enters this charming country, and that, after having traveled many days, it encounters on its route a very rapid river, over which there is only a slender tree-trunk by way of bridge, and that in passing over this it bends so much that the soul is in danger of being swept away by the flood waters. They assert that if unfortunately this mishap occurs, the soul will be drowned, but that all these perils are escaped when once the souls have reached the country of the dead\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:89-90);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1682', '1934', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(16, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Njo3NjE5OjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Sinew weed', NULL, NULL, '1. \"The bark is white and the plant grows about two feet high\" (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938);', '1. \"This grew here [Miami, OK]\" (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: \"The sinew weed was used to make thread. This grew here and peeling off the bark of the body of the weed could be separated into very fine threads which are strong and durable\".(Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1938', '1938', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:16', '2017-09-19 22:48:16')
(17, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MTcwOjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Moss', 'Bryophyta (Moss)', 'anseensi', NULL, '1. Occurs in wet, moist areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: used in orienteering when traveling cross-country, along with stream courses and size, and the sun. \"Their course in an unknown country is regulated by the moss upon the trees, by the general course of the streams and their size and by the sun\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:58); 2. TECHNOLOGY: mukoapineek, are very large roots of the \"pond lily\", and require much preparation. A hole is dug in the ground in which rocks are placed and heated with a fire on top of them. When the fire is done, dry moss is placed over the heated stones and the roots thrown in and covered with grass or moss, bark, water added and then earth covering the top. It is left for five days and then the roots are removed, cut into small pieces, dried on a small scaffold and used later. They are good for a year this way. When used, they are added to a batch of soup before the meat is done cooking. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64); 3. UNKNOWN: (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 4. UNKNOWN: \"anza\'nzi, moss\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3314); 5. UNKNOWN: \"miza\'nza\" \"moss growing on trees\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1284); 6. UNKNOWN: \"ququnruke, green moss\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from  Mongosa);', NULL, NULL, '1. Gravier (ca. 1700) listed this Miami-Illinois phrase: \"ansansigamiwi riviere, ou, maret plain de mousse\", meaning river or marsh full of moss (0.32?);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'anseensi- (it is dark green)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1825', '-1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(18, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxMjA3ODoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, '(sitakaana)', '1. A sunflower (Gatschet ca. 1895);', '1. \"Grows wild and in profusion in Indian Territory\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"sitakana, sunflower, grows wild and in profusion in Indian territory\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:2121);', NULL, '1. There are a number of sunflowers native to the Indian territory prairies, including the Ashy Sunflower, the Maximillian Sunflower and others. \'Sitakaana\' could be any one of these that were common in the past (Olds 2004, Email communication between Daryl Baldwin, Dustin Olds, and Mike Gonella, 7/15/04);', '1. This sunflower was mentioned by Gatschet without mention of its cultural significance. However, the animate \"a\" ending on this term indicates cultural importance during older, including precontact, times. The beginning of the word \"sit-\" is extremely rare in central Algonquian language and no other cognates in other languages have been found (Baldwin 2004, Email communication between Daryl Baldwin, Dustin Olds, and Mike Gonella, 7/15/04);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(19, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzozMjE3MToy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, 'Asteraceae (Sunflower)', '(oncaccou)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: yellow dye made from flower heads. \"To dye yellow they take an herb that they call Oncaccou from the name of the color that it gives, it resembles dandelions. They take the heads of this plant which are like a big button, they dry them in the sun, then they crush and boil them without any other ingredient. The dyeing is very beautiful. They go to seek this plant far from the Mississipi. It is in abundance in the river of the Illinois\" (Anonymous 1724:163B, \"Pour teindre en jaune on le fait d\'une herbe qu\'on appelle Oncaccou du nom de la Couleur qu\'elle donne elle reseemble a des pissanlis, On prend les Testes de cette herbe qui sont comme un gros bouton, on les fait secher qu soleil, puis on les pile et fait bouiller sans autre ingredien, la Teinture est fort belle, On va chercher cette herbe loin de Mississipi, il y en a abondament dans La Riviere de Illinois\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(20, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzoxNjUwNjoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'micousiouaki', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: root used for red dye. \"To dye red, there is on the prairie of the Tamarcoua [Tamarora] a plant that they name red Micousiouaki, they take the root, they dry it, then then pulverize it in the mortar and then boil it with three times as many sumac berries, the red is very beautiful\" (Anonymous 1724:163B, \"Pour teintre en Rouge, il y a a dans la prairie des Tamarcoua une herbe qu\'on nomme Micousiouaki Rouge, on prend la racine on la fait secher, puis on la pulverise dans le mortier et ensuite en la fais bouiller avec 3 fois autant de graine de Vinaigrier, le Rouge est fort beau\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(21, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo2MTkxOjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Lead wood', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: bark boiled and used on all types of wounds, to stop bloody flux 000?, and cure a cancer 000?. \"The bark of lead wood boiled for all sorts of wounds, I have seen a cancer cured, it sserves to stop the bloody flux, we must carry some of this wood to France\" (Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De l\'ecois de Bois de plomb bouilly pour toutes sortes de playes, j\'avay veu gueris un Cancer, il sert pour arreter le flux de sang, il faut emporter de ce bois en France\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(22, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MzM5ODoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Herb of a thousand leaves', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used to treat cuts. \"The herb of a thousand leaves for all sorts of cuts\" (Anonymous 1724:164B, \"De l\'herbe a mille feuilles pour toutes sorts de Coupures\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004; the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(23, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDY4ODoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Listre', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: leaves boiled and used to treat sore eyes. \"The leaves of Listre boiled for soreness of the eyes\" (Anonymous 1724:164B, \"De la feuilles de Listre bouillee pour les douleurs des yeux\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(24, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4MDgzNToy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Reed', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MEDICINAL: root boiled and used to draw out objects in wounds. \"For wounds and for to draw out that which is in the wound musket ballor other thing, it is necessary toboil the root of a certain reed which bears distaffs. I have seen the test of this remedy\" (Anonymous 1724:164B, \"Pour les playes et pour attirer ce qui on dans la playe boule de fusile ou autre chose, il faut faire bouiller de la racine d\'un certain Rozeau qui porte des quenouilles j\'ay veu leexperience de ce remede\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 2. MATERIAL: Shopekenauminkee is a game played with a hundred pieces of small reed or cane about a foot in length. The players take turns taking the bunch of reeds between their hands and letting them drop end-wise upon the bark board where they play, trying to drop them so that five pieces, corresponding to the head and limbs, fall together. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64); 3. TECHNOLOGY: they used a bundle of round reeds for kindling to start a fire, with two bits of wood for striking the flame, for cooking their meat (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:316-317, \"un d\'eux fut a 3. ou 4. arpents dans un fond ou le printemps ce n\'est qu\'une maniere de marais, et apporterent une botte de Roseaux ronds qui sont gros comme les doigts, tirerent de leur Crquois deux morceaux de Bois, qui leur sert de batte feu, Et en moins d\'un demy misere en eurent fait, ils allumerent une partie de leurs Roseaux, sur quoy ils mirent leur vande, qu\'ils tournoient de temps en temps avec leur arcs,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 4. (TECHNOLOGY): little reeds probably used in making some type of arrow shaft. \"atchihar8\" (Gravier ca.1700, translated by Masthay 2003:80, rel info 1);', NULL, NULL, '1.The \'ar8\' ending (-arwa, arwi, alwi) is usually seen with the names of types of arrows (e.g. ahtawaanhsalwi, \'pointed wooden arrow\') and also appears on some plant names that probably all have to do with arrow production (e.g. Gatschet\'s \'napahalwi\', ash tree, and Illinois/Peoria \'iihkalwi\', dogwood). Therefore, the word  \'atchihar8\' is a plural noun for some type of reed having to do with arrow production (McCafferty\'s explanation in an email communication between Costa and McCafferty, March 20, 2003, regarding Masthay\'s listing of this word);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'atchihar8 (little reeds, Grav)', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1700', '1825', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(25, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5NzozNTIyOjI=', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Fern', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: root of small fern boiled and resulting liquid used to treat bloody flux. \"The best and the most prompt remedy that I have seen for the bloody flux is the root of the fern which bears very small seeds, it is necessary to boil it over a small fire or to steep it until the water is red, and when it has diminished about a third, make the patient take a quarter of a litre on an empty stomach until a complete cure. One can take it in the evening to be cured sooner, three, four, or fives times at least will do the trick\" (Anonymous 1724:164B-165A, \"Le meilleur est le plus prompt Remede qui j\'ay veu pour le flux de sang, c\'est de la Racine de feugere qui porte de la graine, et de la plus petite, il fait ca faire bouiller a petit feu ou infuser jusqu\'a ce que l\'Eau soit rouge, et qu\'elle ay diminue environ de tierst, en faire prendre au malade un demy septier a jeun jusqu\'a parfaite guerison, on en peu prendre le fois pour etre plus on guery 3.4. ou cinq fois au plus en seront l\'affaire\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(26, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo4Nzc1NToy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Samelier or Ebeaupain', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: bark chewed or crushed to treat wounds. \"The bark of samelier or Ebeaupain chewed ro crushed for wounds\" (Anonymous 1724:165A, \"De l\'ecois de samelier ou Ebeaupain machee ou pilee pour les Playes\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(27, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo3MjgwMDoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'White creeper', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used to treat veneral diseases. \"The white creeper, for veneral diseases\" (Anonymous 1724:165A, \"De la Lianne Blanche pour les maux veneriens\" translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(28, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo5NTUyNToy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Ash hybrid', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: bark of ash used to treat sprains. \"For accidents or sparins, the bark of the ash hybrid, chewed and put on the inury\" (Anonymous 1724:165A, \"Pour les maux d\'avanture ou fouleure, de l\'ecoise de fresne Mestis, machee en mettre sur le mal\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(29, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MDg3MToy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Pea (Common and wild)', NULL, 'aleciimina', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"species of a berry, its name unknown to my informant\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3646-3647); 2. FOOD: \"lachaminic peas\" (Gatschet ca. 1895); 3. FOOD: \"aleciminiiki peas\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:151em);', NULL, NULL, '1. Dunn (ca. 1900:3647dw) lists the word [latci]miniki as the plural form of the word latcimina, meaning pea. This corresponds closely to Gatschet\'s (ca. 1895) term alatchimini for a species of berry, unknown to his informant; 2. Possibly an older word for a wild pea-like plant, although its contemporary meaning is the cultivated pea (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(30, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo0MzY2Njoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Green grass', 'Poaceae (Grass)', 'ihkipakahkatwi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. (MATERIAL): \"kipakaxkatwa, green grass\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1205); 2. UNKNOWN: \"ikipakaxki mitakatwi, green grass, weeds, stalks. The plural kipakaxkatwa refers to different species of grass and weeds\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1264, 1325);', NULL, NULL, '1. Gatschet (ca. 1895:77) lists the general Miami-Ilinois term for green grass as \"kipakaxkatwi\", indicating green grass, weeds and stalks, where the plural form \"kipakaxkatwa\" refers to different species of grass and weeds. He also lists a phrase \"kipakaxkatw malimawiki, or milamayuwi\" translated as \'the grasses are full of dew\'\" (p.1205); 2. Dunn (ca. 1900) lists the word Miami-Illinois term for green grass as \"ihkipakahkatwi\", translated as solely, green grass;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1895', '-1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(31, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5Nzo5NTQ4NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Aristolochia serpentaria L. (unconfirmed)', 'Virginia snake-root', 'Aristolochiaceae (Birthwort)', NULL, NULL, '1. Moist or dry upland woods in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used to cure snakebites. According to Kenton 1925, this species or Polygala senega could possibly be the one referred to by Marquette, in his 1674 letter in the Jesuit Relations (Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:340 footnote);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1674', '1674', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:17', '2017-09-19 22:48:17')
(32, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNTEzMDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ceanothus spp. (unconfirmed)', 'Redroot', 'Rhamnaceae (Buckthorn)', '(neehpikiciikaahkwi)', '1. A small bush, similar to the huckleberry, which grows on the prairies and has a short, thick, red root (Dunn ca. 1900);', '1. Ceanothus americanus, sometimes called New Jersey tea, or redroot, or C. herbaceus, called Prairie redroot were probably both indicated by \'neehpikiccikaahkwi\', both growing in prairies through Indiana and Oklahoma (Author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: thick red root made into tea for curing \"any disease\" (Finley, in Dunn ca. 1900); 2. CUSTOMS: A traditional story recounts some Peorias that wanted to scare off a white family looking for a house to lease. \"Before the time for their [the white family] return he gathered up turkey feathers and made a large head-dress, smeared his face with red paint from redroot and some yellow clay, dressed himself in some old beaded clothing and, armed with a huge tomahawk, waited for them by the side of the road, concealed in some bushes. When they were even with him he sprang to the road with a wild yell, brandishing his tomahawk. The family left as fast as their horses would travel and never returned and Uncle John never tired of laughing over his \"Wild Indian Stunt.\"(Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938, this reference may not refer to the same \"redroot\" as entry #1);', NULL, NULL, '1. A tea was made from the leaves during the American Revolution. No caffeine is found in the leaves, but the root was once used as an expectorant and astringent, and the root bark has been found to have many blood-clotting properties. (Steyermark 1963);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1938', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(33, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo5OTAzNToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Chamaelirium luteum A. Gray (unconfirmed)', 'Devil\'s bit', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', '(waawiyaciipihki) (also for Colic root)', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist woods and bogs in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used as an antidote to snakebite venom. \"use wahe\'ahchippykick either by holding a piece of the root in the mouth or by making a tea and holding the tea in the mouth\" (Bussard ca. 1960, from Bundy); 2. MEDICINAL: medicinal plant used as an antidote to snakebite venom. \"asanitcipki, colic root or devils bit, medicinal plant said to kill poison\", also \"wawiatcipki\", or waawiyaaciipihki\" (Dunn ca. 1900:1268-9dw);', NULL, NULL, '1. These entries may also refer to \'eehseniciipihki\', or Aletris farinosa (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1960', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(34, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTA2OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Desmanthus illinoensis (unconfirmed)', 'Snakebite Cure', 'Mimosaceae (Mimosa)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: root used to cure rattlesnake bite. \"Rattlesnakes abound among them, not a summer passes but some one is bitten, this troubles them but little since they have an admirable root, which, as soon as it is applied to the wound, softens the swelling so that by the next day one is cured. This root is found in the prairies and is shaped like an onion. The stem grows two feet high, the leaves are narrow and somewhat resemble those of the sumac. It forms large buds in which the seed is lodged. I have made a point of hunting for it in this country, but have never been able to find any. I have been told that they had still another kind, but I have not become acquainted with it.\" (Deliette 1721, Pease 1934:372, \"Il y a une grande quantite de serpens a sonnette chez eux, il ne se passe point d\'annee qu\'il n\'y aye quelqu\'un de pique de quoy ils s\'embarassent tres peu parce qu\'ils ont d\'une Racine admirable, sitot qu\'on en a mis sur la playe elle fait amolir L\'enflure et le Lendemain on est guery, cette Racine se trouve dans Les prairies et est faitte comme un oignon, Le tige vient de deux pieds de deux pieds de haut, La feuille fort etroitte qui aproche celle des Vinaigriers, Il se forme de gros Boutons dans quoy est la raine, je me suis attachez a en chercher dans ce pays mais je n\'en ay jamais pu trouver, on ma dit qu\'il y en avoit encore d\'une autre sorte, mais je ne la connois point,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. MEDICINAL: root used as antidote to snake bites. The root of this plant must first be chewed and then placed on the snake bite. \"I also took time to look for a medicinal plant which a savage, who knows its secret, showed to Father Alloues with many Ceremonies. Its root is employed to Counteract snake-bites, God having been pleased to give this antidote Against a poison which is very common in these countries. It is very pungent, and tastes like powder when crushed with the teeth, it must be masticated and place upon the bite inflicted by the snake. The reptile has so great a horror of it that it even flees from a person who has rubbed himself with it. The plant bears serveral stalks, a foot high, with rather long leaves, and a white flower, which greatly resembles The wallflower\" (Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:101, \"Je pris aussi le temps de reconnoistre un simple qu\'un sauvage qui en scait le secret a enseigne au P. Alloues auec beaucoup de Ceremonies, Sa racine sert Contre la morsure des serpent, Dieu ayant voulu donner ce remede Contre un venin qui est tres frequent en ces pays: Elles est fort chaude et elle a un goust de poudrre quand on l\'escrase sou sous la dent, il faut la mascher et la mettre sur la piquure du serpent, qui en a une si grande horreur, qu\'il s\'enfuit mesme de Celuy qui s\'en est frotte, elle produit plusieures tiges hautes d\'un pied, dont la feuille est un peu longue et la fleur blanche et beaucoup semblable a La giroflee,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites); 3. MEDICINAL: antidote to snake bites. \" . . .I had the curiosity to taste the mineral water of a river near it [a Miami/Maskouten/Kickapoo village], and found a simple [plant] of a wonderful virtue against the venom of the serpents. A savage who knew it, had shown it to Father Allouez, who had often occasion to try its virtues, God having been pleased to provide that country with that wonderful antidote against the serpents, who are very dangerous in those parts. The root of the simple is very hot, and tastes like gunpowder, they chew it, and apply it to the part of the body stung by the serpents;', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1673', '1698', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(35, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo2MzgyNToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Fomitopsis pinicola (Fr.) Kar. (unconfirmed)', 'Red-belted polypore', 'Basiodiomycetes (Mushrooms)', '(lenoonkwia) (prickly pear cactus also)', '1. A mushroom with leathery polypores, with colors in concentric circles, i.e. man\'s face, ilanongwia (Dunn ca. 1900: Indiana State Library L47, Note #35); 2. Fomitopsis spp. is a genus of fungi that grow on trees and have a flat bottom and often semi-conical top portion that could resemble a man\'s nose, and together with the tree could resemble a man\'s face. Dr. Nicholas Money (Miami University) says this is a good guess for this Miami plant, since it is very common in the Midwest and the description fits (author\'s conversation with Dr. Money, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"ilanongwia, fungus with markings, growing laterally on logs or trees (i-la:no\'ngia) literally mans face\" (Dunn ca. 1900:Indiana State Library L47, Note #35);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1900', '-1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(36, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1NjE1Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Impatiens capensis L. (unconfirmed)', 'Jewelweed', NULL, 'mic8kinamagane?', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: plant used to cure inflammation caused by another plant [poison ivy, poison sumac]. \"plant which cures this inflammation/swelling[from having touched some bad plant]. Also marking the swelling that comes from scratching\" (Gravier ca.1700:292.90, \"herbe qui guerit cette enflure. Item marque l\'enflure qui vient pour gratter,\" translation from French to English by Masthay 000);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1700', '1700', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(37, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxNzk2OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Origanum vulgare L. (unconfirmed)', 'Wild marjoram, oregano', 'Lamiaceae (Mint)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: roots boiled for all types of wounds. \"The root of onis [wild marjoram?] [Anonymous\' brackets] boiled for all sorts of wounds\" (Anonymous 1724:164A,\"De la Racine d\'Onis [onitide?] bouilly pour toutes sortes de playes\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. onis; 2. onitide;', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(38, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoyNDExNDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Polygala senega L. (unconfirmed)', 'Snakeroot', 'Polygalaceae (Milkwort)', NULL, '1. Polygala senega has dense racemes with white flowers (Gleason & Cronquist 1991);', '1. Occurs in rocky soils, widely distributed across eastern U.S. west to AR (Gleason & Cronquist 1991); 2. Occurs in rocky, shaded soils throughout IN (Coulter 1899)--not found within western Miami lands;', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used to cure snakebites. According to Kenton 1925, this species or Aristolochia serpentaria could possibly be the one referred to by Marquette, in his 1674 letter in the Jesuit Relations (Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:340 footnote);', NULL, NULL, '1. Dried roots contain saponins which irritate the stomach and intestines and increase bronchial secretions. In large doses (1 gm) acts as an emetic and cathartic, and in smaller doses it is an expectorant, sialagogic 000?, diaphoretic, diuretic, and emmenagogic ?000. Chiefly used as an expectorant (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly Co.); 2. Probably not either of these species, since they are out of the range of both eastern and western Miami lands (author\'s notes); 3. MEDICINAL: used medicinally by numerous tribes, from the Cherokee to the Ojibway, Cree, and Woodlands, mostly for its cathartic and expectorant properties--roots commonly chewed for sore throats (Moerman 1998);', 'TRUE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1674', '1674', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(39, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo5MDUzMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Prenanthes racemosa Michx. (unconfirmed)', 'Rattlesnake-root', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', '(8iskapi≈°ia)', '1. \"the bulb is white and sticks entirely out of the ground. The stem is one-foot high, with four-sided leaves and a little red button on the head\" (LeBoullenger ca.1725:folio 151);', '1. Occurs in streambanks, moist meadows and prairies (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: \"8icapisia\", \"root to protect oneself from the bites of the snake which makes it [the snake] flee\" (LeBoullenger ca.1725:folio 151,  \"racine pour se garantir de la moisure des serpens et qui les fait fuire. L\'oignon est blanc et sort hors de terre. La tige a un pied de haut. Les feuilles 4 cotes et un petit bouton rouge a la teste\", translation from French to English by Costa, not sure if Prenanthes racemosa designation is by McCafferty 2003, or previously assigned by another);', NULL, NULL, '1. This description closely fits other ethnographic entries of colic-root, Aletris farinosa, except the portion about the little red button on the head--this portion does not fit with Aletris farinosa as taxonomists describe it today. McCafferty (unpublished?) cites Masthay (2002:237) interpretation of this entry of LeBoullenger (ca.1725:folio 151) to describe Prenanthes racemosa, although the description also does not quite fit (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1725', '1725', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(40, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoyMDY3OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Psoralea esculenta Pursh. (unconfirmed)', 'Indian turnip', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', NULL, NULL, '1. Psoralidium (Psoralea) tenuiflorum Rydb. occurs in dry prairies in eastern Miami lands. Psoralidium lanceolatum Rydb. occurs on dry, sandy soil in western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: tubers boiled in water by a slow fire, and then eaten. :\"That country [lands around Lake Michigan] also produces potatoes, some are as large as an egg, others have the size of one\'s fist, or a little more. They boil these in water by a slow fire during twenty-four hours, when they are thoroughly cooked, you will find in them an excellent flavor, much resembling that of prunes\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:117, Perrot\'s description may refer to this plant, although other species are possible, including Apios americana or Helianthus tuberosa);', NULL, NULL, '1. mentioned (Coues 1898 000?)--possibly utilized by Sioux;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1680', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
