(45, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo4NDU0Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Plant was about 2 feet high (Interview with Jacob Weisenberger, 2004; speaking of his father\'s plant use);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: plant gathered, hung upside down to dry, rolled into balls and chewed to relieve stomach ailments (Interview with Jacob Weisenberger, 2004, speaking of his father\'s plant use);', '1. Plant gathered after first hard frost (Interview with Jacob Weisenberger, 2004, speaking of his father\'s plant use);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '2004', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(46, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1NzgwNjoy', 2, 0, 1, NULL, 'Aquatic grass', 'Poaceae', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: aquatic grass used during cooking of macopines--\"then they go in quest of a large quantity of grass which they get at the bottom of the water and which they spread as well as they can over these rocks [hot, in a pit] to the thickness of about a foot, after which they throw on many buckets of water, and then as fast as they can each cabin puts its roots in its own place, covering them with dry grass and bark and finally earth.\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:346, \"apres quoy elles Vont chercher quantite d\'herbes qui sont au fond de l\'eau, qu\'elles estendent le mieux qu\'elles peuvent sur ces Rochers de l\'epaisseur d\'environ un pied, apres quoy elles jettent quantite de seaux d\'eau et au plus Viste chaque Cabanes met ses Racines en un Endroit les couvrent d\'herbes seches et des Ecorces par dessus et ensuite de la terre,\" translation from French to English by Pease);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1721', '1721', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(47, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODozNzAzOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Acer negundo L.', 'Box elder', 'Aceraceae (Maple)', '(≈°ii≈°iikweehkihsi)', NULL, '1. Occurs on moist, especially alluvial soils throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason & Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: a medicine was made from some part of this tree: \"A decoction was made from it by these [Miami] Indians\"  (Gatschet ca. 1895:2101); 2. MEDICINAL: medicinal plant, not used by Lamoine or others he knew, but talked about. \"Used in the case of wounds, or something like that.\" Probably used in the last quarter of the 19th century (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 3. MEDICINAL: root and bark used. \"The root and bark of elder for a person falling in his limbs, it is necessary to boil it and to put it in a little bit of soup, drinking about a pint\" (Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De la racine et Ecois de Sureau pour une personae perelus de ses members, il faut la faire bouiller et y mettre un peu de potage, en boire environ chopine\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, '1. Gatschet noted that the Indians said box elder makes poor sugar (Gatschet ca. 1895:1834); 2. Vezina, Robert (pers. Comm. 4/2002). \"assinibwa (cut off in data transfer);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1989', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(48, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo3NTgxMToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Acer saccharinum L.', 'Soft maple tree', 'Aceraceae (Maple)', '(wiikapaahkwaahkani≈°a)', '1. \"Its bark and leaves are darker than those of the sugar maple.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', '1. moist or wet soil, especially along riverbanks (Gleason & Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: leaves thrown into wild potato batch to make them turn black (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65); 2. FOOD: sugar made from the soft maple, or softwood maple (Gatschet ca. 1895); 3. UNKNOWN: word for soft maple bark (Gatschet ca. 1895); 4. FOOD: sap gathered for making syrup. Maple candy suckers were also made: \". . . my uncle John lived in Huntington [Indiana]. He would tap those trees and so then we had a long sled . . .and we had a big black kettle. They\'d cook that down and whenit got down so far, why we\'d take sticks and we\'d put it in there you known and whirl it and keep a little on there. Then we\'d take it out when it would get cold or put it in the snow, because sometimes there would be snow [done during the Fall]. And then we\'d put it back. Sometimes we\'d get a big sucker with that. That was fun. We liked that\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 5. FOOD: tree sap, called \'ahsenaamisaapowi\' was made into maple syrup (Hockett 1938); 6. FOOD: used to make sugar. \"These Indians prefer hard maple to soft maple sugar and manufacture it themselves, they also say that box elder makes poor sugar\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1834); 7. UNKNOWN: sugar tree (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer, 2nd Wea Primer); 8. UNKNOWN: maple tree (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 9. FOOD: trees tapped for obtaining \"sugar water\" which was used to make maple syrup (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 10. MEDICINAL: uncooked \"sugar water\" tapped from sugar maples used for cuts, scratches and inflammation. \"Sugar water\" used in combination with epsom salts and applied as a poultice, which was tied to the area with a bandage and left on overnight, drawing out the \'poison\' or slivers. This process was not used on animals. (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1825', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(49, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODoxOTMxNToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Acer saccharum L.', 'Sugar maple tree', 'Aceraceae (Maple)', 'ahsenaami≈°i', NULL, '1. Rich to dry woods and uplands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: tree sap, called \'ahsenaamisaapowi\' was made into maple syrup (Hockett 1938); 2. FOOD: used to make sugar. \"These Indians prefer hard maple to soft maple sugar and manufacture it themselves, they also say that box elder makes poor sugar\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1834); 3. UNKNOWN: sugar tree (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer, 2nd Wea Primer); 4. UNKNOWN: maple tree (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 5. FOOD: trees tapped for obtaining \"sugar water\" which was used to make maple syrup (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 6. MEDICINAL: uncooked \"sugar water\" tapped from sugar maples used for cuts, scratches and inflammation. \"Sugar water\" used in combination with epsom salts and applied as a poultice, which was tied to the area with a bandage and left on overnight, drawing out the \'poison\' or slivers. This process was not used on animals. (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 7. FOOD: sap gathered for making syrup. Maple candy suckers were also made: \". . . my uncle John lived in Huntington [Indiana]. He would tap those trees and so then we had a long sled . . .and we had a big black kettle. They\'d cook that down and whenit got down so far, why we\'d take sticks and we\'d put it in there you known and whirl it and keep a little on there. Then we\'d take it out when it would get cold or put it in the snow, because sometimes there would be snow [done during the Fall]. And then we\'d put it back. Sometimes we\'d get a big sucker with that. That was fun. We liked that\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 8. FOOD: sugar camps were inhabited in the spring (Draper 1815-1891(6):61);', NULL, NULL, '1. McPherson wrote \"It was a festive time for the Miami Indians when they returned from their winter hunting grounds with furs and maple syrup and sugar. Not only did they relish this natural sweet but it was also an important item of barter for them. Hoosier pioneers quickly learned from the Indians how to tap the sugar maple (Acer saccharum) and make the delicious \"tree molasses.\" In 1900, Indiana ranked third in the nation for production of maple syrup\" (1977:141-142, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 2. Two other representations of Miami-Illinois terms for the sugar maple tree are \"fanumejuqe\"  (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer,from  Mongosa, and \"senamizahkwa\" (Hockett 1983:177);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'ahsenaamisiaahkwi (rel. info. 2)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1815', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(50, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo2MDAzNjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Achillea millefolium L.', 'Yarrow', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: tea made from root or flowers for \"chills and fevers\", poultices made for cuts (Interviews with Miami elders, Rafert 1992:45); 2. MEDICINAL: leaves washed, mashed and placed in cuts/wounds (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004, speaking about her grandmother (Sophia G. LaFalier) and mother-in-law (Rebecca M. Stitt Walker));', NULL, NULL, '1. Eugene Brown remembers being with a Potawatomi medicine man, John Moore, who showed him the yarrow plant [he was not totally sure, but showing him yarrow jogged this memory] and said if you are having trouble with bad dreams/evil spirits, you hang this plant upside down around the outside of the house to keep them away (Interview with Eugene Brown, 2004b);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1992', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(51, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1ODc0NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Acorus calamus L.', 'Calamus root or Sweetflag', 'Araceae (Arum)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in swamps and shallow waters throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. \"Grows in the marshes\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: root chewed to treat sore throat and cough. Beth recalls her mother treating her cough and sore throat recently, with calamus root, which she chewed and the cough got better. \"The root looked just like a chicken foot, all scaly, and yellow. Mom made us chew it or made tea with sugar\" (Interview with Beth Devers, 2003, speaking of her mother, Mildred Walker); 2. MEDICINAL: root chewed on or made into tea to treat pneumonia and chest ailments (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 3. MEDICINAL: root chewed for coughs, \"My dad made me eat the root and I didn\'t like it\" (Interview with Phyllis Miley, 2003); 4. MEDICINAL: leaves pulverized and used to wrap a wound (Interviews with Miami elders 1977-1992, Rafert 1992:45);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1977', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(52, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1ODU1Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Aesculus glabra Willd.', 'Buckeye tree', 'Hippocastanaceae (Horse Chestnut)', 'mihsihkii≈°ikomi≈°i', NULL, '1. Occurs on moist, well-drained, alluvial and often calcareous soils (limestone or dolomite) in eastern and western Miami lands; 2. Occurs on rich, moist soil throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: \"There are many roots and weeds used by them for emetics, the most common of which is the root of the Buckeye.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:48); 2. UNKNOWN: \"muskishiku=mizhi sipiwi\" means \"buckeye creek\" of the Cherokee Nation, \"mu\'s\'=ki\'shi=mkumizhi tawani\" means \"buckeye tree, a tree frequently found in Kansas but not occuring in the eastern parts of the ind. Terr.  (Gatschet ca. 1895:1327, 1286); 3. UNKNOWN: \"miskicekwomindji, buckeye tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 4. MEDICINAL/MATERIAL: necklace, bracelet and rings made with seeds, carried to keep rheumatism away (Interview with Dani Tippman, Mary (Strack) Swenda and Mary Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. Ohio buckeye, A. glabra, is the most common or the only  buckeye species in both the Western Miami territory. Both Yellow, A. flava, and Ohio buckeyes are present in Eastern Miami terroritory, with the Ohio buckeye still being the most prevalent. Therefore, the Miami word for \'buckeye\' probably refers to both species but came to commonly mean the Ohio buckeye, in more recent times, including those of Dunn. (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1825', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(53, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo0OTQ1NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Aletris farinosa L.', 'White olic-root', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', 'waawiyaciipihki', '1. \"This root is is found in the prairies and is shaped like an onion. The stem grows two feet high; the leaves are very narrow and somewhat resemble those of the sumac. It forms large buds in which the seed is lodged.\" (Pease 1934:372, Deliette 1721); 2. \"The plant bears several stalks, a foot high, with rather long leaves; and a white flower, which greatly resembles the wall-flower.\" (Thwaites 1966:101, Marquette 1673);', '1. Occurs in open woods and barrens throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. \"This root is found in the prairies . . . \"  (Pease 1934:372, Deliette 1721);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: medicinal plant used as an antidote to poison. \"asanitcipki, colic root or devils bit, medicinal plant said to kill poison\", also \"wawiatcipki\", or waawiyaaciipihki  Dunn ca. 1900:1269dw & 1268dw); 2. MEDICINAL: root used as medicine. \"use wahe\'ahchippykick either by holding a piece of the root in the mouth or by making a tea and holding the tea in the mouth\" (Bussard ca. 1960, from Ross Bundy);', NULL, NULL, '1. Entries cited from Dunn and Deliette 1721 are most likely describing colic-root, although they may also be referring to Devil\'s bit, Chamaelirium lutem (author\'s note); 2. Entries from Marquette (1673) may be referring to a different plant altogether, as seen in the discrepancies between descriptions, Kenton\'s (1925) edited version of the same passage has a footnote noting that although the plant cannot be identified by the description given, the two plants Aristolochia serpentaria and Polygala senega have been known for their treatment of venonous snake bites; 3. Dried rhizomes of roots taken in small doses (0.6-4.0 gm) have medicinal cathartic and emetic properties (Coulter 1932:10, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 4. Colic-root was used medicinally by the Catawba Indians of North and South Carolina (Coulter 1932); 5. Wild yam, Dioscorea villosa L. is also sometimes called coli-root but not commonly; 6. Whtie colic-root has been used medicinally by the Cherokee, Catawba, and Micmac cultures (Native American Plant Database--Univ. of Mich., 2006);', 'FALSE', 'ahseniciipihki (Dunn, lit. stone root)', NULL, 'round root', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1960', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(54, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo4Nzg4OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Allium cepa L.', 'Cultivated onion', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: modern traditional food/crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1895', '1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(55, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5ODo1Mzk4MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Allium sp. L.', 'Garlic', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', NULL, '1. May refer to A. sativum, cultivated garlic, or A. vineale or A. canadense, wild garlic (Small 190, Coulter 1899, Steyermark 1963, Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', '1. A. sativum L. is a cultivated species native of western Asia, occuring in cultivated areas and rarely as an escape throughout eastern and western Miami lands. A. vineale L. (field garlic or scallions) is a native of Europe and found in lawns and fields as a weed throughout eastern (Gleason and Cronquist) and western Miami lands (Steyermark 1963?). A. canadense L. (bulb ovoid-conic?) is a native garlic ocurring in open woods and prairies throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: 000  (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 2. (FOOD): \"luqenfefuke, garlic\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from  Mongosa), from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'luqenfefuke', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '-1835', '-1837', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:18', '2017-09-19 22:48:18')
(56, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4NjE3Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Allium stellatum or A. cernuum.', 'Wild onion, Nodding onion, Prairie Onion', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', 'wiinhsihsia', '1. \". . . the root is like a leek, and the plant which grows from it resembles the salsify. This onion, I declare, is so exceedingly acrid that if one tries to swallow it, it would all at once wither the tongue, the throat, and the inside of the mouth; I do not know, however, whether it would have the same injurious effect on the inside of the body . . .\" (Dunn 1919, from Perrot);', '1. Occurs in various habitats, prairies, open, dry or rich wood (Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. \"The tribes of the prairies also find in certain places lands that are fertile, and kept moist by the streams that water them, whereon grow onions of the size of ones thumb\" (Dunn 1919, from Perrot);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '5. FOOD: Mable Olds (Leonard) picked poke and wild onions for cooking (Interview with Peggy McCord, 2004); 6. FOOD: gathered and eaten as greens rather than for the bulbs. Gathered this year. (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004); 7. FOOD: corms gathered and used (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 8. UNKNOWN:  (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 9. FOOD: Barbara Mullin\'s mother, Julia Lankford picked wild onions every spring for a wild onion and egg meal, consisting of wild onions, eggs, bacon grease and salt. Barbara still cooks this, using green onions for wild ones (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki,  2(3):14, 1999); 10. FOOD: \"I pick, clean, and peel an onion\" (Gravier ca.1700:253.15, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter); 10. FOOD: usually boiled then eaten. \"The tribes of the prairies also find in certain places lands that are fertile, and kept moist by the streams that water them, whereon grow onions of the size of one\'s thumb. The root is like a leek, and the plant which grows from it resembles the salsify. This onion, I say, is so exceedingly acrid that, if one tried to swallow it, it would all at once wither the tongue, the throat, and the inside of the mouth, I do not know, however, whether it would have the same injurious effect on the inside of the body. But this difficulty hardly ever occurs, for as soon as one takes it into the mouth he spits it out, and one imagines that it is a certain wild garlic, which is quite common in the same places, and has also an insupportable acridness. When the savages lay in a store of these onions, with which the ground is covered, they first build on oven, upon which they place the onions, covering them with a thick layer of grass, and by means of the heat which the fire communicates to them the acrid quality leaves them, nor are they damaged by the flames, and after they have been dried in the sun they become an excellent article of food. Their abundance, however, counts for nothing, although the agreeable taste which one finds in them often induces him to satisfy his appetite with them, for nothing in the world is more indigestible and mo??;', NULL, NULL, '1. Allium stellatum and A. cernuum are the likely species referred to by this Miami word. A. stellatum is listed in Coulter (1899) as Prairie wild onion, in Steyermark as Wild Onion, and in Gleason and Cronquist (1991) without common name.  A. cernuum is listed as Nodding Wild Onion in Coulter, Steyermark, and Gleason and Cronquist, and listed in Small (1903) without a common name. It appears that the exact common name often varies with the flora author, yet most consider both these species, commonly, as some type of \'wild onion\' (author\'s note); 2. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993); 3. Due to lead, cadmium and zinc contamination in the Tar Creek Superfund Site\'s watershed, around Miami, Oklahoma and the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma\'s headquarters, Miami and other local tribal members worry that traditional gathering of food, medicine and CUSTOMS items may be contaminated. Fish, wild blackberries, sassafras, pokeweed, basket-making supplies and wild onions could have high concentrations of lead, as do the waters of nearby lakes, and it is not always successful keeping tribal members out of these areas. The Seneca-Cayuga\'s berry dance could not be held, if all the wild blackberries and strawberries in the area are found to be contaminated (Tulsa World 7/13/2003); 4. The city name Chicago, originates from the Miami-Illinois word sikaakwa, meaning striped skunk. Sikaakwa is also the Miami-Illinois word for Allium tricoccum (McCafferty 2003) or other common, similar Allium species (author\'s note). As McCafferty states, Chicago \"is a perfect example of this very practical, fundamental kind of botanically oriented place name. It was a sign indicating that somewhere in the immediate local watershed one could find a signficant patchof wild leeks,\" or wild onions (McCafferty 2003:1-3); 5. The Miami term \"cikakwa\" was formerly used for the wild onion by the Miamis and other Algonquians. Now the word is only used for \'skunk\' (Dunn ca. 1900); 6. Another reference to an \"onion\" which probably is not an Allium species: \"They also store up onions, as big as Jerusalem artichokes, which they find in the prairies, and which I find better than all the other roots. They are sugary and pleasing to the palate. They are cooked like macopines\" (Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721, \"Elles amassent aussi des oignons gros comme des Topiniamboures, qu\'elles trouvent dans les prairies que je trouve meilleures que toutes les autres Racines, ils sont sucre et font plaisir a manger on les fait cuire comme les Macopines,\" translation from French to English by Pease) [author\'s note: this may or may not be an Allium species]; 7. . Lora Siders recalled the legend that one of the greatest Miami cities was on the shores of the big lake near the onion patch [this was presumably Chicago, named after the word meaning \'onion patch\' or \'stinking place\'], where the son of the Great Spirit walked with the Miami on sands by the big lake at the onion patch. She believed this to have been confirmed when archaeologists found a ancient city, at New Lennox (near Chicago) with remains of two skeletons identified as Miami (Interview with Lora Siders, Baldwin  1997);', 'FALSE', '?ikaakwa, mihkweeleeyakwi', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(57, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo3MjAzOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Alnus spp. Miller', 'Alder', 'Betulaceae (Birch)', '(neehpiaakimi≈°a)', NULL, '1. Associated with moist to wet soils and waterways (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"nepiaki, nepiakiminja, aulne arbre\" alder tree. Also, \"nepiaca, nepssa aulne, arbrissaux\", alder, shrubbery (Gravier ca. 1700:0337.000?);', NULL, NULL, '1. An undetermined source listed \"kilu..sah\" for \'alders\', but this probably refers to elderberry bushes (see Elderberry for \"kilu. .sah\" cognates) (Language database, 2004);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'nepiaki (Gr)', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1700', '-1700', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
