(59, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo5MDQ4NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ampelopsis cordata', 'Raccoon grapes', 'Vitaceae (Grape)', '(mihsipakimini)', '1. A vine with grape-like leaves that is often mistaken for true grapes, Vitis spp., which has berries that turn from green to shades or orange, rose, purple and finally turquoise, and is thus very ornamental. It is also a high climbing vine, growing up and covering the tops of the tallest trees in undisturbed forests (Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: 000? (Gatschet ca. 1895:1780 & 816); 2. UNKNOWN: mihsipakimi (Dunn ca.1900, rel info);', NULL, NULL, '1. The word \'mishsipakimini\' literally means \'leaf berries\', and Finely believed it meant \'coon grapes\' (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. \'Leaf berries\' could indicate that this plant has the lleaves similar in morpohology to the true grape vine, while \"sunshine bush\" may indicate its habit, as a high climbing vine, even to the tops of the tallest trees in undisturbed forest (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'leaf berries (Gat)', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1895', '-1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(60, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo5NzkyOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Andropogon gerardii L.', 'Big bluestem grass', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in moist or dry open places and prairies throughout the eastern portion of eastern Miami lands, (eastern Indiana and most of Illinois) where tallgrass prairie is found, and throughout western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Fibers used by Ohio cave and rock-shelter dwellers for coarsely woven items like rope and moccasins. Commonly used without preliminary treatment (Whitford 1941);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(61, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTozMjU2MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Anthoxanthum odoratum L.', 'Sweet vernal grass', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in lawns, meadows, roadsides and disturbed areas. Introduced from Europe (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: Joe V. Olds mentioned a place on the Geboe property where \"sweetgrass\" once, but no longer grows (Interview with Peggy McCord, 2004);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-2004', '-2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(62, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo2MjIwNzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Apios americana Medikus. (A. tuberosa)', 'Ground nut, bean/cherry, hog peanut/Indian potatoes', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', '(eepiihkanita)', '1. The tubers were called \"rosaries\" by the early Candians, because they resembled beads (Jesuit Relations, Vol. 6, p. 273); 2. Miami name, a-pi-ka\'-ni\'ta is similar to a-pi-ka\'-na-ki, which is their name for \"peace beads.\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Dunn 1919); 3. A small bush plant, about the size of a bean plant (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989);', '1. Occurs in moist woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: ground cherry eaten (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:97); 2. (FOOD): apikanita (Dunn ca. 1909);', NULL, NULL, '1. \"Of course, the ground cherry, which is almost extinct now around here [was eaten]. . .  and they would still use it, if they could find it. Modern day cultivation and the weed control has got rid of the ground cherry.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 2. William Wells, a parentless child captured with two other children by the Miami, was given the Miami name eepiihkanita. After he grew up he was given his freedom (Baldwin, pers. comm. 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. apikanita (Dunn); 2. apihka(a)na-peace beads/wampum;', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1909', '1989', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(63, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo2MDg3OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Apocynum cannabinum L.', 'Dogbane or Indian hemp', 'Apocynaceae (Dogbane)', 'ahsapa', NULL, '1. La Salle was one of the first to note the name of a tributary to the upper portion of Illinois River, called \'masaana [rope] siipiiwi\', which is the present day Kankakee River, so named for the surrounding land (present day Mazon, McCafferty 2004, pers. Comm.) where he noted a \'great quantity\' of hemp growing (Margry 1974:174, reprint 2, La Salle, between 1680-1693); 2. Occurs in open places throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: fiber plant for fishnets, \"a rush used for weaving\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. TECHNOLOGY: for making thread (Kickapoo, Dunn ca. 1900:2160dw); 3. MATERIAL: game of ball with rackets of Algonquian and Iroquoian tribes of the Atlantic seaboard and region of the Great Lakes, much like Lacrosse--played with a single racket which was curved at the end and netted [possibly dogbane, basswood, nettles, or another strong fiber\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:93); 4. (TECHNOLOGY/MATERIAL): \"I have observed that Hemp grows naturally in that Country, and that they make Tarr and Pitch toward the Sea-Coast\" (Thwaites 1903:212, Hennepin 1698); 5. TECHNOLOGY: cordage for fishing nets made from nettles and wild hemp. The women gather, spin and twist lengths of cordage on their bare thighs. The cords used to draw these nets are made of the bark of basswood or leather. With these nets many fish and beaver are captured. They also fish with still lines [possibly of the same cordage material] (Raudot 1904:Letter 41, secondary source for Deliette 1721); 6. MATERIAL: name for Lacrosse is \'asahpa tawaani\' meaning \'net stick\', where the word for net is the same as the word for dogbane, since the net was made from dogbane or similar fiberous material (Interview with George Strack, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/1/04); 7. MATERIAL: there are three Miami items made of \'hemp\', possibly dogbane or nettles, including a sack, medicine pouch and necklace cordage, all housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, in Washington D.C. (see attachment, NMAI items); 8. (MATERIAL/TECHNOLOGY): there are 2 items that are possibly made with plant fibers, which could include dogbane, nettles or basswood, among others, at the Cranbrook Institute in Michigan (see attachment, Cranbrook items);', NULL, '1. Imlay listed it as present in North America in 1792 (Imlay 1792);', '1. Used for cordage in contemporary Miami community: 4-5 stalks used to make about 1.5 feet of cordage, made into nets for weir, fishnet--cordage made into a net by wrapping cordage pieces around an end piece of cordage, so that the two ends hand down next to each other, and then tying two of those at regular intervals with a square knot, forming diamond-shaped openings (Woodland Village at Mihsiihkanaakwa Pow Wow 2003); 2. A plant called \'sinew weed\' was used to make thread. \"It grew here [northeastern Oklahoma] and after peeling the bark the body of the weed could be separated into very fine threads which are very strong and durable. The bark is white and the plant grows about two feet high.\" (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 3. Both Apocynum androsaemifolium, dogbane, and A. cannabinum, Indian hemp, were probably used indiscrimminately for fibers. Pieces of fabric attributed to the Hopewell and Adena culture of Ohio were made using Apocynum fibers and a fish net was made by the Nanticoke. Older specimens have less processed fibers, whereas more recent Indian material is well broken down with fine fibers for thread or cordage (Whitford 1941); 4. Dried rhizome and roots, in doses of 0.3-1.2 gm may be used similarly to digitalis, in weakness of heart and artery strength. Dangers in its use are its irritation to the gastrointestinal tract and potential of cumulative action (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly &Co.); 5. Indian hemp grew abundantly in the Miami-Illinois country: \"There are meadows ten or twenty leagues broad, encompass\'d with fine forests, behind which are other meadows, in which grass grows six foot high. Hemp grows naturally in all that country\" (Joliet 1674:187, from Thwaites); 6. Indian hemp grew abundantly in the Miami-Illinois country: \"There is the best hemp in that country I have seen any where, though it grows naturally without any culture\" (Thwaites 1903:627, from La Salle 1674:190); 7. There is a place on the Wabash River where there is an old fish weir still visible, probably from the old Miamis (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2004). Fish nets, possibly made of dogbane fibers, were used at the mouth of these weirs (000). Lamoine Marks told Rafert (1989) that before the commercial nets basket nets were made from bark, mostly the inner bark of the slippery elm, or red elm, and these were used at the weirs (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:47); 8. In old times, according to Lamoine Marks, Miami fishermen used fishnets and baskets to catch fish (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:29, 2ndy source, original unknown); 9. In more modern times Miami fishermen [like Charlie Marks, 1870-1946, Lamoine\'s father) used commercial seine nets and spears (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:29); 10. An ancient fishing weir dam still exists on the Wabash River, northeast of Peru, Indiana and was and is known to most Miami fishermen. Lamoine Marks was told about it when he was a boy, by his father Charlie, and last saw it while fishing in winter in 1953.  Rafert and Marks rediscovered it in July, 1988. This weir dam is described in Outdoor Indiana, July/August 198;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'waapahsapiiki (hemp cord-Grav-see Rel Info #19);', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(64, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OToyMDkyMToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Aralia nudicaulis L.', 'Wild sarsasparilla', 'Araliaceae (Ginseng)', '(maahkwana)', NULL, '1. Occurs in woods of various conditions (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"makkwana, vine, generic term sometimes used specifically for wild sarsasparilla\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MEDICINAL: root used for wounds and cuts. \"The root of sasparilla for wounds and cuts\" (Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De la racine de sarsepareille pour les playes et coupures\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 3. UNKNOWN: \"macac8ani\", wild sarsasparilla (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'macac8ani (Pinet)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '(1696) 1724', '-1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(65, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4MDUyMzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Aralia racemosa L.', 'Spikenard', 'Araliaceae (Ginseng)', 'kahkiitiahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used medicinally (Dunn ca. 1900), See Rel. Info. 1); 2. MEDICINAL: tea made by boiling \"spicnert\", horehound, comfrey, cherry bark and \"alicompain\"[spelling may not be accurate] (Mildred Walker\'s papers, given to Myaamia Project 2004);', NULL, NULL, '1. Steyermark (1963:441) remarks that young shoots and starchy rootstocks are a food source for some Indian tribes, and the berries possess a cathartic action;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(66, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo2MDgwMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Arisaema triphyllum Schott.', 'Indian turnip, Jack-in-the-pulpit', 'Araceae (Arum)', '(wiikopayiisia)', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist rich woods or bogs throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: poisonous raw, prepared for eating. \"That which they call wi\'kopaisia meaning \"bear\'s root,\" is an actual poison if eaten raw, but they cut it in very thin slices, and cook it in an oven during three days and three nights, thus by heat they cause the acrid substance which renders it poisonous to evaporate in steam, and it then becomes what is commonly called cassava root (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:115); 2. FOOD: indian turnip prepration. \"The \"oven\" mentioned was a hole dug in the ground, and heated by a fire in it, after which it was cleaned out, filled with food, and covered over. Further mention of its use is made in connection with the wild onion\" (Blair 1911:115 footnote, from Walter Hough, Handbook Amer. Indians); 3. FOOD: wild plant and tuber called \'Indian turnip\'. \"This is a good description [referring to Perrot\'s description in entry #1] of the Indian turnip (Arisaema triphyllum), but the Miamis call it wi\'kopaisia, which does not mean bear\'s root\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 4. MEDICINAL: root used as an emetic, root tea used for treating asthma (Interviews with Miami elders, Rafert 1992:45); 5. FOOD: used to make horseradish even stronger tasting. A neighbor taught Jim Strack that if you use the bulf from the jack-in-the-pulpit, grind it a bit and put it in the horseradish, it will make it so strong that just a bit on your tongue would make your tongue burn (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, '1. Perrot said the meaning of the Miami word for this plant was \'bear\'s root\', but he probably confused the meaning of the Miami word for this plant with the meaning of macopine, which would literally mean \'bear root\'.  The Miami no longer used \'macopin\' for this plant in 1919, but did in Perrot\'s time (1800s). Makopin is the Chippewa name of the water-chinquepin, but micoupena was the Peoria name of the white water lily-, Nymphaea tuberosa. (Dunn 1919) (Makopin could be a generic term for aquatic, underground, edible tuber);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(67, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTozNjI1MToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Arundinaria gigantea Chapman. (A. tecta)', 'Giant cane or Canebrake', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in damp woods, swamps and other moist areas in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Also known as \'cane reed\' with former specific epithet of A. macrosperma (Small 1903); 2. Fibers used for moccasins and rope making by most prehistoric cave and rock-shelter peoples within its range (Whitford 1941);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(68, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTozOTUzMzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Asarum canadense L.', 'Wild ginger', 'Aristolochiaceae (Birthwort)', NULL, NULL, '1.Occurs in rich woods, in colonies (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: used for seasoning (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 2. MEDICINAL: root used to stop childbirth pains. \"The root of ginger crushed in powder for putting a stop to the pains of a woman in childbirth\" (Anonymous 1724:164A-B, \"De la Racine de Gingembre pile en poudre pour Empecher le Cranchez a un femme dans l\'enfantement\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 3. FOOD/MEDICINAL: roots harvested, ground and used as a spice or chewed to alleviate motion sickness. Can cook roots with honey to make candy. Thick and fine roots all have good taste and scent. Can dry and store in frig (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(69, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OToyMzAxODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Asclepias syriaca L.', 'Common milkweed', 'Asclepidaceae (Milkweed)', 'lenin≈°i', '1. Grows clonally into patches of several to many stout stems, 1-2 m high, mostly unbranched, hairy; leaves thick, elliptic to ovate, soft-hairy beneath, 10-15 cm in length, acute; petioles 5-15 mm; umbels often numerous, terminal and lateral, compactly many-flowered (spheric); peduncles 3-10 cm; corolla pink to nearly green; hoods pale purple, somewhat divergent surpassing the gynostegium, the lateral margins with a prominent, sharp triangular lobe near the middle; horns short, inflexed; fruit erect on deflexed pedicels, tomentose with soft conic nobs (Gleason & Cronquist 1991); 2. flowering from June to August, fruiting from July to frost (Duke 1992);', '1. Occurs in fields, meadows and roadsides in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason & Cronquist 1991); 2. Occurs in open fields, woods, waste ground, along roadsides and railroads (Steyermark 1963); 3. abundant weed in pastures, prairies, old fields (Duke 1992);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: shoots eaten as greens, prepared much as asparagus, flower buds cooked in soup, \"Their preference in greens is for the shoots of the common (purple) milkwweed, which is prepared much the same as asparagus. Godfroy said that milkweed \"has substance\", and that it could be used in place of potatoes\" (Dunn 1919); 2. FOOD: buds eaten. Wash harvested buds well and chop up. Boil them, pour off water, parboil it and cook until tender, then pour off most of water, then add bacon. Then sprinkle flour over it and stir it. Eva always made it into rivlins, which is using fine flour and milk or water, cooking it a bit after adding the flour. Or just add vinegar and salt to taste, not pepper (Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978); 3. FOOD/MEDICINAL: \"Milkweed was used as food since 1400\'s and 1500\'s, known as \'medicine food\', this is not written down anywhere, that it was used so far back, but the info has been passed down orally\", \"soup was made from milkweed, using some part for medicine or food\" (Interviews with Gary Shoemaker, 2003 & 2004); 4. FOOD: \"It was boiled first--they didn\'t have flour for thickening--so they just boiled it and ate it with seasoning. Seasoning was probably some type of meat. But in later years, as they acquired knowledge of using thickening like flour or corn meal, they thickened it, and made a type of gravy, much like you would cook asparagus today. It was one of the real important things for the Indians, important foods of the spring.\" \"It was used like a tonic and of course it was something green, which they hadn\'t had in the winter time\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:90-91, Rafert mentions in these interview notes that other tribal members mentioned the importance of milkweed as a spring food); 5. FOOD: Swan Hunter liked eating milkweed, and his father did too. Eva also mentioned wanting to get some and knowing where. Swan says he had some plants to harvest. Eva froze some. (Interview with Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley,  Rafert 1978); 6. FOOD: the center, tender leaves and shoot part, of the top of the plant [possibly the new flower buds] and cook it.\" She also indicated that when the pods were small, you can take out the insides [immature floss] and cook it for eating (Interview with Phyllis Miley, 2003); 7. MEDICINAL: milky sap used to treat warts (Rafert 1992:43, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy); 8. FOOD: eaten as greens (Interview with Howard Walker, Judy Davis, Ken Dagenet and Mildred Walker, 2004); 9. FOOD: sap used as chewing gum (Interview with George Strack, Sr. relating use of milkweed learned from non-Miami friends/relatives, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 2004); 10. MEDICINAL: general use. \"My mother [mother-in-law] used milkweed and other plants as medicine\" \". . .it was good spring medicine . . .she cooked it and we ate it because it was good. . .had a lot of iron in it and everything and so we\'d have that for greens\". Pods were not eaten (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004, Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 11. FOOD: eaten. Jim Strack and his family did not eat milkweed but he knew people that did (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 12. UNKNOWN: (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 13. UNKNOWN: laninji (Dunn ca. 1900); 14. FOOD/MEDICINE: young shoots, top four leaves of stems, and flower buds are gathered, cooked and eaten. Sap used to remove moles  (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005); 15. MEDICINAL: sap used to remove warts (Interview with George Dorin, 2004);', '1. The young shoots with four leaves or less are harvested in early spring (Interview with Lora Siders, Baldwin 1997); 2. \"Harvest young shoots at various heights, when they first have the little buds beginning and the buds are still green, then you just take about 6-8 inches off the top\" (Interview of Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978); 3. \"Milkweed was very iimportant. Milkweed was usually gathered when it was about eight to ten inches tall. We always broke off the small leaves at the top--I mean the leaves at the top which were really the largest ones--they used mostly the stem, much like asparagus\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:90); 4. Mildred Walker\'s mother-in-law, Rebbeca M. Stitt Walker, brought seeds of common milkweed from Indiana and planted them in her garden in Oklahoma (Quapaw area) for harvesting and eating as greens. Other women in the neighborhood also harvested milkweed for eating, and when Mildred returned one time as an adult to her old home and Rebecca\'s old garden, the milkweed had been harvested, presumably by the old friends of Rebecca (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004); 5. Mildred Walker remarked that the young shoots and leaves of common milkweed they harvested for eating were fuzzier and narrower than the ones we harvested during a language camp outing (author\'s note: Some variation in leaf width and \'fuzziness\' does occur between individual plants and areas). She also picked a very young dogbane (Apocynum cannabinum) shoot and said it was a \'milkweed\' and was eaten as greens (author\'s note: This species has narrower leaves, not necessarily fuzzier, but has milky sap and looks very similar to common milkweed shoots--it may have been called a \'milkweed\' at this stage due to its similar look, milky sap, and purposes identical to common milkweed) (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004); 6. Dani Tippman and her mother Mary (Strack) Swenda harvest the top four leaves of taller plants, or plants of any stage of growth and cook them as greens. \"The four leaves represent the four directions, \" said Mary. The white milkweed, not eaten was probably a name for dogbane, which looks reddish and not-fuzzy when young, unlike milkweed. She has noticed the stems kept growing and flowered after tops removed for eating (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005); 7. Dani Tippman learned from her mother, Mary (Strack) Swenda, to harvest one out of every four milkweed stems (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2004); 8. A milkweed harvesting trip was part of the language camp in June 2004, when the milkweed had both young shoots and taller stems for harvest. Mildred Walker, Howard Walker, Daryl Baldwin and many other tribal members participated in this late spring harvesting (Aatotankiki myaamiaki 2004 7(2):6);', '1. Cases of poisoning have been recorded from livestock feeding on leaves and stems, but usually these plants remain untouched in pastures (Steyermark 1962); 2. Red milkweed beetle (Tetraopes tetraoophthalmus) feeds almost entirely on this species of milkweed, its life cycle often restricted to one plant (McCauley 1991); 3. The bast fiber quality varies greatly depending on soil type, climate, amount of rainfall, and other environmental factors (Wild and Useful Plants of Texas 000: 35); 4. The area around Miami, OK and KS, at the time of Miami relocation was all tallgrass prairie, where the buffalo and fire kept the forest limited to river bottoms. The buffalo only went through a particular area about once a year, probably following early spring shoots of prairie plants north as spring progressed. Common milkweed plants would\'ve persisted well in this annual, early spring disturbance, and Miami harvesting of this disturbance would mimic the disturbance caused by buffalo (Conversation with Dustin Olds, Tribal Property Prairie, Miami, OK, 6/7/03);', '1. The root used by Forest Potawatomi as an undetermined medicine; 2. MATERIAL: fibers in stem used for threat materials like dogbane; 3. FOOD: flowers and buds used in soups. \"One always finds a riot of milkweed close to the wigwam or house of the Indian, suggesting that they have been cultivated. Meat soups are thickened with the buds and flowers . . . \" (Smith 1933); 4. The root used by Ojibway as a undetermined female medicine, fresh flowers and tips of shoots in soups, gather and dry flowers and use in soup in winter, use the milk along with milk of Canada Hawkweed to put on a deer call (Smith 1932); 5. Common milkweed has been used by Delaware in burden strap, drum string (Whitford1941); 6. Fish nets made of milkweed fibers by Cherokee (Whitford 1941); 7. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993); 8. The Miami did not eat the shoots of a smaller species of Asclepias, called the white-flowered milkweed [Squaw milkweed] which they called \'lemontehsa\'. They considered the small shoots, or \'pups\' of this species to be poisonous. (Dunn ca. 1900); 9. Fibers from the common milkweed were widely used by most tribes within the plant\'s geographic distribution. Objects were made in part of whole using common milkweed fibers, including a Sauk and Fox bag, a Delaware drum string, a Kickapoo ball of string and a fish net by the prehistoric cave and rock-shelter dwellers of Ohio (Whitford 1941); 8. Dried roots of Asclepias tuberosa (Butterfly milkweed) in small doses (1-3 gm) reduces arterial tension by depressing heart action and causes diaphoresis (000?) and increases diuresis (000?). It is also an expectorant, and be a slight tonic, mild laxative, carminative (000?), diuretic, and an emetic in large doses (Coulter 1932:10, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 9. Young shoots of other milkweed species have been noted as food of Canadian Indians, beginning as early as the 18th century. Use of young flower buds and pods as food by Native Americans in recent times has also been documented for the Zuni, Blackfoot, Cheyenne, Rio Grande Pueblo at Jemez, Tarahumar, Tewa, Kiowa, White Mountain Apache and Hopi. Often, pods were cooked with meat, in an attempt to soften the meat by action of a compound in the pods that caused tenderizing. There are some reports of Native American groups eating butterfly milkweed, Asclepias tuberosa, tubers, although these are treated by contemporary researchers as poisonous. Numerous species were used by numerous tribes for the bast (stem) fibers for cordage, ropes, basketry and netting in historic times. (Cheatam et al. 1995:30-33); 10. McPherson wrote, \"The Miami Indians used the sap to rid themselves of warts.\" \". . . milkweed may have been cultivated by the Potawatomie Indians. Milkweed grew so close to the wigwams that it could have been planted th??;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, '(~common weed/plant??)', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'lenomeesha (Mary (Strack) Swenda)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1978', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(70, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo4MDg5MToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Asclepias variegata L.', 'White milkweed', 'Asclepiadaceae (Milkweed)', 'alemontehsa', NULL, '1. Occurs in upland woods and thickets (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. NONE: lamonda\'ssa (Dunn ca. 1900)', NULL, NULL, '1. Shoots of the smaller species of Asclepias or of the white-flowered milkweed, were not eaten according to Dunn (ca.1909); 2. Literal meaning of Miami word means \'puppy\'--possibly a name for the seedling of the dogbane plant that would have been very similar in look to young shoots of the food plant, common milkweed, but not eaten (author\'s note). The Miami \"used green shoots of milkweed - don\'t use small purplish stem with slim-sharp pointed leaves\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, '(pup root, or puppy)', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(71, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo3Njk0Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Asimina triloba (L.) Dunal.', 'Pawpaw tree', 'Annonaceae (Custard-apple)', 'mihsiimi≈°aahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich, damp woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"missiminjakwi, pawpaw trees, eat pawpaws\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3636dw); 2. UNKNOWN: \"mihsimini lakiihkwi\", pawpaw bark (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. UNKNOWN: (Dunn ca. 1900-EM 000?); 4. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 5. UNKNOWN: \"missi=mishaxkwi, pawpaw tree\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1261); 6. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"nuxsiminaxkwi, the pawpaw tree and its fruit . . . the fruit is pulpy and higly prized on account of its sweet nutritious quality, shape oblong and up to four inches in length or over\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1691); 7. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"There were other trees as thick as one\'s leg, which bend under a yellowish fruit of the shape and size of a medium-sized cucumber, which the savages call assemina. . . They have five or six nuclei inside which are as big as marsh beans, and of about the same shape. I ate, one day, sixty of them, big and little. This fruit does not ripen till October, like the medlars\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:320, \"il y en avoit encore d\'autres gros comme la jambe qui ployoient d\'un fruit jaunastre de la figure et grosseur d\'un moyen concombre que les sauvages appellent assemina, . . . Ils ont 5 ou 6 noyaux dedans qui sont gros comme de fevves de marais, et a peu pres faits de meme, j\'en ay mange unjour soixante tant gros que petits, il n\'est mure qu\'au mois d\'ocotobre, aussi bien que les neifles,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 8. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"Pawpaws they ate. That was considered a fruit and I still eat them. And by the way, there are going to be some this year. We\'re going to have a good pawpaw season. . . I eat them when they are dead ripe. And I can go through the woods, and smell it??s the time to hunt pawpaws. I just beat the \'coons and \'possums by a little bit. I introduced all my nephews and my grandsons to eating pawpaws. And the way to introduce \'em to it is to get them good and hungry out in the woods, and then as a last resort they\'ll eat one of \'em.\"(Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:100); 9. UNKNOWN: pawpaw (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 10. FOOD: used as a snack food when in the woods (Rafert 1996:182); 11. UNKNOWN: \"nasimini patek, the paw-paw fruit has fried, or dries up\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1762); 12. FOOD: fruits gathered and eaten (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005); ', NULL, NULL, '1. Fibers from stems used in numerous historic objects, including coarse bags, fabrics and split bark bags of Ohio cave and rock-shelter dwellers, a bag from the Menomini where the pawpaw fiber is used only in the weft, a Potawatomi bag. Its use seems only limited by its distribution (Whitford 1941); 2. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993); 3. Dunn gives the Miami term \"ha?siimi\" for pawpaw (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989, editorial note in interview transcript); 4. Gatschet also lists the Miami term \"noohsiimi?aahkwi\", \"noohsiiminaahkwi\", and \"nuximinaxkwaki\" for the pawpaw fruit (Gatschet ca. 1895:1691); 5. There is an area in the heart of eastern Miami lands called Pawpaw alley, east of Peru along highway 19 (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2004);', 'FALSE', 'noohsimisaakwi (Gat),', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'asimezkiki (grove, rel info 5); mihsiimini (fruit)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1721', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
