(81, 'MTUwNTg2MTI5OTo0MzMxOToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Carpinus caroliniana Walter.', 'Ironwood, Hornbeam, Blue beech, Musclewood', 'Betulaceae (Beech)', 'myaalwami≈°i', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. (TECHNOLOGY/MATERIAL): \"mialwami\'ndji, ironwood\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. Eastern Hophornbeam, Ostrya virginiana, is also known as Ironwood, but is not known for its muscle-textured stems, having brownish, shreddy trunk bark. American hornbeam, Carpinus caroliniana, has smooth, grey, muscle-textured trunk bark and the Miami word \'myaawaamisi\' refers to this aspect of this species (author\'s note and Baldwin 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1900', '-1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:19', '2017-09-19 22:48:19')
(82, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo0OTA2Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Carya glabra (P.Mill) Sweet', 'Pignut hickory tree', 'Juglandaceae (Walnut)', 'paapahsaahkimi≈°i', '1. Carya cordiformis is much more common throughout MO than C. glabra, and both are commonly called Pignut hickory, suggesting that C. glabra was not common in the past in NE OK (Steyermark 1963) although it was mentioned from one account in OK (Bogue 1900); 2. Carya glabra is the only Pignut hickory mentioned in Coulter\'s flora of Indiana, and this was widely distributed throughout the state, a tree up to 120 feet high with 3-5 foot diameters. C. cordiformis is not mentioned (Coulter 1899); 3. Carya glabra is the only Pignut hickory mentioned in Small\'s flora, a tree up to 180 feet high and 4.5 foot diameters. C. cordiformis is not mentioned (Small 1903);', '1. Occurs in upland woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: canoe, \"If they wanted canoes lighter than dug-outs, they made them of the bark of the water-elm or hickory, the pig-nut hickory being considered best. They cut down a tree, peeled off the bark with flat sticks. In the spring, when the trees were beginning to leave, the bark came off easily, and at other times they had to pound it to loosen it.\" (Dunn 1919); 2. TECHNOLOGY: bark used for sugar-sap containers, wood for drying tables. \"this kind [of hickory wood] also used for tables for drying corn, berries, or fruit. In this case, poles were placed in forked sticks. Bark used for sugar troughs--the ends were bent up, fastened, soaked and straightened out and laid up like shingles when dry for use the following uear. These would last for several years. Boxes also made of this wood\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. (FOOD/TECHNOLOGY): \"paciani\'kopa, peorias call this pignut\" (Dunn ca. 1900:102, report); 4. UNKNOWN: 000? (Dunn ca. 1900); 5. FOOD: nuts gathered for food (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, '1. Early settlers obtained an oil from the nut that was used in oil lams and in the treatment of rheumatism (Steyermark 1963); 2. There were Carya sp. charcoal remains and other hickory nutshells found in sample  082, 082 & 085,  from the New Lennox remains (MTO files, F-8 data from 213A); 3. The Miami-Illinois term \"paapakimini\" referred to the actual pig-nut, not the wood or tree (Dunn ca. 1900:2466dw); 4. Dunn noted that the Miami term \"\'pa\'cianikopa\" was used by the Peoria for only the Pignut hickory (Dunn ca. 1900); 5. The Peoria term cited by Dunn (ca.1909) for pignut hickory tree is also used by the Eastern Miami as a generic for all hickory trees; 6. Perrot describes a nut about 2 inches long that is bitter and oily and inedible which could be referring to the pignut, although it is not that bitter (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:119);', 'FALSE', 'pa\'ciani\'kopa (Dunn)', NULL, 'middle wood/tree', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(83, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMTQ3NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Carya illinoenensis (Wangenh.) K. Koch', 'Pecan nut', 'Juglandaceae (Walnut)', 'kaansensimini', NULL, '1. Occurs in wet and alluvial forests (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \" . . . The pakan-tree, when not of very large dimensions, grows fast and in the Quapaw Reservation and in same latitude elsewhere begins to bear when six or seven years old. The Peoria call its nut, kanzespakani, they grow taller when standing within the timber than on the prairie where they branch out sidewise on account of frequent storms.\" (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria); 2. UNKNOWN: pecan, the Miami name of the Ohio River is similar, being \'kanzansapiwi\' (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. FOOD: nuts gathered for food (See entry #1, in ecological information) (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 4. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 5. (FOOD): \"kanzanzamini\", pecan nut (Dunn ca. 1900:3661dw); 6. UNKNOWN: \"akansepakaninji\", pecan (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', '1. Pecan nuts begin falling and are ready for harvest typically in mid-October (Aatotankiki myaamiaki 7(2):2);', NULL, '1. A 30 acre wild pecan grove at Geboe property was purchased in 2002  (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 5(1):7, 2002); 2. Pecans from a tree on Tribal land (Libbert properties--Tahway Farms\') that produces good kernel with thin shell won Oklahoma State Pecan Award for 2001 in \"Small Native\" category (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 5(4):13, 2002); 3. McPherson wrote \"Pacca, the Miami Indian chief who succeeded Little Turtle in 1812, was named in honor of the pecan. Paccan is the Algonquian word that pecan is derived from\" (1977:61, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 4. The Miami-Illiinois name for the pecan, is linguistically related to the name for all the prehistoric Dhegiha tribes, including the modern Kaw or Kansa. Most likely, the tribe was associated with this name by themselves and other tribes, due to their residency along the portions of the Ohio river where they lived and designated the southern range of this tree species (Costa 2000:31-32); 5. The Miami Tribe\'s Tahway Farms has pecan groves and the pecans are part of a traditional, healthy, diet of the Miami and other Native Americans living in the native range of the pecan. The tribe is selling these pecans as part of a way to promote a healthy diet (Aatotankiki myaamiaki 2004 7(2):2);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1696 (1895)', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(84, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MDE4MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Carya laciniosa (Michx. f.) G.', 'Shell-bark hickory', 'Juglandaceae (Walnut)', 'caacinkilaakia or ceecinkilaakia (tree)', NULL, '1. Occurs on flood plains (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"a place near Kokomo, where a number of shell-bark hickories grew, having white nuts\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. UNKNOWN: \"wapipakani, hickory nut\" (Dunn ca. 1900:2677); 3 FOOD: nuts gathered for food (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 4. FOOD: eaten by Fox squirrel in the traditional story Wissakatchakwa (Gatschet ca. 1895, told by Elizabeth Vallier, Miami speaker, with help of Sarah Wadsworth); 5. UNKNOWN: \"cacingilakaxkwa\" Peoria word for shell-bark hickory (Gatschet ca. 1895); 6. UNKNOWN: \"tcatcingilakakwa\" Wea word for shell-bark hickory (Dunn Report ca. 1900:102 & 2676dw); 7. UNKNOWN: \"tchatchingilakaxkwa pakani, shellbark hickory nut\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1725);', NULL, NULL, '1. Bartram (1739-1823) described the Creek\'s processing of shell-barked hickory nuts. \"I have seen above an hundreds of bushels of these nuts belonging to one family. They pound them to pieces, and then cast them into boiling water, which, after passing through fine strainers, preserves the most oily part of the liquid: this they call by a name which signifies hiccory milk, it is as sweet and rich as fresh cream, and is an ingredient in most of their cookery, especially in homony [sic] and corn cakes.\" (Van Doren 1928:57, Bartram); 2. Shell-bark hickory has been reported to produce 3 bushels of nuts per tree, yielding approximately 42 pounds of edible nutmeat per tree, per year--seven trees being enough to feed one person for a year (Gardner 1997:103); 3. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period (Bush 2003); 4. Dunn listed the Miami term \"tcatcingilakakwa\" for the shell-bark hickory (Dunn rep. p102), where Hockett listed \"cecingilakya\" [special characters changed to regular alphabet] (Hockett 1938:140) and Thornton listed \"tshatshinggalukeh\" (Thornton 1802);', 'FALSE', 'caacinkilakaahkwa (fruit, Hock, Gat)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. waapipaakani (hickory fruit); 2. waapipa.. (grove, Dunn);', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(85, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2Nzc0NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Carya sp. Nutt.', 'Smooth-bark hickory', 'Juglandadeae (Walnut)', '(kweehsiaanikopa)', '1. The species indicated by this Miami word was probably the saplings of one or more of the following: Carya ovata, Shagbark hickory, C. glabra, Pignut hickory, or C. laciniosa, Shell-bark hickory. The bark of each of these species is relatively smooth for the first few years of its life, then turning furrowed, or scaley, but not extremely (Small 1903; Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', '1. Occurs in rich, moist soils (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: wood for long bows was made from the smooth-bark hickory (kwassiani kupa), one split sapling making two long bows and other bows made from buffalo ribs. Bird arrows made with blunt points of hickory wood. The sweat lodge in Peoria was made of hickory branches or other material that bent easily (Dunn ca. 1900-Peoria); 2. UNKNOWN: kwassianikupa, smooth-bark hickory (Gatschet ca. 1895);', NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period (Bush 2003); 3. The term \"kwaciani\'kopa\" was used for hickories, in general (Dunn ca. 1900:102report); 4. The term \"qefeneqopu\" also refers to the hickory (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer,from  Mongosa);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'waapipaakani (hickory fruit)', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(86, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTg2Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Carya spp. Nutt.', 'Hickory tree', 'Juglandaceae (Walnut)', 'peesiaanikopa', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich, moist soils (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: bird arrows with a blunt point made out of dogwood and hickory wood, both which sink in the water (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MATERIAL: Shingaukekaunekee is a game played on the ice, with a bow, about fifteen feet long, four inches wide and a half an inch thick, made from hickory or another hard wood. \"it may be said to resemble a sleigh runner rather than a bow, in shape, and one end is thicker & heavier than the other.\" Two people play, and each has a boundary, quite far apart, that the other tries to obtain by throwing the bow. The bow is thrown to move towards the far boundary, each person trying to gain their own boundary behind their opponent. The whole village is involved, and there are objects of value staked upon the game, by the villagers. Sometimes the game starts by one village sending a challenge to another village, by way of a miniature bow, decorated with the items to be staked upon the game. Poles are set up during the game, for hanging these items used for betting. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:63); 3. UNKNOWN: peesiananikopa means hickory tree, \"pacianikopa, hickory\" (Dunn ca. 1900-EM000?); 4. UNKNOWN: The term \'kwacianikopa\' was used generically for the hickory tree by the Peoria (Dunn ca. 1900); 5. TECHNOLOGY: stems hollowed out using a willow branch, then a whittled down hickory stick placed inside along with a paper wad to make a \'pop-gun\' (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 6. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 7. TECHNOLOGY: hickory bark bundles lit and used as torches for night spear fishing. \"But they also made it of hickory bark and fastened it in bundles and fired that and made torches with that, to walk by at night and spear fish . . . This getting fish at night when the water\'s clear was the best way in the world to get them\" (Interview tih Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:35; 2ndy source, original unknown--he read about this tradition); 8. TECHNOLOGY: Peoria arrows were made of hickory and dogwood (Frank Beaver, from Gatschet ca. 1895:2661); 9. TECHNOLOGY: bark used for making canoes.  \"The Miamis did not use birch-bark canoes, which the Algonquians usually called tci-maun, but they sometimes made canoes of hickory or elm bark. The name for these is la-kik-kwi-mis-so-li or bark canoe\" (Dunn 1908:manuscript 1701); 10. MATERIAL: temporary houses made of bent hickory branches and other trees to form a dome. \"nusikani, sweat-lodge or aboriginal sudatory [000?]. These temporary structures consisted of bent branches of hickory or other trees, and planted in the ground on both ends. A buffalo or cowhile was thrown over the circular space within, and after excluding the outside air, heated stones were brought inside and steam developed by throwing water\" (erf --what ref? 000); 11. UNKNOWN: \"pakanizhi\", \"pakana tawani\" and \"pakanizhaxkwi\" all mean the \"hickory tree in all its species as enumerated under pakani\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1726); 12. UNKNOWN: \"qefeneqopu, hickory\" (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer, 2nd Wea Primer); 13. FOOD: nuts gathered for eating (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005); 14. TECHNOLOGY: wood used to make bow (Interview with Jacob Weisenberger, 2004; speaking of his father\'s plant use);', NULL, NULL, '1. A Peoria observation of Nez Perces when they were held in Miami--\"To make their bows they would bury their hickory poles in the coals until the outside of the poles charred and then they would scrape off the charred portion. This was repeated until the pole became the size wanted and in this way the wood was seasoned at the same time.\"(Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period (Bush 2003); 3. Great Lakes tribes, in general, use sweats to treat many illnesses. To provoke a sweat, hickory wood and pine branches are boiled in a kettle under the person, causing a profuse sweat (Charlevoix 1682-1761:175, from Kellogg 1923:163); 3. Allouez remarked about the Illinois\' use of bow and arrow: \"They ordinarily carry only the warclub, bow, and a quiver full of arrows, which they discharge so adroitly and quickly, that men armed with guns, have hardly time to raise them to the shoulder. They also carry a large buckler made of skins of wild cattle; which is arrow-proof, and covers the whole body\" (Allouez 1677, from Shea 1903:78); 4. Human-charred hickory shell material recovered from excavations at an early 19th century Miami village site (Bush 1996:181);', 'FALSE', 'pakana tawani (Gat)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'waapipaakani (hickory fruit, lit. white nuts)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1825', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(87, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3MjQ2MToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Castanea dentata Borkh.', 'Chestnut', 'Fagaceae (Beech)', 'maami≈°imi≈°i', '1. Chestnuts eaten by Indians were reportedly \"bigger and finer than those of Lyons,\" (Pease 1934:348-349, Deliette 1721);', '1. Originally occurred on acid upland soils throughout eastern Miami lands, but now almost eliminated due to blight (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: leaves used for coughs, especially whooping coughs (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy); 2. FOOD: roasted and eaten. \"There are Indian chestnuts of admirable beauty full of nuts bigger and finer than those of Lyons. There is no one who on seeing them does not believe them to be excellent.\" They were reportedly very bitter, even after cooking on a fire. (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:348-349; \"Il y a des maroniers d\'inde d\'une beaute a admirer remplies de marons plus gros et plus beaux que ceux de lion, il ny a personne en les voyant qui ne croient qu\'ils soient Excellentes . . . j\'en  mordis un croyant manger le meilleur maron du monde, mais je fus bien paye de ma Curiosite car je fus plus d\'un quart d\'heure sans pouvoir m\'oster l\'amertume qu\'il m\'avoit laisse a la bouche,\" translation from French to English by Pease);', NULL, NULL, '1. Human-charred chestnut nutshell and nutmeat material were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181): 2. LeBoullenger has \"mamichimina\" for chestnut, and Thornton has \"mamishiminjeh\", for chestnut tree (author\'s note, info from Costa, pers. comm. 2006);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'maami?imina (chestnut )', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1721', '(1964)-2ndy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(88, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzQzMDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Celtis occidentalis L.', 'Northern hackberry tree', 'Ulmaceae (Elm)', 'pakamaakani≈°i', NULL, '1. Occurs in a moist, rich soils including floodplains throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. CUSTOMS: boards lining sides of burial holes. \"pakamakaninji, hackberry\" used to make puncheon of hackberry made pieces for top, bottom, sides and ends of holes (Dunn ca. 1900:2465); 2. TECHNOLOGY: young shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar fed to livestock during hard times (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 3. TECHNOLOGY: used for firewood. \"The tree gives good fuel\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1719); 4. UNKNOWN: \"papaaki\'mini, hackberry berry\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 5. UNKNOWN: \"apakamanganingi\", 	hackberry Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Peoria of OK cut up the tender shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar for cattle fodder (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. The Miami term \"pakamakani\" refers to the berry of the hackberry, \"the dark red berry of the hackberry tree\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1719);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'paapakimini (fruit)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900 (1700)', '1938', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(89, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo0MzkyOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Cercis canadensis L.', 'Eastern redbud', 'Caesalpiniaceae (Caesalpinia)', '(eeyoonsaaweekisa)', '1. A tree related to the locust and mesquite reaching a diamter from 8-18 inches and yellow grained wood (Gatshet 1895);', '1. Occurs in moist woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: redbud or \'judas tree\', with yellow wood (Dunn ca. 1900:3936dw); 2. UNKNOWN: \"ayunzawikisha\" -- in this name the adjective \"-unzawi\" yellow refers to the yellow graining of the tree, indicated also by Finley (Gatschet ca. 1895:456); 3. FOOD: young, tender pods cooked like snow peas. Flowers eaten raw or dried and added to soups (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, '(-ooonsawee)=yellow wood', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '(1900) 2005', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(90, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MzQ3NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Chenopodium ambrosioides L.', 'Goosefoot, Lamb\'s quarters', 'Chenopodiaceae (Goosefoot)', '(waapinkopakahki)', NULL, '1. Native to tropical America, occurring as a weed in disturbed areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: young leaves gathered and cooked as greens. \" It was used as a spring tonic for cleansing the body. The young leaves of poke, curly dock and lamb\'s quarter\'s were gathered near my house, mixed together and cooked with vinegar\" (Interview with Judy Davis, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/1/04); 2. FOOD: greens collected and eaten. Seeds collected and made into flour, cut in half with wheat flour (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005); 3. (FOOD): \"waapinkopakahki\" (Dunn, Peoria fieldnotes ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. Volative oil distilled from fresh aboveground portions of the flowering and fruiting plant of Chenopodium ambrosioides var. anthelminticum, in small doses (1cc) has been used to treat round-, tape-, and hook-worms. In general, it increases cardiac rate, promotes secretions of bronchial tubes and kidneys, and has been used to treat hysteria (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 2. McPherson wrote, \"It is believed that prior to introduction of corn prehistoric Indians in Indiana cultivated lamb\'s quarters [Chenopodium sp.] is a green for its seeds. It is high in vitamins A and C and an excellent source of calcium\" (1977:81, 2ndy source without primary source citation);  3. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that goosefoot was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" for consumption of seeds by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '2004', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
