(93, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMTM1Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Citrullus vulgaris Shrad.', 'Watermelon', 'Cucurbitaceae (Gourd)', 'iihkihtaminki', NULL, '1. Also known as C. colocynthis (Hickman 1993), hence \'coloquinte\', C. vulgaris is a native to Africa cultivated throughout eastern and western (?) Miami lands;', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: eaten raw (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"They harvest also a great many watermelons which are admirable. I have seen numbers of them as big as water buckets\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:344-345; \"Elles recueillent aussi quantite de melons d\'eau qui sont admirables j\'en ay vu quantite d\'aussi gros qu\'un seau,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 3. FOOD: given to missionaries to eat (Kenton 1925:364, The Jesuit Relations); 3. UNKNOWN: 000? (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 4. (FOOD): \"They have abundance of water-melons, citruls, and gourds\" (Joliet 1674:186, from Thwaites 1903:622); 5. FOOD: dried and eaten. \"They greatly esteem their citruls, though they are none of the best. They dry them up, and keep them till the Winter and Spring\" (Thwaites 1903:652, from Marquette 1673:209-210); 6. FOOD: given to Marquette and Jolliet\'s party to eat. \"We ate no other fruit there than watermelons\" (Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966 (reprint from 1900:59)); \"nous n\'y avons pas mange de fruictz que des melons d\'eau,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites); 7. FOOD: modern modern traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 8. FOOD: watermelons grown (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112); 9. MEDICINAL: seeds used for medicine. \"Their medicines they use for purging have all the effectiveness possible. There are some who use coloquinte, with which the wilderness abounds in autumn when they gather their seeds.\" (Pease 1934:367, Deliette 1721; \"Celles don??t ils se servent pour purger font tout l\'effet possible. Il y a qui se servent de Coloquinte don??t les deserts sont pleins L\'automne, quand ils ont cueillis leurs grains,\"ranslation from French to English by Pease);gg', '1. \"They never see snow in their country, and recognize the winter only through the rains, which there fall more frequently than in summer. We ate no other fruit there than watermelons. If they knew how to till their soil, theywould have fruits of all kinds.\" (Kenton 1925:364, The Jesuit Relations); 2. Watermelons, along with sunflowers and gourds are first sprouted in a hot-bed and then transplanted into crop fields (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112)', NULL, '1. No listing of Citrullus in Gleason and Cronquist (1991), but Steyermark lists as C. vulgaris and Small (1903) as C. citrullus (Author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'coloquinte', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1673', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(94, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozMzY2OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Coffea arabica L.', 'Coffee', 'Rubiaceae (Madder)', 'kociihsaapowi', NULL, '1. Native to Africa--not cultivated but traded in Miami lands (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: \"They took to coffee like a duck to water when it became introduced to them. But in their earlier days, their primitive days, they didn\'t know coffee. The only drink they had of that type would have been sassafras or spicebush\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989);', NULL, NULL, '1. Miami word given here for dogwood is from \'kocisa\', meaning bean, and \'poi\', meaning tea (C.F. Voegelin, Shawnee Stems and the Jacob P. Dunn Miami Dictionary, pp. 292 and 311);', 'FALSE', 'kaahpi', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1989', '1989', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(95, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2MjQwMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Conzya canadensis (L.) Cronq.', 'Horseweed', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in oldfields and other disturbed areas as a weed (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: worm borers found in stem of plant obtained and used as live fish bait (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2004; information learned from family and friends and not necessarily traditional Miami culture);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '2004', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(96, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMDM3ODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Cornus florida L.', 'Dogwood', 'Cornaceae (Dogwood)', '(akanteemi≈°i)', NULL, '1. Occurs in woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: wood used for arrows. \"bird arrows with blunt points made out of dogwood wood and hickory wood, both which sink in the water\" (Dunn ca. 1909, 1778dw): 2. TECHNOLOGY: Peoria arrows were made of hickory and dogwood (Gatschet ca. 1895:2661, from Frank Beaver);                                                                                             3. TECHNOLOGY: arrows made of wood of dogwood tree. \"nah\'hpikaxkwi kaneki, dogwood, arrow made of it\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1357);', NULL, NULL, '1. Allouez remarked about the Illinois\' use of bow and arrow: \"They ordinarily carry only the warclub, bow, and a quiver full of arrows, which they discharge so adroitly and quickly, that men armed with guns, have hardly time to raise them to the shoulder. They also carry a large buckler made of skins of wild cattle; which is arrow-proof, and covers the whole body\" (Allouez 1677, from Shea 1903:78); 2. Dunn lists the Miami-Illinois term \"akandamindji\" for dogwood (Dunn Report p103, Wea) and \"ikalwi\" for dogwood tree (ca. 1900:1779dw, Peoria); 3. Gatschet lists the Miami-Illinois term \"ikalwi\" for the dogwood tree or bush  (ca. 1895:2661) as well as \"neehpikaahkwi kaneki\" for dogwood, literally translated as tree/shrub with red legs [bark] (ca. 1895:1357); 4. Father Gravier listed the Miami-Illinois term \"iihkalomi?i\", indicating the dogwood tree (ca. 1700);', 'FALSE', 'iihkalwi (Dunn), iihkalomisi (Gr), See Rel. Info.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1909', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(97, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo2OTEzMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Cornus stolonifera L.', 'Red osier dogwood, Red willow', 'Cornaceae (Dogwood)', 'neehpikaahkwi', NULL, '1. Found along streambanks and in moist woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. CUSTOMS: inner bark used for killikinnick [=tobacco and dogwood] (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. CUSTOMS: dried bark of the osier willow scraped fine (George Winter 000); 2. CUSTOMS: inner bark used for tobacco mixture. \"napikakki, red willow (inner bark used for killinkinnick)\" (Dunn ca. 1900:5378dw); 3. UNKNOWN: \"nepikaxkwi, naphpikaxkwi, red willow, a bush or growth called so from the color of the bark (kaxkwi); about 5-7 feet high\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1588dw);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(98, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyODgxMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Corylus americana Walter.', 'American hazelnut bush', 'Betulaceae (Birch)', 'pahkihteenhsaahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist or dry woods and thickets throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. (FOOD): hazel bush (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 2. UNKNOWN: \"pakita\'nsaxkwa\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1745); 3. FOOD: nuts gathered for food (See entry #1, in ecological information) (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 4. (FOOD): \"ketenzuqe, hazel bush\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer,from  Mongosa); 5. (FOOD: hazel nut (Dunn ca. 1900);  6. (FOOD): hazel nut (Fox 000); 7. (FOOD): hazel nut (Munsee 000);', NULL, '1. Jim Strack mentions the declining abundance of hazelnut and butternut trees. \"A lot of hazelnut around [then]\" \"they don\'t seem to grow very good any more, the hazelnuts do, likewise with butternuts\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', '1. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period (Bush 2003); 2. Human-charred hazelnut nutshell and nutmeat material were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181): 3. Other Miami terms for hazel nut include \"pakitansaxkwi\" and \"pxkixtansaxkwi\" (possibly from Gatschet ca. 1895), and \"pakita\'nsaxkwi, hazel bush, all of the genus Corlyus\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1745);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'pahkihteenhsi (fruit)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '~1850', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(99, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo3NTA4MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Crataegus sp.', 'Red Haw, Hawthorn', 'Rosaceae', NULL, NULL, '1. Most species in this genus found in  disturbed sites or seral communities, including oldfields, fencerows and thickets (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: berries gathered and eaten. \"Oh my we liked redhaws\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999); 2. FOOD: fruits eaten raw or made into jellies and pies (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. Cratageus spp. Are most commonly called \'hawthorns\', some are black, called black hawthorns, and some are red, called redhaws. Blackhaws are usually referring to Viburnum prunifolium, not Cratageus spp. Hawthorn uses include Meskwaki (drug, food/fruit), Ojibway (food/fruits, drug/root), Potawatomi (drug/berry, food/berry) (author\'s note, 7/2006);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1999', '2005', NULL, '(7.02.06)--Dave Costa:  Speaking of haws, while I was continuining to plow thru Dunn\'s fieldnotes  this weekend, I noticed that he gave the following form: <wawik??piminj??kwi> \'haw bush\'. (He doesn\'t give any further description of the semantics. I assume this is exactly how his speaker glossed the word). This is presumably /waawiikapimi?aahkwi/, which looks like the \'basswood\' word with an extra reduplicated syllable /waa-/ at the front, plus that semiredundant /-aahkwi/ at the end. I\'ve never noticed this word before, and no one else seems to have it, but there\'s no reason to doubt its validity. However, I have two questions, both of which you\'ve probably already thought of:\n1) what exactly is a \'haw bush\'?\n2) why would a name for the \'haw bush\' be a derivative of the name for the basswood tree? Similar appearance? Similar uses?\n(7.03.06)--Mike Gonella: Dave, Not much to go on here, botanically. Haws indicate either a hawthorn/redhaw (Crataegus sp.) or blackhaw (Viburnum prunifolium). The\nonly thing I can think of is that the blackhaw is more truly a bush than the redhaw, whi', NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(100, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo4MTA2NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Cryptotaenia canadensis (L.) DC.', 'Wild chervil, honewort', 'Apiaceae (Carrot)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: roots used to cure eye problems. \"The root of the wild chervil is marvelous for illnesses of the eyes, by dropping in the eye water in which this root has steeped, in the month of May when the vine is in sap\" (Anonymous 1724:163B, \"La Racine Cerfeuil Savage est merveilleuse pour le maux des yeux, en faisant de gouter dans l\'oiel l\'eau dans la quelle a rompre la Racine, dans le mois de May quand la Vigne est en Seve\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004; the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1724', '1724', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(101, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyMzI1Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Cucumis melo L.', 'Melon', 'Cucurbitatceae (Gourd)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in dry soils and along railways in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: melons cultivated. \"They also sow beans and melons, which are excellent, and especially those whose seed is red\" (Marquette 1673:210, from Thwaites 1903:652); 2. FOOD: melons cultivated. \"melons grow there [in lands inhabited by tribes along Lake Michigan, possibly including Miami-Illinois peoples] which have a juice no less agreeable than refreshing\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:113); 3. FOOD: Human-charred material that closely matched a modern cantaloupe, suggesting some type of Cucumis sp., was recoverd from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181):', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1673', '~1850', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(102, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDozNDAxOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Cucurbita maxima Duch.', 'Hubbard squash', 'Cucurbitaceae (Gourd)', '(kihkalapootiki)', NULL, '1. Agricultural crop;', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"kixkalapotiki, hubbard squash\" (Hockett 1938:259); 2. FOOD: squashes cultivated. \"Their Squashes are not of the best; they dry them in the sun, to eat them during The winter and spring\" (Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:351); 3. FOOD: two types of pumpkins, which may have been squashes, were identified as being cultivated . \"Common pumpkins and Illinois (pumpkins)\" (Potier ca. 1740, from Toupin 1996:278, \". . . Citrouilles communes et illinoises\");  4. FOOD: squashes dried in the sun for winter and spring food source (Kenton 1925:343, The Jesuit Relations);', NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that squash was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1674', '1938', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
(103, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDoyNTc5OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Cucurbita pepo L.', 'Wild pumpkin, squash (not hubbard)', 'Cucurbitaceae (Gourd)', 'eemihkwaani', NULL, '1. Occurs on dry soils in various habitats (Gleason & Cronquist 1991); 2. C. foetidissima (wild pumpkin) occurs in dry soils in western and potentially in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: \"a\'mkwani\", wild pumpkin (Gatschet ca. 1895); 2. FOOD: \"amkwani\", pumpkin (Dunn ca. 1900:3850); 3. FOOD: cultivated, dried, cooked with meat and corn and eaten. \"There are abundant and excellent pumpkins. They have a mode of drying them that is not common to all the nations of this region by which they keep from one year to the next. They scrape the rind well, and take out all the inside, and cut them into slices full circle and an inch thick. They let them wither for a day in the air, after which they tie them together, putting as many as five pumpkins together in this way. They expose them to the sun for several days, which dries them out to such a degree that they break like a turnip. They cook this with meat and Indian corn. It is a great treat among them. The French always make a liberal provision of this\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:345; \"Des citrouilles en quantite qui sont excelentes elles ont une mainere de les faire secher, ce que n\'ont point toutes les autres nations de ces contrees icy leqlles. elles concervent d\'une annee a l\'autre elles grattent bien la peau et ostent tout le dedans et les coupent par tranches de l\'epaisseur d\'un poulce de toute leur rondeur Et les laissent fauer un jour a l\'air apres quoy elles le Lassent l\'une avec l\'autre Et mettent d maniere jusqu\'a cinq citrouilles Ensemble Et les Exposent au soleil plussieurs jours ou elles sechent d\'une maniere quelles se cassent comme un navet, ou en met cuire parmy la Viande et le Bled d\'inde mesle c\'est un grand regal parmy eux, Les francois en font toujours bonne provision,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 4. FOOD: Barbara Mullin\'s mother, Julia Lankford, placed pumpkins in a pressure cooker and prepared them for caning. Her grandmother (000) and great grandmother dried pumpkins for storage (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 2(4):10, 1999); 5. FOOD: squash/pumpkins brought to missionaries for eating (Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:372); 6. FOOD: \"powdered part/piece of meat, pumpking, etc.\" (Gravier ca.1700:254.09, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter); 7. FOOD: wild/domesticated pumpkins grown (Interview with Rose Carver, Tyner 1968); 8. FOOD: two types of pumpkins cultivated and eaten. \"Common pumpkins and Illinois (pumpkins)\" (Potier ca. 1740, from Toupin 1996:278, \". . . Citrouilles communes et illinoises\"); 9. FOOD: gourds, or \"pompions\" [pumpkin?] grown as a food crop (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112); 10. FOOD: Human-charred cucurbit material was recoverd from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River. Flower scars and seeds on material recovered suggest varieties of an acorn squash, Cuburbita pepo (Bush 1996:181); 11. FOOD: cultivated and eaten. Has yellowish skin and orange flesh (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);      12. FOOD: domestic pumpkins used in contemporary griddle-cake recipe (Aatotankiki myaamiaki 2003 6(1):8);', '1. Gourds, watermelons and sunflowers are first sprouted in a hot-bed, then transplanted into a crop field (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1921:112);', NULL, '1.  Barbara\'s recipe for dried pumpkins: Cut ripe pumpkin in rings, remove the peeling hang on a stick before the fire near enough to dry slowly. This may be stored until ready for use. To prepare, it should be washed and cooked any way you like pumpkin. The Indians often ate it dried (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 2(4):10, 1999); 2. Human-charred cucurbit material was recoverd from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181): 3. Miami-Illinois terms for pumpkin also include the Miami word \"emmkwani\" for squash or pumpkin and the Peoria word  \"eemihkookani\" or \"haemihkwa?ani\" for pumpkin (Hockett1938), \"eemihkookani\", \"rerequne, amkokune\", for gourds or pumpkins  (Kerr 1835, from Wea Primer), and the documented the phrase \"keekeeshondoa haamuhkwaunau\" meaning \'cut up the pumpkins\' in Miami-Illinois(Ts 000?);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'eemihkookani, (rel info)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1682', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
