(107, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMDo1NDI0OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Diospyros virginiana L.', 'Persimmon tree', 'Ebenaceae (Ebony)', 'pyaakimi≈°aahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs mostly in dry-soiled woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"piakimindjakwi\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3694dw); 2. UNKNOWN: \"I remove the crown [sepals] from a persimmon, the stem from fruit\" (Gravier ca.1700:253.13, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter); 3. FOOD: Barbara Mullin\'s mother, Julia Lankford,  gathered wild persimmons in the woods around the homestead at Timber Hill (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 2(4):10, 1999); 4. FOOD: persimmon pudding recipe (Karen and Daryl Baldwin 2003--see attachment); 5. FOOD: used as a snack food when in the woods (Rafert 1996:182); 6. FOOD: used for jelly by her grandmother Geboe [?] (Interview with Peggy McCord, 2004); 7. FOOD: gathered for food (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 8. MEDICINAL: fruit made into a paste which is baked into loaves. \"The Indians make a paste of the fruit, which they bake into loaves of the thickness of a man\'s finger, and of the consistence of a dried pear. The taste seems at first somewhat disagreeable, but people are easily accustomed to it. It is very nourishing, and a sovereign remedy, as they pretend, against a looseness and bloody-flux\" (Charlevoix 1683-1761:223, from Kellogg 1923:208); 9. FOOD: fruits dried. \". . . When the arrived home they had left at the place where he had been drying his wife persimmons . . .\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:manuscript 1556, from Sarah Wadsworth; \"napiatchi manahwilitchi; niaha da passamelidci wiwali piakimini\"); 10. UNKNOWN: \"piakiminja\", persimmon (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', '1. harvesting and preparation for use: \"They must fall to the ground to be ripe.  Not quit ripe persimmons taste terrible.  This time of year (early October) for southeast Indiana is when they start to fall.  Check under the tree every day and collect.  Wash and take out seeds.  I take seeds out by hand. It\'s a messy job but very effective.  You can then run the remains of the seed through a food mill to make a pulp and eliminate the skin.  This is the pulp used in the recipe.  The pulp can be frozen.\" (Karen and Daryl Baldwin, 2003--see attachment for pudding recipe);', NULL, '1. The Shawnee collected this plant for food (Clark 1933); 2. The common name persimmon is of Algonquian origin and is taken from the Delaware word pasimenan, meaning dried fruit (McPherson 1977:162, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 3. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that persimmons were utilized as a food resource by Late Woodland (800 A.D to 1300 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003); 4. Human-charred persimmon material was recovered from excavations at an early 19th century Miami village site (Bush 1996:181); 5. Jim Strack recalled seeing a recipe in a cookbook when he was growing up that called for persimmons to flavor the meat of a opposum (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', 'TRUE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'pyaakimini (fruit)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1683', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:20', '2017-09-19 22:48:20')
