(116, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyNDQ1OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Fraxinus nigra Marshall.', 'Black ash, Swamp Ash', 'Oleaceae (Olive)', '(peepihkwilakiki)', '1. Also known as swamp ash (Dunn ca. 1900);', '1. Occurs in wet woods, frequently flooded areas, and swamps mostly in northern areas of eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991), perhaps more abundant in southern portions of eastern Miami lands prior to agricultural drainage (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: bark used for baskets. \"papkwilakiki, swamp ash, bark used for baskets\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. Philip Alexis (Potawatomi Pokagon) started making black ash baskets in 1975. He co-oped with Mike Daugherty--it is the job of the men to get the wood. Some basketmakers in Pokagon band became famous, incuding Julia Wesaw and Agnes Rapp. Frank Bush (Pot. Pok.) also made/makes baskets, gathering wood every 2-3 months, has a basket making class (Kohn 1997); 2. Dried exudation (sap) of Fraxinus ornus used as a mild laxative in doses of 15 gm (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.)', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(117, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5MjYyOToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Fraxinus quadrangulata Michx.', 'Blue ash', 'Oleaceae (Olive)', '(saakikase)', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist woods in eastern and western Miami lands 1. Occurs on rich, moist soil throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"saki\'kaca, white or blue ash\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. UNKNOWN: \"sakikansia, blue ash tree\" (Gatschet 1895:2057); 3. TECHNOLOGY: ash wood was best for bows and spears (Carter 1987:17, 2ndy source);', NULL, NULL, '1. Miami name also refers to white ash (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. Dried exudation (sap) of Fraxinus ornus used as a mild laxative in doses of 15 gm (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1987 - 2ndy (1895)', '1987 - 2ndy', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(118, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTozNDEzMDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Fraxinus sp. L.', 'Ash', 'Oleaceae', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs mostly in moist or wet woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: leaves used (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '2003', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(119, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyNzQwNjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Gaylussacia frondosa (L.) Torr. & Gray ex Torr.', 'Huckleberry', 'Ericaceae (Heath)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in sandy soils or cold swamps (Small 1903); 2. Occurs in moist woods or thickets (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: fruits gathered around swampy areas, \"buckbrush swamp wetlands\" and eaten (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:103);', NULL, NULL, '1. Frank Bush (Potawatomi Pokagon) has knowledge of huckleberry marshes and harvesting of huckleberries traditionally by his band. He stopped collecting in the 1940\'s and 50\'s until recently. The Kay-boom-a-kay pow wow is a celebration of the huckleberry harvest (Kohn 1997);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1989', '1989', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(120, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo1MDc5OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Gleditsia tricanthos  L.', 'Honey locust', 'Caesalpinioideae (Caesalpinia)', 'akaawins≈°aahkwa', '1. \"There is another tree which has branches filled with thorns as long as one\'s fingers. It also has pods which are not so big nor so long; they are full of little beans which are very hard.\" (Pease 1934:348, Deliette 1721);', '1. Occurs in rich, moist woods in the southern portions of eastern, and throughout western Miami lands, and cultivated in many other areas (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MATERIAL:  \"At night most of the men, seated like dogs on mats of round reeds, play with straws. For markers they use the little beans which I have mentioned, which grow on the thorny trees,\" \"They have perhaps five or six hundred of these beans, some of which they stake on each play . . . \" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:351 & 352; \"et la nuit comme des Chiens la plus part assis sur des nattes de joncs ronds jouent avec des pailles, pour leurs marques ils se servent de ces petites fevves don??t je viens de parler que ces arbres charges d\'epines raportent,\"ils ont peut estre 5. ou 600. de ces fevves don??t ils mettent une partie a chaque coup,\"translation from French to English by Pease); 2. UNKNOWN: \"kawinjakwa, honey locust, thorn tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900);; ', NULL, NULL, '1. Algonquians play the game of straws with seeds, probably taken from the Honey locust tree or Kentucky coffee-tree. \"Sometimes they play [the game of straws] with seeds which grow on the trees, which clsoely resemble little beans\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:97); 2. The Miami-Illinois term \"akaawia\" means thorn (Dunn ca. 1900:4902);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1721', '1721 (1900)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(121, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo0MzYwOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Gnaphalium obtusifolium L.', 'Sweet everlasting', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', '(peetihsahki) (also for peppermint)', NULL, '1. Common native weedy species occurring in dry soils and open areas in woods (Steyermark 1963, Small 1903);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. CUSTOMS: the old Miamis use a mixture of dried, leaves of common everlasting (Gnaphalium polycephalum), which the Weas call pawakiki, and the Miamis patsaki (odorous) with tobacco and red cedar. They are dried and rubbed in the hands until a fine powder, and thrown to the \'manito\' [the Great Spirit] (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. CUSTOMS: mixed with tobacco for smoking (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999); 3. CUSTOMS: living plant placed at Miami family gravesite in Francis Slocum cemetary (Gonella 2004, Field Notes);', NULL, NULL, '1. Peppermint, Mentha piperita, was also added to this mixture sometimes, and was called \'patsakgi\' (Gatschet ca. 1895);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1900', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(122, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDY4Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Gymnocladus dioicus (L.) K. Koch', 'Kentucky coffee tree', 'Caesalpiniaceae (Caesalpinia)', '≈°oo≈°ookwalalaakaneemi≈°aahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich, moist woods, uncommon (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: \"ch8ch8c8inagan8injaki\", beans from the fruit are used to play [games] with (Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38, from Costa 2005:118); 2. FOOD: seeds eaten by William Francis Hale (Interview with George Dorin, 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. Algonquians play the game of straws with seeds, probably taken from the Honey locust tree or Kentucky coffee-tree. \"Sometimes they play [the game of straws] with seeds which grow on the trees, which clsoely resemble little beans\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:97);', 'FALSE', '?oo?ookwalalaakani (seed), ?oo?ookwalalaakanioaahkwa (tree);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'ch8ch8c8inanganaki (berry-Pinet)', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1696', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(123, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyODQ4MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Gyromitra brunnea Under.', 'False morel', 'Basidiomycetes (Mushroom)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: mushrooms eaten. \" . . . Godfroy\'s belief was that they did not use poke, mushrooms, or wild lettuce, until they learned to eat them from the whites. He was probably wrong as to this, as the instruction concerning the use of native plants came the other way\" (Dunn 1919); 2. FOOD: gyromitras eaten. \". . .the Miamis eat the morels and the two large gyromitras--esculenta and brunnea. They do not eat puff-balls, believing that they cause dropsy--in fact the name given to them, pa-sa\'-to-wa-ka-ni, means \"thing that causes dropsy\".  The edible sponge mushrooms, which they used, as mentioned, are called mi-no-sa\'-ka-I, which is the name given to tripe (Dunn 1919);', NULL, NULL, '1. False morels are difficult to mistake for true morels. They produce a toxin gyromitrin, which volatizes upon cooking, although caution should be employed in eating this fungus (Money 2002);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1919', '1919', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(124, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo1Mzk2NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Gyromitra esculenta (Pers. ex. Fr.) Fr.', 'False morel', 'Basidiomycetes (Mushroom)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: gyromitras eaten. \". . .the Miamis eat the morels and the two large gyromitras--esculenta and brunnea. They do not eat puff-balls, believing that they cause dropsy--in fact the name given to them, pa-sa\'-to-wa-ka-ni, means \"thing that causes dropsy\".  The edible sponge mushrooms, which they used, as mentioned, are called mi-no-sa\'-ka-I, which is the name given to tripe (Dunn 1919);', NULL, NULL, '1. False morels are difficult to mistake for true morels. They produce a toxin gyromitrin, which volatizes upon cooking, although caution should be employed in eating this fungus (Money 2002);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1919', '1919', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(125, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5NDExNjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Hedeoma pulegioides (L.) Purs.', 'False Pennyroyal', 'Lamiaceae (Mint)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in upland woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: tea used as a blood thinner or conditioner, similar to sassafras (Interviews with Miami elders 1977-1992, Rafert 1992:45);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1977', '1977', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(126, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyOTQxOToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Helianthus tuberosus L.', 'Jerusalem artichoke', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', 'oonsaapeehkateeki', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist soils and disturbed areas (fencerows) throughout easstern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: tubers eaten, called \"Indian potatoes\" and \"the Jerusalem artichoke (Helianthus tuberosa) appears to me to meet his (Perrot\'s) description more nearly than any other plant, and its tubers were eaten by the Indians\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Dunn 1919); 2. FOOD: \"As soon as they found out about it, they used the Jerusalem artichoke, but they didn\'t have \'em native here in this country.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:97-98); 3. FOOD: \"They also store up onions, as big as Jerusalem artichokes, which they find in the prairies, and which I find better than all the other roots. They are sugary and pleasing to the palate. They are cooked like macopines\" (Pease 1934:347, Deliette 1721; \"Elles amassent aussi des oignons gros comme des Topiniamboures, qu\'elles trouvent dans les prairies que je trouve meilleures que toutes les autres Racines, ils sont sucre et font plaisir a manger on les fait cuire comme les Macopines,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 4. FOOD: sunflowers are grown as a crop, probably indicating the jerusalem artichoke (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112); 5. FOOD/MEDICINAL: oil from the seeds is used for rubbing on the skin. \"The Indians make no other use of the turnsoles, but to extract from them an oil with which they rub themselves: this is more commonly drawn from the seeds than from the root of this plant. This root differs little from what we call in France topinambours or apples of the earth [this plant is probably jerusalem artichoke]\" (Charlevoix 1682-1761:125, from Kellogg 1923:115); 6. FOOD: tubers eaten. \'onzapakataki\", \"indian potatoes\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 7. FOOD: tubers gathered, cooked and eaten (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', '1. \"But as soon as they found out about them they cultivated them and used them.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 2. Sunflowers, along with watermelons and gourds are first sprouted in a hot-bed and then transplanted into crop fields (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112)', NULL, '1. The Shawnee collected this plant for food (Clark 1993); 2. Many Indian tribes of North America used the tubers of this plant for food. Sometimes, archaeologists are able to locate the sites of old Indian villages by the presence of large stands of Jerusalem artichoke plants. Spanish explorers brought this plant back to Europe where it was cultivated and sold as \'girasol\', the spanish word for sunflower. The English incorrectly tranformed \'girasol\' to Jerusalem, and the \'artichoke\' part of the name comes presumably from the tuber\'s taste (McPherson 1977:173-174: 2ndy source without primary source citation); 3. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that sunflowers [including a variety of Helianthus spp.] were either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, '(yellow flower)', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(127, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo0MzU5Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Hemerocallis fulva (L.) L.', 'Day-lily', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: flowers, flower buds or petals fried and eaten. Buds eaten raw as a snack (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '2005', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(128, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMToyMDAxMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Hierochloe odorata L. Beauv.', 'Sweet grass', 'Poaceae (Grass)', 'none (contemporary use only)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. CUSTOMS/MEDICINAL: the chief smokes a sick person for healing. \"the smoking ceremony we think it kind of purifies us  . . . If you\'re sick or anything the chief will come out and smoke you which we feel like it helps you get well . . .we use to make the smoke is cedar and cedar is a cleanser . . green cedar to get more smoke, we use tobacco, tobacco is a purifier and then we use sage and its for medicinal [purposes] . . . there was some sweetgrass mixed with the combination of sage and tobacco uh and the cedar\" (Interview with Chuck Wade by Brant Hall, MTO Headquarters, Miami, OK, 6/21/99, MTO Archives); 2. MEDICINAL: component of medicine bag. \". . . cedar is like a purification, um, the sweet grass . . . corn all of those have a something, I\'m not sure what they all are. Its just medicine. Everything you would need to sustain you here or here after, is that little tiny portion, is in that bag\" (Interview with Barbara Mullin, Carlson 1996); 3. CUSTOMS: current Nation drum has tobacco and sweetgrass tied all around the Nation drum. Gary\'s personal habit is to tie a sweetgrass turtle to drum. Use of sweetgrass with drum learned from the Ojibway (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2004); CUSTOMS: used for smoking, like cedar. \". . that\'s the only thing she ever used it for, kind of a purifying, just like we used cedar\" \". . . it was just loose and she\'d just tied a string around it. I didn\'t see any in Oklahoma. She got that whenever she came back here [Indiana]. If they came back here to visit or something why then she\'d come back with some of that. And she would just . . .set it on the stove sometimes, you know, we had a wood stove and she\'d put it on the top of that like she did cedar. And I guess it was medicine as far as it purified the air and everything. It made a smoke. Yeah, just like the cedar does\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999);', '1. The sweet grass with the red stem was preferred (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999);', NULL, '1. Only two plants, wild tobacco and red cedar, were used traditionally as ceremonial plants by the Miami. Contemporary uses of other plants in ceremonies, including white sage (Salvia apiana, from western U.S.) and sweetgrass (Hierochloe odorata) have been acquired often from the pan-Indian movement of modern times (author\'s note and pers. comm. with Baldwin 2005);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1999', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(129, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo3MjEyNzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Hordeum pusillum Nutt.', 'Little barley', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, '1. A native weedy species occurring in moist areas including oldfields, pastures, other human-disturbed areas (Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Small 1903);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. A relative of the cultivated barley (H. vulgare), Little barley is extremely abundant in some areas (Thieret 2001); 2. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that Little barley was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" by indigenous peoples during the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. through 1450 A.D.) (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
(130, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMTo5MTA4MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Hydrastis canadensis L.', 'Golden seal', 'Ranunculaceae (Buttercup)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in rich, deep woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MEDICINAL: root dried and pounded into a powder was used to relieve pain and heal membranes and cuts (Interviews with Miami elders 1977-1992, Rafert 1992:45); 2. TECHNOLOGY: collected and dried, then sold for pharmaceutical use (Rafert 1996:182); 2. MEDICINAL: carefully used as an unspecified medicine, with the potential to cause abortion (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds, and Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1977', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:21', '2017-09-19 22:48:21')
