(132, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo4OTM0NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ipomoea batata L.', 'Sweet potato', 'Solanaceae (Nightshade)', 'keekanwakoosia or kiinwaahkoohsia', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: eaten. \"Kekanwa kuthiaki\", or \"kinwa kussia\"  or \"paxkussia\" are the old Miami language terms for wild potatoes, also called batate. Now the shortened term \'kussia\' is used for commercial sweet potatoes (Gatschet ca. 1895:756 & 1753); 2. FOOD: eaten. \"wawikapakosia, sweet potato\" (Dunn ca. 1900:4734-35dw);', NULL, NULL, '1. Sweet potatoes a traditional food (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 2(2):12, 1999); 2. Checked in Small\'s Flora of the Southeastern U.S.(1903), Gleason and Cronquist (1991), and Coulter\'s Flowering Plants and Ferns of Indiana (1899), none of which mention a \'sweet potato\' in the index or within the potato family, nor a \'batate\' in the index;', 'FALSE', 'paahkoohsia (Gat)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1895', '1900', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(133, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMDI3Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ipomoea pandurata (L.) G.F.W. Mey. (rel. ref.)', 'Wild potato, Man-of-the-Earth', 'Solanaceae (Nightshade)', 'kiinwaahkoosia', NULL, '1. Ipomaea pandurata: dry woods and thickets; Helianthus tuberosus: moist soils and waste places (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: tubers eaten. [Perrot\'s \"Indian potatoes\" probably refers to this species or Jerusalem artichoke] (Perrot 1680-1718, from Dunn 1919); 2. FOOD: gathered in wet prairies and eaten. \"paneekee, wild potato, these are found in abundance in the wet prairies throughout the country and are gathered in hoeing time (June). They are easily boiled and when they wish to change the color the Indians throw a few leaves of the soft maple [into the cooking kettle] which turns them black\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64-65); 3. FOOD: waupeeseepina is the white potato, found growing in low prairies and the potatoe portion similar in appearance and taste to the commericial potato of the times (ca. 1938). Easily cooked and very good tasting, these roots are used much by the Miami, particularly when food is seasonally scarce. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65); 4. FOOD: wild potatoes are gathered in prairies, cooked and eaten. \"pa\'na, pena . . . Refers to one or more species of onion-like or turnip-shaped nutritious bulbs growing extensively upon the western prairies. This \"pomme blanche\" as named by the \"coureurs des bois\" look dark and are sweeter than our Irish potatoes. They cook in six hours and are usually called by these Indians [the Miami] nalauxki pa\'naki\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1809);                                                                                                                                          5. FOOD: the archaic term for this [sweet potato] fruit is kinwa kussia, pl. kinwa(ki) kussiaki \"long potato.\" The archaic term is still used by many people  (Gatschet ca. 1895);  6. FOOD: kenkanwa kuthiaki sweet potatoes, archaic for batates, now kussia (Gatschet ca. 1895); 7. FOOD: paxkussia, kussia /-aki pl. sweet potato, better called batate. The archaic name given to this fruit is kinwa kussia long fruit (Gatschet ca. 1895);', '1. nimic8ah8aki = \"I found some roots, potatoes, for example digging with a stick etc.\" (Gravier ca.1700:295.15);', NULL, '1. The Miami-Illinois term \"panick\" means potatoes (Kerr 1835:359, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa), \"paniki axki\" means potato field (Gatschet ca. 1895:69) and \"ahpeniikiinsa\" means little potatoes (Dunn ca. 1900:3788dw). Ts [000] recorded the term \"paanarkee\" as indicating potato in Miami-Illinois (ts000); 2. The Miami term \"ahpena\" means the cultivated, domesticated garden potato, Solanum tuberosum in contemporary times, but  originally used for another edible tuber [author\'s note]; 3. According to the University of Michigan at Dearborn, Native American Ethnobotany Database (Moerman), Ipomoea pandurata is widely used by indigenous groups across North America, with most uses being medicinal, and only two records, one by the Cherokee, as a food/starvation food source. This species is the best guess at what was harvested in the summer (not oonsaapeekatiki, since this is a fall/winter/early spring harvest) and considered  \'ahpena\' (author\'s note, 5.6.06);', 'FALSE', 'nalauxki pa\'naki (Gat), paneekee (Trow)', NULL, 'what is dug up', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'ahpena (also for cultivated potato)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(134, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNjkyNzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Iris versicolor L.', 'Blue flag iris', 'Iridaceae (Iris)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in marshes, swamps, meadows and shores (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: roots chewed as a remedy for mouth sores (Rafert 1992:43, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1992', '1992', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(135, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjozMTIyNToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Iva annua L. (I. ciliata)', 'Sumpweed or Marsh Elder', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in moist soils or swamps (Small 1903) and waste places (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that sumpweed was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Remains of seeds of sumpweed do not appear again after 700 A.D. in Indiana archaeological sites (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(136, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjozMjQyNDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Jeffersonia diphylla (L.) Pers.', 'Rheumatism root', 'Berberidaceae (Barberry)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in rich woods, especially on calcareous soils (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: part of recipe for rheumatism. \". . . A quart of whiskey two handfuls red pepper two oz casteel soap half oz salt hartshorn the same of laudnaum and as much jimweed or L. rheumatism root as some term it as you can hold in your hand. Bruise and boil it in a quart water until it is bitter. The stronger the better. Strain it and add the ingredients. Stew them till soft and bottle for use. While using the above, ironweed tea or bitters to cleans the blood\" (Hackley 000);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '? Hackley', '? Hackley', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(137, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNTA2Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Juglans cinerea L.', 'Butternut tree', 'Juglandaceae (Walnut)', 'kiino≈°i≈°i', '1. Butternuts are oblong, longer than a walnut. \"Butternut has a shell that looks something like a walnut but they\'re smaller . . .They\'re long, almost twice as long as a walnut . . They\'re oblong\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', '1. Occurs on rich, moist soils throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"sinkisisa, butternut tree\"  (Hockett 1938:043); 2. UNKNOWN: \"kinoci\'ci, butternut tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900:943dw); 3. FOOD: nuts gathered for food (See entry #1, in ecological information) (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 4.  MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred butternut/walnut timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184);  5. UNKNOWN: \"kin8chichi8ingi\", butternut (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, '1. Jim Strack mentions the declining abundance of hazelnut and butternut trees. \"A lot of hazelnut around [then]\" \"they don\'t seem to grow very good any more, the hazelnuts do, likewise with butternuts. I don\'t know whether they [people] going after the wood of the butternut trees or what cause it but the butternut just seemed to die out. The butternuts you\'d pretty near had to fight with the squirrels to get \'em, cause they really, I mean they really ate the butternuts. If one falls out, . . .if one drop out of a tree there were a couple of squirrels watching . . . \" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', '1. Also known as \'sinkisisa\' (Hockett 1938); 2. McPherson wrote, \"The Potawatomie Indians drank a tea made from the inner bark of the butternut for stomach upsets\" (1977:57, 2ndy source without primary source citation);', 'FALSE', 'siinki?i?a (Hock); kin?chichi?ingi (Pinet)', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '~1850 (1696)', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(138, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo0ODI0OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Juglans nigra L.', 'Black walnut tree', 'Juglandaceae (Walnut)', 'ayoonseekaahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs on rich, moist soil throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"mialwa\'hki, walnut tree\", \"ayoonseekaahkwi\", called ayunsaki because it stains the hands yellow (Gatschet ca. 1895:1184 & 48); 2. UNKNOWN:Peoria and Miami term (Hockett 1938:303); 2. MATERIAL: wood used to make Lacrosse stick. \"They make the [racket][ Pease\'s brackets] of a stick of walnut, about three feet long, which they bend half way, making the end come within a foot of the other end which serves them for a handle. To keep it in this shape they fasten a buffalo sinew to the curved end, which, as I have already said, they fasten about a foot from the end which serves as a handle. They lace the interior with more buffalo sinew so that the ball, which is a knot of wood of the size of a tennis ball, cannot pass through.\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:341; \"ils les font d\'un brin de Noyer, d\'environ 3. pieds de long qu\'ils courbent a moitie, et font venir le bout vis a vis pres d\'un pied de l\'autre bout, qui leur sert de manche, pour la faire tenir dans cet estat, ils attachent du nerf de Bouef au bout courbe, qu\'ils attachent comme j\'ay deja dit pres d\'un pied de ce qui sert de manche, ils lacent le dedans avec encore du nerf en sorte que la Boulle qui est un noeud de Bois de la grosseur d\'une balle de jeu de paume ne passe au travers,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 3. CUSTOMS: lacrosse played at the funeral of a man who liked lacrosse (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:360;  \"Si le mort aimoit le jeu de la Crosse les parens feroient crosser les Villages l\'un cotre l\'autre,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 4. MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred butternut/walnut timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184); 5. (UNKNKOWN): \"meuluahke, walnut tree\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer,from  Mongosa); 5. FOOD: nuts gathered for food (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 6. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 7. UNKNOWN: nut meat eaten (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 8. TECHNOLOGY/MEDICINAL: used to make a black dye, and stop looseness or serve as an emetic. \"The forests are full of walnut-trees [in Miami country], resembling those of Canada, and their roots have several properties not observed in the others. They are very soft, and their bark affords a black dye; but their principal use consists in medicine. They stop a looseness, and furnish an excellent emetick\" (Charlevoix 1683-1761:242, from Kellogg 1923:225); 9. FOOD: \"walnuts one can\'t tell if there are nutmeats inside\" (Gravier ca. 1700:253.08, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter 2003);', NULL, '1. Jim Strack mentions the declining abundance of hazelnut and butternut trees. \"A lot of hazelnut around [then]\" \"they don\'t seem to grow very good any more, the hazelnuts do, likewise with butternuts\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', '1. Walnut timbers used to construct early sections of home of Mary Wells Wolcott, in 1827--one of the oldest Miami homesteads still standing (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 4(4):3, 2001); 2. McPherson wrote, \"The Indians [undescribed tribe] boiled the walnut kernels in water and skimmed off the oil to use as a sweet-flavored cooking oil. Both Indians and pioneers used the husks around the shells along with the bark to produce a brown dye\" (1977:56, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 3. Human-charred black walnut material recovered from excavations at an early 19th century Miami village site (Bush 1996:181); 4. The Miami-Illinois term aayoonsee-\" Hockett (1938:303) refers  to the walnut tree fruit (Baldwin); as do \"ayunsaki\" or \"eyunsaki\"  which mean to stain hands yellow (Gatschet a. 1895:1191, 47), because walnuts stain the hands yellow when handled; 5. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that nuts (preserved as nutshell, which represent walnut, hickory and hazelnut species) were an important wild food resource utilized by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D. through approximately 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana. Results of these studies indicate that nut use declined over the Late Woodland period (prior to 700 A.D. to 1450 A.D.), probably due to increased cultivation of fall-maturing crops, like corn, and conflicts with gathering nuts during this same time period (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', 'myaalweehki', NULL, 'stain hands yellow tree (the fruits-rel info)', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'ayoonseeki (fruit)', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1683', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(139, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMzE1NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Juniperus virginiana L.', 'Eastern red cedar', 'Cupressaceae (Cypress)', '≈°inkwaahkwa', NULL, '1. Occurs on dry, especially calcareous, and other soils throughout the eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: red cedar, black locust and mulberry tree wood used for shorter war bows (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria); 2. CUSTOMS:  prior to the body being taken to the cemetary, an elder or the Chief goes to the cemetery to smoke the ground with cedar and tobacco. The cedar is evergreen, and signifies continuing life and the tobacco helps prayers ascend to the Great Spirit (Dunn 1919, Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 3(1):3, 2000);  3. CUSTOMS: funeral--if the ceremony is performed at the gravesite then the leader will cast cedar to the four directions and into the grave and over the coffin. After the ceremony friends and family gather at a relatives house. If the deceased smoked cigarettes, relatives will place cigarettes in containers around the area and each person should smoke one of the cigarettes as an honoring. Accompanying this is a smoking ceremony where cedar cedar and tobacco are placed in a receptable and left to smolder. The smoke is fanned over a person in a manner similar to washing, the purpose being to cleanse away the spirit of death (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 3(1):3, 2000, Interview with Chief Floyd Leonard); 4. CUSTOMS: funeral--\"We smoked cedar and stayed all night with her [Sharon\'s deceased granddaughter, in funeral casket].\" (Kohn 1997:44, Interview with Sharon Burkyvile, Miami Tribe of Oklahoma); 5. CUSTOMS: chief\'s medicine bag, used for blessing a grave or new building, contained tobacco and cedar. \". . . the chief usually had the medicine bag that has tobacco and cedar in it and uh he blesses the grave. . . the cedar is to purify things and the tobacco and the cedar is to get rid of evil spirits the way I understand it cause when they built this building they what you call smoked it. They use cedar and they put it in a little old pot and they kind of made a smudge out of it and they kind of used a fan maybe to keep it smoking and they\'d go all around the room and smoke the building. . . they can take their hand and go like this you know get that smoke all over them and that\'s to get rid of evil spirits\" (Interview with Evelyn Scott by Kirsten Mathias and Reid Nelson, MTO Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/19/96, MTO Archives); 6. CUSTOMS/MEDICINAL: the chief smokes a sick person for healing and the deceased. \"the smoking ceremony we think it kind of purifies us  . . . If you\'re sick or anything the chief will come out and smoke you which we feel like it helps you get well . . .we use to make the smoke is cedar and cedar is a cleanser . . green cedar to get more smoke, we use tobacco, tobacco is a purifier and then we use sage and its for medicinal [purposes] . . . there was some sweetgrass mixed with the combination of sage and tobacco uh and the cedar\" (Interview with Chuck Wade by Brant Hall, MTO Headquarters, Miami, OK, 6/21/99, MTO Archives);  7. CUSTOMS: chief smokes a funeral casket with cedar. \" whenever we bury anybody the chief sprinkles cedar around the casket, uh then its traditional that th oldest women starts the line and she puts a little bit of dirt on the casket and it goes down as the ages get younger all the way to the back of the line. Then the man, him, it??s the same way all the ladies are through then the oldest man comes in and he puts some dirt on the casket. One of the tribal members stays as the casket gets lowered in the ground until it gets covered up. So uh to make sure the spirit stays there. Then a white flag is put at the head of uh the grave. Its left for three days . . . \"(Interview with Chuck Wade by Brant Hall, MTO Headquarters, Miami, OK, 6/21/99, MTO Archives); 8. CUSTOMS: component of a medicine bag. \"cedar is like a purification, um, the sweet grass . . . corn all of those have a special purpose, I\'m not sure what they all are. Its just medicine. Everything you would need to sustain you here or here after, is that little tiny portion, is in that bag\" (Interview with Barbara Mullin, Carlson 1996); 9. CUSTOMS: used when leaving the Nation drum, Gary??s personal habit to honor drum (Interview ww', '1. The Eastern red cedar is dioecious, having separate male and female trees. It is customary for Miami men to gather only from the male trees and Miami women to gather only from the female trees (Baldwin 2005, pers. comm.);', NULL, '1. Red cedar fibers were found in on specimen from a bag made by the Potawatomi (Whitford 1941); 2. Contemporary Catholic masses in Oklahoma have adopted some traditional ways of the Ottawa, and use a mixture of cedar and sweet grass over coals for incense, just like the Ottawa way. They also use a cedar sprig to spray Holy Water out, instead of the catholic bulb-shaped tool for the same purpose (Kohn 1997:81-82, Interview with Charles Dawes, Principal Chief at that time, Ottawa of Oklahoma); 3. A volative oil derived from the dried ripe fruits of Juniperus communis, in small doses (0.1 cc) is a gentle stimulant to the kidneys and act as a diuretc. In too high of a dose it may suppress urinary flow (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 4. Only two plants, wild tobacco and red cedar, were used traditionally as ceremonial plants by the Miami. Contemporary uses of other plants in ceremonies, including white sage (Salvia apiana, from western U.S.) and sweetgrass (Hierochloe odorata) have been acquired often from the pan-Indian movement of modern times (author\'s note and pers. comm. with Baldwin 2005);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE'