(151, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyNDIxMzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Monotropa uniflora L.', 'Indian pipe, Snowdrops', 'Monotropaceae', '(kyeehkiiwanitia)', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"kiaxkikwanitia pakateki, snowdrop flower\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1729); 2. UNKNOWN: \"kaxkikwanitia, one or what has the neck broken, snowdrop flower. The flowers look like they are bending over from the stalk and are the earliest to pierce the snow in the spring\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', NULL, NULL, '1. Steyermark (1963) mentions that this species is edible--perhaps this was a very early spring food (author\'s note 2005);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1895', '-1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(152, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo2MjA1Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Morchella esculenta & spp.', 'Morel', 'Basidiomycetes (Mushroom)', 'minosakayi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: eaten. \"the Miamis eat the morels . . . The edible sponge mushrooms [morels] . . . are called minosakai, which is the the name given to the tripe [the upper part of the stomach of a ruminant, also edible] (Dunn ca. 1900);                                                                                                                                                                                                 2. FOOD: prepared by soaking in salt water for a few minutes, shaking out the bugs, then cooked--always cook the wild variety (Patsy Hensen, Miami, 2002, from discussion with Sharon Prescott, relayed 7/14/03);                                                                                                                                                                                                                            3. FOOD: gathered and cooked. \"We hunted morels at just the right time in spring\" (Interview with Peggy McCord, 2004); 4. FOOD: gathered for cooking and eating. \"we gathered the mushrooms for cooking and eating, looked like christmas trees with holes\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004; speaking about her grandmother (Sophia G. LaFalier) and mother-in-law (Rebecca M. Stitt Walker));                              5. FOOD: hunted, gathered and eaten. Right time of year to collect is when the lilac\'s are in bud (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2004; information gleaned from family, friends and neighbors, not necessarily traditional Miami culture, however believes his grandmother mentioned the timing of morels with the lilac buds);                                    6. FOOD: morels gathered. \". . . she [Rebecca Stitt Walker] would get those that look like pine cones, you know how they come up, morels. My mom [Josephine Goodbo] was good at hunting those too\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999);                                            7. FOOD: \"nipopi minosakyai, a species of mushroom resembling the paunch of cattle; when on its stem it stands about two inches above the ground\" and \"nipopi, nipupi, a species of small yellow or brown mushroom, hollow inside; when cooked in water they form a froth or scumm which recalls our soups\", probably morels (Gatschet ca. 1895:1228 & 1647);', '1. When the mayapple plant umbrellas, winter is over and the mushrooms are out; when wild plum trees bloom it??s the time to start looking for morels, generally found in damp, shady places (Patsy Hensen, MTO, 2002, from dicussion with Sharon Prescott, relayed 7/14/03); 2. When the lilac flowers are in bud, that\'s when to hunt morels, around late April/May depending on weather and rain; favorite spots were old elm tree bark lying on ground, once found a whole row of them growing up in a seam of two old cement slabs from an old house in woods--a perfect row of morels, yellow, spear-shaped (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2003/2006; believes his grandmother probably told this to him);', NULL, '1. The Miami term \"minosakayi\" means the upper part of the stomach of a ruminant, or tripe (Gatschet ca. 1895:1228);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1895', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(153, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjo0NTgxNDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Morus rubra L.', 'Mulberry tree', 'Moraceae (Mulberry)', 'mihtekwapimi≈°i', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich soils of woods and flood plains in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: wood used for making bows. mihtekwaapimi?aahkwa [modern Miami], or \"m\'takwapijakwa, bow wood used for making bows\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: blossoms cooked as a vegetable. \"mihtekwaapimi?i, used to gather bloom of native mulberry and cook as a vegetable\"  (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: berries gathered (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 3. UNKNOWN: \"mangaraking8eminja, meurier\", mulberry (Gravier ca. 1700:243);  4. TECHNOLOGY: red cedar, black locust and mulberry tree wood used for shorter war bows (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria); 5. TECHNOLOGY: wood used for making bows. \"mitteg8aba\" (LeBoullenger ca.1725, see rel info);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Miami-Illinois term \'mitteg8aba\' is described by LeBoullenger (ca.1725) as the term for bow wood, but the closely related word \'mihtehkwaapa\' does not mean that in Gravier (ca.1700) and Dunn (ca.1909). Le Boullenger\'s word means \'bow\' or \'bowstring\' in sister languages, but never bowstring in Miami-Illinois. The accuracy of LeBoullenger\'s interpretation is somewhat questionable (Email communication between Costa and McCafferty, March 20, 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1725', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(154, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMjoyMjkxNToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Nelumbo lutea (Willd.) Pers.', 'American lotus, water chinquapin', 'Nelumbonaceae (Lotus-Lily)', '(poohkihs≈°kwaliaki)', '1. \"This root has large leaves that spread out on the water, like what we call votets, but they are much larger. Between two of these leaves issues something shaped like the body of a drinking-glass in which are the seeds, which are as big as hazelnuts.\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:346-347); 2. \"The missionary dictionary, ascribed to Le Boullenger, preserved in the John Carter Brown Library, at Providence, gives the following definitions: \"pokicorewaki, hollow roots\"; \"micopena, large root in the water\"; \"apena, pl. apeniki, potatoes\"; wicapisia, root for guarding themselves from death from serpents that they fear. The bulb is white, and rises out of the ground. The stem is a foot high, the leaves of four ribs (or on four sides), and a little red button on the top\" (Dunn 1919, footnote); 3. \"It has the appearance of a root, about half as thick as ones arm, or a little more; it also has firm flesh, and externally resembles an arm; in one word, you would say at sight of these roots that they are great radishes. But cut it across the two ends, and it is no longer the same thing; for you find inside it a cavity in the middle, extending throughout its length around which are five or six other smaller cavities, which also run from end to end\" \"The shape (of the dry top) is like a crown, of red color; it is as large as the bottom of a plate, and is full of seeds in every way resembling hazelnuts;\" \"The Miami name is pok\'-ci-kwal-ya\'-ki, i.e. full of holes, or nostrils (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:115-116);', '1. Occurs in quiet waters (Gleason & Cronquist 1991) in streams, floodplains and ponds (Small 1903, Steyermark 1963); 2. \"they dig . . .a certain root . . .only found in the Louisiana country, some fifty leagues above (below) the mouth of the Wisconsin\" (Dunn 1919, from Perrot);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: roots cooked; \"They gather also in these same marshes [as the macopines] other roots which are as big as one\'s arm and which are all full of holes. These give them no trouble to prepare; they merely cut them into pieces half as thick as one\'s wrist, string them, and hang them to dry in the sun of in the smoke\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:346-347); \"Elles prennent encore dans ces memes marests d\'autres Racines qui sont Grosses comme le bras, qui sont toutes remplies de toux, celles la ne leur donnent point de peines a aprester elles les Coupent seulement par morceaux gros comme la moitie du poignent les Enfilent et les mettent Secher au soleil ou a la fumee,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. FOOD: root eaten and seeds made to make soup. \"To eat it, you must cook it over a brazier, and you will find that it tastes like chestnuts. The savages are accustomed to make provision of this root; they cut it into pieces and string them on a cord, in order to dry them in the smoke. When these pieces are thoroughly dry, and as hard as wood, they put them into bags and keep them as long as they wish. If they boil their meat in a kettle, they also cook therein this root, which thus becomes soft and, when they wish to eat, it answers for bread with their meat.\" \" . . . when these [seeds from the dried top] are roasted under hot cinders they taste just like chestnuts\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:116); 3. FOOD: roots prepared and eaten. \"This plant is plainly Nelumbium luteum - the American lotus, yellow water-lily, water chinquepin, wankapin or yoncopin. Sarah Wadsworth informed me that the common mode of its preparation by the Miami women was to gather the roots (tubers), soak them in lye to loosen the skin, and then peel and boil them. The seeds were likewise soaked in lye, and shelled. Of these they made soup or cooked them as desired. The Miami name of the plant is \"pokcikwalyaki\" i.e. full of holes, or nostrils, which will be appreciated by those who are familiar with the plant\" (Dunn 1912-1915:31, word list); 4. FOOD: roots cooked and eaten. \"poakshikwileearkee, which means \'hollow root\' is similar in size to the white water lily, and grows in the same place--wet prairies. It is boiled with meat or eaten raw, as opposed to white water lily (macopines) and is said to be very good to eat\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:65); 5. FOOD: \"the word makopin is not used by the Miamis. It is understood to have been the name given to the water chinkapin, nelumbo lutea, comonly known as the yoncopin or wankapin--the pokekoretch of Nicolas Perrot\'s memoir. The Miamis call this pokcikwalyaki, i.e. full of holes. They used this to eat the roots of this, and make soup of the seeds (Dunn ca. 1900);', '1. \"Also in winter they dig from under the ice, or where there is much mud and little water, a certain root, of better quality than that which I have just mentioned; but it is only found in the Louisiana country, some fifteen leagues above the entrance to the Ouisconching [Wisconsin River]. The savages call this root, in their own language, pokekoretch; and the French give it no other name, because nothing at all resembling it is seen in EuropeThe women gather this root, and recognize it by the dried stem, which appears sticking up above the ice\" (Dunn 1919, from Perrot);', NULL, 'a', 'FALSE', 'mahkohpina', NULL, '(hollow root/full of holes)', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1680', '1912', NULL, '(2.4.06)--Dave Costa: Peoria <pukshikulia> \'pond lily\'. It looks awfully similar to that word for \'nose ring\'.', NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:22', '2017-09-19 22:48:22')
(155, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoyNzYwOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Nepeta cataria L.', 'Catnip', 'Lamiaceae (Mint)', NULL, NULL, '1. Native of Europe occurring in fields, waste lands, open woods, streams and disturbed areas (Small 1903, Steyermark 1963, Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: catnip and bear grease were used as an unspecified medicine (Interview with Sharon Burkybile by Lynwood Montell, Miami, OK, 12/12/94, MTO Archives);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1994', '1994', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(156, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoxMTg0Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Nicotiana rustica L.', 'Tobacco', 'Nyctaginaceae (Four o\'clock)', 'ahseema', '1. Plant up to 1m with 1.5-2cm diameter wide, salverform with greenish-yellow flowers (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', '1. Cultivated throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Interviews with Miami Tribal elders by Dr. Hamill\'s students, Miami, OK, 1996, MTO Archives); 2. Cultivated by native americans throughout the northeastern U.S. but now very rare or extinct in the wild (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: used by patient and doctor when sick. \"Indians raise a kind of tobacco called miamia sama [Miami tobacco] does not grow big-use it only when go to a doctor-put some in a bag and give it to him and he can tell whether you will get well\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. CUSTOMS: used to keep storm away. \"Also when storm is coming, put a pinch in the fire, or by the door to keep storm away\" (Dunn ca. 1900);  3. CUSTOMS: Funerals. Prior to the body being taken to the cemetary, an elder or the Chief goes to the cemetery to smoke the ground with cedar and tobacco. The cedar is evergreen, and signifies continuing life and the tobacco helps prayers ascend to the Great Spirit (Dunn 1919, Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):3, 2000);  4. CUSTOMS: If the ceremony is performed at the gravesite then the leader will cast cedar to the four directions and into the grave and over the coffin. After the ceremony friends and family gather at a relatives house. If the deceased smoked cigarettes, relatives will place cigarettes in containers around the area and each person should smoke one of the cigarettes as an honoring. Accompanying this is a smoking ceremony where cedar cedar and tobacco are placed in a receptable and left to smolder. The smoke is fanned over a person in a manner similar to washing, the purpose being to cleanse away the spirit of death (Interview with Chief Floyd Leonard, Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):4, 2000); 5. CUSTOMS: the calumet dance (tobacco pipe dance) is done on a carpet of large rush [cattail] mats spread under the trees, in the summer (Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:343); 6. CUSTOMS: peace-making ceremony involving peace-pipe smoking with enemy. \"He [the peace ambassador] proceeds directly to the principal village of the enemy the chief of which he asks for upon his arrival. he is shown the lodge of this chief and proceeds to it. After setting down his flag at the door he enters and having lighted his pipe and smoked, offers it to the Chief. If he accepts and smokes the sign is held good and the ambassador immediately commences to propose the arrangements for a peace. But if he refuses to smoke at all, it is totally unnecessary to attempt any thing and me makes the best of his way home.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:27); 7. CUSTOMS: peace-making ceremony involves dancing who are chosen by the warriors of the recent battle. Warriors take turns standing up, recounting great feats of bravery during battle, and choose a dancer by striking a pipe stem or piece of tobacco or a knife against a pole in the ground (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:28-29); 8. CUSTOMS: used to make an offering to the deity that inhabits unusual rock formations, mountains or upon entering caves, as they are passed in travels. \"It is not an uncommon thing for an Indian to lay upon a large stone a quantity of tobacco, and then to address it -- \"O Stone, you are fond of tobacco and I here give you a little to smoke--I am fond of life, I like to stay inthis world and I hope you will let me remain, and that you will give me success in hunting and travelling.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:56); 9. CUSTOMS: show repect to elders. \"Often the young men take to the aged the finest part of a deer which they have killed, or a skin, some tobacco, or moccasins.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:57); 10. CUSTOMS: offered to the Manitou, the spirits. \"There is a common Tradition amongst that People [the Illinois] That a great number of Miami\'s were drown\'d in that Place [a place just above the city of Alton, Illinois, where there are a great number of animal figures painted on a steep rock face with red paint], being pursu\'d by the Savages of Matfigamea [an Algonquian tribe living near the mouth of the St. Francis River in Arkansas, which later became part of the Kaskaskia]; and since that time, the Savages going by the Rock, use to smoak, and offer Tobacco to those Beasts, to appease, as they say, the Manitou, that is, in the Language of the Algonq', '1. A small variety of tobacco that was cultivated in the area of the Maumee River was used for ceremonies and offerings (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(3):2, 2002, Rogers); 2. Tobacco branches/leaves were cut with a knife (Gravier ca.1700:255.22, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter); 3. The tobacco was cut, or picked by plucking the leaves off. \"We pluck, thin out the tobacco,\" \"I pick it, cut it,\" \"I pluck the leaves off it\" (Costa 2004, St. Jerome ca.1692; \"nipapak8namina. nichikai8namina\", \"nipakich8a,\" \"i8chi nimarirena michipak8ki,\" translation from French to English by Costa); 4. Tobacco is cultivated by past and present Miamis. A strain called Mecsuki Tobacco was being grown at the Longhouse in 1996. Cultivation involves the following steps: The crop is started in February, in planters with potting soil. Seeds are sprinkled over the surface of the soil and can be mixed with sand prior to sprinkling. Seeds are pushed into soil one half an inch deep and watered once. Remove weaker, smaller seedlings as seeds germinate and grow. In mid April after the final frost transplant outside about one foot apart and water moderately. Plants grow to five or six feet high. In July the plants will bloom. When seed capsules are present, cut off top of plant and dry for planting next year. Then, harvest the rest of the plant, roll the leaves up and tie with twine to keep them rolled, and hand leaves for drying. Finally, shred leaves and smoke (Interviews with Miami Tribal elders by Dr. Hamill\'s students, Miami, OK, 1996, MTO Archives); 5. Tobacco was transplanted by hand in the early days. \"I put [it] standing in the ground, transplant some tobacco\" (Gravier ca.1700:319.04, \"nimamara acema8a\", \"je mets debout en terre, transplante du tabac,\" translation from French to English by Masthay000); 6. Charlevoix mentions a native tobacco that is far inferior in taste to the introduced tobacco. Kellogg adds that the tribes of the Great Lakes used a species of native tobacco, not a true tobacco, called \"petun\" and a tobacco mixture containing herbs, sumac, dogwood, and cornel [?] bark (Charlevoix 1682-1761:125, from Kellogg 1923:116);', NULL, '1. On the origin of tobacco: Tobacco Garden Creek was first described by Lewis and Clark, April 17th, 1805. It was actually a marsh of reeds, Phragmites communis and was misnamed by some early traveler, confusing the Sioux and Assiniboine name for reed, cedi (cheddy), and tobacco, candi (chandee), says Larpenteur. He adds, \"Of course, Indians cultivated a native tobacco (Nicotiana quadrivalvis) in those days; but not in separate gardens, apart from corn, etc.\" (Coues, 1898); 2. Keller George (Oneida) described uses and growing of tobacco (Kohn 1997); 3. The tobacco pipes were made from a red stone, now known as catlinite, joined to a hollow reed for smoking, and decorated with feather. Tobacco pipes are also known as calumets (Thwaites 1903:654, from Marquette 1673:211); 4. The calumet, or tobacco pipe, dance is described in detail in Thwaites (1903:655, from Marquette 1673:212); 5. The Miami-Illinois term \"nimikima\" translates as \"I play with him. I gather tobacco or some other animate thing\" (Gravier ca.1700:293.10, \"je joue avec luy. Je cueille du tabac ou autre chose noble,\" translation from French to English by Masthay000?); 5. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that tobacco was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" during the late Woodland period (A.D. 1000 through A.D. 1450) (Bush 2003); 6. Mildred Walker recalls that althought they did not grow tobacco in her family garden in Miami, others in the community grew \"long green fat tobacco\" which was stronger than Indian tobacco (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 7. Algonquian chiefs of villages can remarry as soon as six months after a wife has died, to ensure they have women to cultivate fields for tobacco and other crops. \"The chiefs of the villages are not under obligation to remain widowers after six month\' time, because they cannot get along without women to serve them, and to cultivate the lands which produce their tobacco and all [else] that is necessary for them to be prepared to receive those who come to visit them, and strangers who have any business regarding the tribe to place before them\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:373-74); 8. Other terms for tobacco have been documented as \"samwah\" (Kerr 1835:133, 283 & 400, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa), ts (000:134-135) as \"saamau\", and by Hockett(1938, from Peoria, spelling cannot be reproduced here); 9. There is a can of sweet gum for mixing with tobacco, thought to be Miami, housed at the Cranbrook Institute of Science, Bloomfield Hills, Michigan (see attachment, Cranbrook items); 10. 1. Only two plants, wild tobacco and red cedar, were used traditionally as ceremonial plants by the Miami. Contemporary uses of other plants in ceremonies, including white sage (Salvia apiana, from western U.S.) and sweetgrass (Hierochloe odorata) have been acquired often from the pan-Indian movement of modern times (author\'s note and pers. comm. with Baldwin 2005);', 'FALSE', NULL, 'Tabac', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1674', '2004', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(157, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzozNzk5Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Nymphaea spp. Aiton.', 'White water lily', 'Nymphaceae (Water-Lily)', 'mahkohpena', '1. Nymphaea tuberosa has leaves that are green beneath, N. odorata has leaves that are purple beneath. Both species are the only large aquatic plant (of Nelumbo, Nymphaea and Nuphar) that have floating leaves and flowers (Steyermark 1964); 2. This species was also known as macopine (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:345);', '1. Occurs in quiet waters of streams and ponds (Small 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: roots cooked and eaten. \"There are also many roots which the women gather. The one which they esteem the most is the macopine. It is a big root which they get in the marshes. I have never tried to learn what the flower is like, so I cannot speak of it, although I have seen the women pull the roots up from the ground at the bottom of the water into which they wade sometimes up to the waist, so that they often duck their heads under the water to pluck them up. There are some as big as one\'s leg. The savages assert that that they are poisonous when raw, which I hardly believe. The women have peculiar difficulty in cooking them. Sometimes three of four cabins combine and dig a hole in the ground five or six feet deep and ten or twelve square. They throw a great deal of wood into it, which they set on fire and when it is aflame they throw in a number of rocks, which they take care to turn over with big levers until they are all red; then they go in quest of a large quantity of grass which they get at the bottom of the water and which they spread as well as they can over these rocks to the thickness of about a foot, after which they throw on many buckets of water and then as fast as they can each cabin puts its roots in its own place, covering them over with dry grass and bark and finally earth. They leave them thus for three days. They shrink to half their former size\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:345-346, \"Elles ont aussi quantite de Racines qu\'elles amassent celles qu\'elles Estiment le plus est la macopine, c\'est une grosse racine qu\'elles prennent dans les marais, je ne me suis jamais attache a connoistre le fleur, ainsi je ne puis en parler, quoy que je les ayent vues arracher de la terre au fond de L\'eau, ou elles se mettent quelquefois jusqu\'a la Ceinture si bien qu\'elles se mettent souvent la teste dans l\'eau pour les arracher, il y en a de grosses comme la jambe, Les sauvages assurent que c\'est un poison estant crues ce que j\'ay de la peine a croire, Les femmes ont des peines estranges a les faire cuire, elles se mettent quelquesfois trois et quatre Cabanes Ensembles, et font un trou dans la terre de cinq a six pieds, et de dix ou douze en quarre, Elles Jettent dedans quantite, de Bois dans lequel elles mettent le feu, et quand il est bien allume elles y jettent force Roches quelles ont soin de Retourner avec de gros Leviers jusqu\'a ce quelles soient toutes Rouges, apres quoy elles Vont chercher quantite d\'herbes qui sont au fond de l\'eau, qu\'elles estendent le mieux qu\'elles peuvent sur ces Rochers de l\'epaisseur d\'environ un pied, apres quoy elles jettent quantite de seaux d\'eau et au plus Viste chaque Cabanes met ses Racines en un Endroit les couvrent d\'herbes seches et des Ecorces par dessus et ensuite de la terre, elles les Laissent de cette maniere trois jours, elles se reduisent a moitie de leur Grosseur ordinaire,\" translation from French to English by Pease);                                                                                                                                                             2. FOOD: roots cooked in the ground and eaten. \"mukoapineek, this is the root of the pond lily. It is very tough and requires considerable preparation before it is fit for use. They find it as large as a man\'s wrist and one to two feet long. After taking up considerable quantity of it, they dig a hole in the ground, upon the bottom of which they place a layer of stones, on these a layer of wood and on the top another layer of stones. They set the wood on fire, and when it is consumed they cover the heated stones with dry moss, and then throw into the hole the mukoapineek. Thjs is covered with grass or moss, and bark, and having filled the hole with water they cover it with earth. They suffer it to remain untouched for five days, when they take out the roots and cut them into small pieces, after which they are dried upon a scaffold and put away for use. They are preserved in this way for a year,;', '1. \"It [the macopine] is a big root which they get in the marshes. I have never tried to learn what the flower is like, so I cannot speak of it, although I have seen the women pull the roots up from the ground at the bottom of the water into which they wade sometimes to the waist, so that they often duck their heads under the water to pluck them up. There are some as big as ones leg.\" (Pease 1934:345-346, Deliette 1721; \"c\'est une grosse racine qu\'elles prennent dans les marais, je ne me suis jamais attache a connoistre le fleur, ainsi je ne puis en parler, quoy que je les ayent vues arracher de la terre au fond de L\'eau, ou elles se mettent quelquefois jusqu\'a la Ceinture si bien qu\'elles se mettent souvent la teste dans l\'eau pour les arracher, il y en a de grosses comme la jambe,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 2. The Old Illinois term \'nimic8picahan\' translates to modern French as \"je l ay cherche dans l eau avec un baston et je la ay trouve,\" meaning \"I looked for it in the water with a stick and I found it\" (Gravier ca.1700:292.25). Since this directly follows the entry for macopines, it proably refers to a harvesting methods of this, and other edible aquatic roots (author\'s note);', NULL, '1. Gravier (ca. 1700) lists the Miami-Illinois terms \"kaahsikaahsileeka\", (103.41) and \"mac8peniki\" for the macopine, or white water lily root. In modern Miami this would be spelled \"waapisipina, or waapipakaani?i\" (Language Database 2005); 2. This species\' roots require lengthy cooking (author\'s note, 2006);', 'FALSE', 'nipinki peehkateeki (cult use 4)--same sp?', NULL, 'bear root (Gr)', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'mihkohpena (lit. red root)', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1683', '1824-food; 1900-med', NULL, '(4.25.06)--Michael McCafferty to Daryl Baldwin: Just wanted to let you know that the most common referent for Native American place names on record for Indiana is the wild sweet potato (/Ipomoea pandurata/). I haven\'t yet counted its occurrence in local hydronyms and toponyms but it is by far the dominant referent.  What M-I terms do you find associated with this plant? Is this what they used to call batates?  (4.25.06)--Daryl Baldwin: /mihkohpina/ and /mahkohpina/. Both terms are attested in Miami-Illinois. Old Potwatatomi also has cognates for both terms. I\'m not sure if the French called them \"patates\" of not. They did refer to them as macopines. La Salle has an excellent description of their preparation, including how they should be red before they are eaten. When cut or damaged, the root becomes red naturally. The Macoupin River, tributary of the Illinois River, is named after this plant, as is Potato Creek, tributary of the Kankakee. The Miami name for Vincennes /aciipihkahki/ also refers to this plant. It was an extremely important food for the Miami and Illinois, at least in early historical times.??????--not sure if this is accurate id or transcription of dialog', NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(158, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoyOTU3Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Opuntia spp. Miller', 'Prickly pear cactus', 'Cactaceae (Cactus)', 'lenoonkwia (also for red-belted polypore?)', NULL, '1. Occurs on dry, rocky, soils in prairies and dunes (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"prickly pear, species of flat leaved cactus creeping along the soil and growing on rocks or on the ground, flower red or pink, leaves round 3 to 4 inches in diameter\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'man\'s face', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '-1895', '-1895', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(159, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo5NTM1Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Oxalis spp. L.', 'Wood sorrel', 'Oxalidaceae (Wood sorrel)', '(wiihkapeepiikwi)', '1. Oxalis acetosella is the only wood sorrel mentioned in Small (1903), yet there are five other Oxalis species that were present in the area at that time (author\'s note);', '1. Occurs in various habitats, often as a weed. Both native and non-native species (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"wikapipikwi, . . . a weed called sheep-sour, leaves like clover, white people make pies of it\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: eaten while hunting to keep hunger at bay (Interview with Daryl Baldwin, Miami Pow Wow, Civic Center, Miami, OK, 6/7/03);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '2003 (1900)', '2003', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(160, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoxNTY0MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Panax quinquefolius L.', 'American ginseng', 'Araliaceae (Ginseng)', 'piloohsa', NULL, '1. Occurs in rich woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MEDICINAL: Ginseng (pilo\'sa) used to produce fruitfulness in women, taken as a tea or decoction pilosapo\'I (Dunn ca. 1900:Indiana State Library L47, Note #35); 2. TECHNOLOGY (trade): collected and dried, then sold for pharmaceutical use (Rafert 1992:182); 3. MEDICINAL: \"abesoatchenza\", ginseng root used to make women fruitful (Charlevoix 1682-1761:99, from Kellogg 1923:93); 3. MEDICINAL: harvested for use (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', '1. Harvested just a little each year from large patches (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, '1. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993);', 'FALSE', 'abesoatchenza (Charl)', NULL, 'baby', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1682', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(161, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo1MTY2NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Phalaris caroliniana Walter.', 'Maygrass', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in waste places, moist roadsides and wet fields (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that maygrass was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" by indigenous people\'s during the late Woodland period (seen in archaeological sites prior dated from before 700 A.D., then again in sites dating from A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450) (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(162, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo5NTU3NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Phallus impudicus', 'Stink-horn fungus', 'Basidiomycetes (Mushroom)', 'weempa awiilakayi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"wamba wilakai, mushroom, the large stink-horn phallas, i.e. wambas penis; wamba is a mythical wild man, very tall, who lives in the woods (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. The latin name means \"shameless penis\", and are also known as stinkhorns, create a smell of rotting flesh with a \" hint of sweetness too.\" The spores are produced on the receptacle and embedded in a slime that contains a number of volatile chemicals including hydrogen sulfide, formaldehyde, methylmercaptan, and phallic acids, together producing the smell of rotting flesh to attract flies which will disperse the spores (Money 2002);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'weempa\'s penis', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'na', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(163, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoxMDE4Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Phaseolus coccineus L.', 'Scarlet runner bean', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', NULL, '1. Phaseolus polystachios L. is the native bean, but with seeds only 2mm wide. For this reason it is presumed that the beans referred to in the below sources were referring to the non-native cultivars of Phaseolus, including common bean P. vulgaris L. and scarlet runner bean P. coccineus L. (author\'s note);', '1. P. coccineus (scarlet runner) is a non-native species cultivated throughout eastern and western Miami lands and North America (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: beans with red seeds cultivated, indicating Phaseolus coccineus. \"They also sow beans and melons, which are excellent, and especially those whose seed is red\" (Marquette 1673:210, from Thwaites 1903:652); 2. FOOD: red beans with brown cultivated and eaten (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', '1. FOOD: \"they also sow beans and melons, which are excellent, especially those that have red seeds.\" (Kenton 1925:000, The Jesuit Relations); 2. Beans were hoed as part of the cultivation process. \"koatsheesaukee utsheekelotauwee\", translated as, let us hoe the beans (ts 000?:204);', NULL, '1. There were a number of varieties of the common bean used by the Potawatomi (Smith 1933), and a number of our most successful pole beans come from bean varieties of the Ojibway (Moerman 1998, Smith 1932); 2. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that beans were cultivated during the late Woodland period (A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450) becoming common around A.D. 1200 (Bush 2003); 3. There was a single specimen of common bean found from sample 082 of the New Lennox Remains (MTO files);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1673', '2005', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
