(165, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzozNjkyOToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Phaseolus spp.', 'Bean', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', 'kociihsa', NULL, '1. P. vulgaris (common bean) is a non-native species cultivated throughout eastern and western Miami lands and North America (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: eaten. \"mollom wis cochoesock amwhakek\", translated as, I ate too many beans (em 000?:160); 2. FOOD: speckled green beans brought to Kansas and Oklahoma from Indiana and cultivated (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 3. FOOD: modern traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 4. FOOD: beans grown with corn stalks as their support (Charlevoix 1682-1761:121, from Kellogg 1923:112); 5. UNKNOWN: \"kotcisa, bean\" (Dunn ca. 1900:451); 6. UNKNOWN: \"kutchissa axki\", bean field; \"pawaliaki kutchissahi palakinatchiki\", translated as, the Peorias hull of a quantity of beans (Gatschet ca. 1895:69, 1786); 7. FOOD: cooked and eaten. \"ampesi8aki c8tchissaki\" translated as \"the beans swell while cooking\" (Gravier ca. 1700:028.36); 8. FOOD: boiled with corn and eaten. \"minzhipee tshee koatsheesauk goawenzauweearn\", translated as, \"are the corn and beans boiled?\" (ts 000?:291);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1682', '1999', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(166, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo1NTU4ODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Phragmites australis Trin.', 'Common reed', 'Poaceae (Grass)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in swamps and shores, mostly reproducing vegetatively, in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: Shopekenauminkee is a game played with a hundred pieces of small reed or cane about a foot in length. The players take turns taking the bunch of reeds between their hands and letting them drop end-wise upon the bark board where they play, trying to drop them so that five pieces, corresponding to the head and limbs, fall together. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:64); 2. MATERIAL: the hollow portion of the is tobacco pipes, calumets, are made from the common reed (Thwaites 1903:654, from Marquette 1673:211); 3. MATERIAL: flutes made with reeds. Lora Siders remembers her uncle Clarence Godfroy making reed flutes for the kids in his family. She wanted to take flute lessons but the Delaware man that gave lessons, following his Delaware culture, didn\'t believe in giving flute lessons to girls/women. So she never learned. She remarked that the Miami women were always active in the tribe, including musically, as well as spiritually and politically. \"We didn\'t have to fight for women\'s freedom, cause we\'ve always had it.\" (Interview with Lora Siders, Baldwin 1997);', NULL, NULL, '1. Only two species are listed with the name \'reed\' in Coulter\'s flora of Indiana (1899), Small\'s flora of southeastern U.S. (1903), the first, Calamovilfa longifolia, which is confined to beaches and sandy stretchs of the souther Lake Michigan, and the other, Phragmites communis, much more widespread and common.', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1673', '1997', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(167, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzozNTY3Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Phytolacca americana L.', 'Pokeweed', 'Phytolaccaceae (Pokeweed)', '(maamilaneewiaahkwia)', NULL, '1. Occurs in fields, fencerows and damp woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. FOOD: shoots eaten as greens. \"mamilanewiakwi\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MEDICINAL: berries soaked in whiskey used to treat rheumatism, and pulverized root used as a poultice. \"use berries for medicines, for rheumatism--soak berries in whiskey\", \"sometimes pulverized boiled root for [used] for poultice\"  (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. TECHNOLOGY: berries used for paint. \"Indians used pokeberries for paint\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. FOOD: eaten as greens. \" . . . many said it was poison and wouldn\'t eat them but they did.\" (Interview of Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978); 4. FOOD: eaten as greens, \"Pokeweed was always used by the Indians . . . pokeweed was a very important green.\" \"It was made almost identical to the way you would could asparagus. And tasted a lot like milkweed or asparagus.\" \"You used mostly just the stem. . . only th every smallest of the leaves would be used. All greens were considered a tonic [food to cleanse or protect against illness]. . . In the spring of the year after a winter of eating dried fruits, dried foods, and meat, they felt that they needed something else, a purge, that could be purgative, that could be used for that purpose.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:92-94); 5. FOOD: eaten as greens. \"They use the shoots of poke, but Godfroy\'s belief was that they did not use poke, mushrooms, or wild lettuce, until they learned to eat them from the whites. He was probably wrong as to this, as the instruction concerning the use of native plants came the other way\" (Dunn 1919); 6. FOOD: Mable Olds (Leonard) picked poke and wild onions to cook with (Interview with Peggy McCord, 2004); 7. (FOOD): roots of \'poke\' were cooked and eaten. \"They had what they call poke potatoes. That was a potato, but the name was poke root potato . . . something similar to a sweet potato when you first take it out of the ground before the skin has got dark, kind of a cream color . . . Mama said she cooked on a fireplace when she was about six years old. . . I think they said it came from Canada. I ain\'t seen it since we left Indiana, long years ago. But I saw it growing there\" (Interview with Rose Carver by J.W. Tyner, Miami, OK, 9/9/68, MTO Archives); 8. FOOD: shoots gathered and eaten. \"My mother and her gathered poke in Oklahoma and I do in Utah\" (Interview with Patti English, speaking of her mother Hilda Faye Billington, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/2/04); 9. FOOD: young leaves gathered and cooked as greens. \" It was used as a spring tonic for cleansing the body. The young leaves of poke, curly dock and lamb\'s quarter\'s were gathered near my house, mixed together and cooked with vinegar\" (Interview with Judy Davis, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/1/04); 10. FOOD: eaten as greens (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 11. FOOD: greens gathered (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 12. UNKNOWN: \"mamilaniwai\", pokeweed (Gatschet ca. 1895); 13. FOOD/MEDICINAL/TECHNOLOGY: young shoots eaten; mature berries used as temporary, nonwashable, paint; dried berries used to deworm dogs (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', '1. \" It had to be gathered before it was about 15 inches tall. Beyond that stage it became poisonous.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 2. Barbara Mullin and her mother, Julia Gamble Lankford would go out in late March and early April with brown bags and fill them with poke they found in uncultivated areas. \"It has a large leaf. In spring the greens are tender and very good\". It is plentiful where ditches have been bladed and cleared and any other vegetation has been removed. The berries, developing later, are noxious (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):11, 2000);', NULL, '1. Pokeweed greens were eaten by Lamoine Marks. Prepared almost identical to asparagus or milkweed and tasted like them. Mostly just used the stem. Only the very smallest  of the leaves would be used. Considered a tonic (like all greens, Lamoine says), a spring tonic that could be a purgative (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 2. Barabara Mulllin\'s recipe for poke (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):11, 2000); 3. Daryl Baldwin found a reference to use of Phytolacca decandrea, older nomeclature for Phytolacca americana, which used to be cooked on the fireplace (Baldwin 2003); 4. Due to lead, cadmium and zinc contamination in the Tar Creek Superfund Site\'s watershed, around Miami, Oklahoma and the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma\'s headquarters, Miami and other local tribal members worry that traditional gathering of food, medicine and CUSTOMS items may be contaminated. Fish, wild blackberries, sassafras, pokeweed, basket-making supplies and wild onions could have high concentrations of lead, as do the waters of nearby lakes, and it is not always successful keeping tribal members out of these areas. The Seneca-Cayuga\'s berry dance could not be held, if all the wild blackberries and strawberries in the area are found to be contaminated (Tulsa World 7/13/2003); 5. Human-charred pokeweed material was recoverd from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181): 5. Dunn documented Gabriel Godfroy saying that  poke, mushrooms or wild lettuce wre not used by the Miami until the whites taught them how to use them. Dunn comments that \"He was probably wrong as to this, as the instruction concerning the use of native plants came the other way [from the Indians to the whites]\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', 'FALSE', NULL, 