(168, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo5MTczMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Picea glauca (Moench) Voss.', 'White spruce', 'Pinaceae (Pine)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in rich, moist soils of coniferous forests in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Algonquian villages celebrate a feast of the dead, where they dance in a large cabin, around spruce-trees or three cornstalks. \"They dance from one end to the other of the cabin, returning after one another, in single file, around spruce-trees or three cornstalks which are set up there\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:86-87);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(169, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo4ODczNzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Picea mariana (Miller) BSP.', 'Black Spruce', 'Pinaceae (Pine)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs mostly in bogs in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: camoflage during attack. \"Upon arriving near the Iroquois encampment the spies gave her [a Miami woman who lived in the village on the Great Miami, after the village having been attacked by the Iroquois, had a dream in which the Miami were to pursue the Iroquois, recover their imprisoned people and kill every one of their opponents. She organized the retaliation and since was considered a woman of great bravery] information of the fact, and she caused every one to pull a piece of spruce or pine from the trees, and with these before them they approached the camp. They fell suddenly upon the sleeping Iroquois and her prediction was literally fulfilled.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:26);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(170, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzozNzIwMToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Pinus spp. L.', 'Pine tree', 'Pinaceae (Pine)', 'naanahami≈°aahkwa', NULL, '1. A variety of species occurring various habitats (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: camoflage during attack. \"Upon arriving near the Iroquois encampment the spies gave her [a Miami woman who lived in the village on the Great Miami, after the village having been attacked by the Iroquois, had a dream in which the Miami were to pursue the Iroquois, recover their imprisoned people and kill every one of their opponents. She organized the retaliation and since was considered a woman of great bravery] information of the fact, and she caused every one to pull a piece of spruce or pine from the trees, and with these before them they approached the camp. They fell suddenly upon the sleeping Iroquois and her prediction was literally fulfilled.\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:26); 2. MEDICINAL: sap spread on bottom to heal saddle soreness. Scott Shoemaker\'s great grandfather (by marriage) Camillus Bundy, taught Scott\'s grandfather, Frances Shoemaker  (Phyllis\' Miley\'s father) to ride horses and other wilderness skills horseback trips into the woods for a few days. His grandfather got a sore bottom and his great grandfather told him to smear pine sap on it, and the soreness got better. His grandfather had said, \"It made it [his bottom] sticky but it made it better\" (Interview with Scott Schoemaker and Phyllis Miley, 2003); 3. TECHNOLOGY: sap good for starting fires (Interview with Scott Schoemaker and Phyllis Miley, 2003); 4. TECHNOLOGY: pine cones used to make house smell good. His wife, Mary Ellen would prepare them by soaking them in something to bring the aroma out (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman, 1999); 5. MEDICINAL: bark of young pines boiled to treat burns. \"Boil the bark of the young pines for burns and for wounds\" (Anonymous 1724:164B, \"Faire bouiller de l\'ecoise de jeunes pins pour la Brulure et pour les Playes\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 6. MEDICINAL: branches of young pines boiled to treat veneral diseases. \"The branches of young pines boiled for veneral diseases\" (Anonymous 1724:164B, \"Des Branches de jeune Pins bouiller pour les maux veneriens\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 7. UNKNOWN: \"nanahaminjakwi, pine tree, implies without limbs\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3731); 8. UNKNOWN: \"nauhenamaazhau, pine\" (tw 000?:150);  9. UNKNOWN: \"nanimihinja, sapin\", pine (Pinet 1696-ca. 1700); 10. UNKNOWN: \"pupaundeeoanee maazhauhungk nauhenaumazhauk, the lightning struck that pine\" (ts 000?:177); 11. UNKNOWN: \"nanimihinja\", pine tree (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, '1. A concentrated distillation of pine sap, in small doses (0.5 gm) can be used externally as an antiseptic dressing to help heal skin rashes, and is readily absorbed through the skin. Internally it acts as a stimulant, expectorant, diaphoretic 000?, and antiseptic (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 2. Gatschet listed the Miami term \"sakindapwa\" as the generic term for a bur, pine cone, or specific term for cocklebur (Gatschet ca. 1895:2066); 3. Dunn also listed the Miami term \"saki\'napwa\" for cocklebur (Dunn ca. 1900); 4. An unknown source listed the Miami term \"chimezohqua\" for pine trees, although this is a cognate for the term for red cedar (Lanaguage Database, from 000?);', 'FALSE', 'rel. info. 4', NULL, 'rel. info. 2 & 3', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(171, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoyMDQ5Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Planera aquatica (Walter) J.F. Gremlin', 'Water elm', 'Ulmaceae (Elm)', '(pakhkokwaninci siipiiomeekwi)', NULL, '1. Occurs in swamps and low, wet woodlands of western and the southernmost portions of eastern Miami (Illinois) lands, covering the coastal plain north to southern Illinois, portions of southeastern Oklahoma (Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Petrides and Wehr 1988, Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MATERIAL/TECHNOLOGY: canoe, tables for drying corn, berries, and fruit. \"If they wanted canoes lighter than dug-outs, they made them of the bark of the water-elm or hickory, the pig-nut hickory being considered best. They cut down a tree, peeled off the bark with flat sticks. In the spring, when the trees were beginning to leave, the bark came  off easily, and at other times they had to pound it to loosen it. This kind also used for tables for drying corn, berries, fruits, etc. Laid poles placed on forked sticks. Also used for sugar troughs--bend ends up and fasten them. When through would soak and straighten them out and lay them up like shingles when dry to use next year. Would serve for several years. Also made boxes of it\" (Dunn 1919:1953dw); 2. UNKNOWN: \"pakkokwaninji sipiomakwi\", water elm (Dunn ca. 1900:1954);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Peoria of OK cut up the tender shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar for cattle fodder (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. Human-charred American elm timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(172, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo4MTg2NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Plantago sp. L.', 'Plantain', 'Plantaginaceae (Plantain)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: prepared as greens (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 2. MEDICINAL: leaves collected and mashed into a poultice and put on sunburns for healing (Interview with Beth Devers, 2003, speaking about her mother\'s (Mildred Walker) plant use); 3. MEDICINAL: leaves of wide-leaved plantain (Plantago major, an exotic) picked, crushed and put on burns (Interview with Mildred Walker, 200, speaking about her grandmother (Sophia G. LaFalier) and mother-in-law (Rebecca M. Stitt Walker)); 4. MEDICINAL: cure for pink eye. Leaves mashed and put placed in a damp cloth and put over the eyes (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 5. FOOD: leaves gathered, after thick, stringy veins removed, and cooked as greens (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. Not specifically referring to this species, Eugene Brown recounted the story of his grandmother, Rebecca M. Stitt Walker, gathering a number of wild herbs to help heal a man with who had come seeking treatment for his severe toothache. His grandmother took him out towards the woods and first gathered a big, flag leaved herb (possibly the introduced common plantain, Plantago major) from their yard which she scraped the outer layer off of, and got the juicy pulp, then rolled it up, in a \"burrito\" like fashion. Then she proceeded towards the woods and there gathered other herbs which she mixed with the first. She tried to put this mix on his gums but the man wouldn\'t let her. She told him to how to apply it to the bad tooth and he left. A year later Eugene saw this man hanging around, with hollowed out cheeks. Eugene asked his grandmother what had happened with the man\'s tooth problem and she said he probably put it all over his mouth and lost all his teeth! (Interview with Eugene Brown, 2004a);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(173, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzozOTg3Mzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Platanus occidentalis L.', 'Sycamore or Buttonwood', 'Platanaceae (Plane-tree)', 'kaakih≈°aahkatwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist or wet alluvial soils (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: sycamore cut up to make syrup and tea (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. MEDICINAL: bark used to make tea for treatment of diarrhea (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 3. UNKNOWN: leaves and bark used (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 4. MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred sycamore timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184); 5. UNKNOWN: \"kaakihsaahkatwi, sycamore tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900:4753dw); 6. UNKNOWN: \"kokshaukautwee, sycamore\" (tw 000?:153); 7. UNKNOWN: \"cotshacotwi, sycomore\" (Marks 000?); 8. UNKNOWN: \"cakijacat8i\" (Gravier ca. 1700); 9. UNKNOWN: \"kakishaxkatwi, sycamore\" (Gatschet ca. 1895); 10. UNKNOWN: \"kakinjakat8i\", sycamore 	(Pinet1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Peoria of OK cut up [tender shoots and leaves] to make syrup and tea (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(174, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoyMjEzOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Podophyllum peltatum L.', 'Mayapple', 'Berberidaceae (Barberry)', 'kahkiteemi≈°i', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: fruit eaten [in summer] (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:95); 2. MEDICINAL: the root was used [at an unknown season] as a \"physic\" or \"purgative\" . . . \"they took the May apple root and pounded it up, and then soaked it out--it was always a liquid form, of course, when they used it.\" \"May apple roots are still being used. There were still people who practiced herbal medicine [in his generation]\", although he or no one he knew ever used it. \"We knew that the used it, because we sometimes gathered it, and sold the root to people who did used it.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:95-96); 3. MEDICINAL: Lyman Mongosa described preparing a liquid  for a woman who was given up by doctors, in the early 1930s. His medicine, he felt, saved her . . and it may have been prepared from mayapple (Lyman Mongosa, from Rafert 1980); 4. MEDICINAL: root used for stomach disorders (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Calrence Godfroy, 2ndy source ); 5. FOOD: used as a snack food when in the woods (Rafert 1996:182); 6. FOOD: fruits eaten raw or made into preserves (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2004);', NULL, NULL, '1. Listed as a purgative and many other uses for the mayapple root (American Indian Medicine, pp. 334, 336, ?); 2. Listed on the U.S. Pharmacopeia as a drastic purgative (?); 3. Dried rhizome and roots in small doses (0.3-1.0cc) can be used to increase flow of bile, and is a slow but powerful cathartic, emetic, and can be poisonous in too large a dose. In large doses it can cause violent purging with profuse watery stools, hemorrhaging to internal organs and depression of central nervous system (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.);', 'FALSE', 'kahkiteemi?aahkwi', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(175, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzozNTAxMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Polygonum sp. L.', 'Knotweed', 'Polygonaceae (Smartweed)', NULL, NULL, '1. Many species occurring in a variety of habitats throughout eastern and western Miami lands, many introduced species growing as weeds (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: Human-charred knotweed/smartweed material was recoverd from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181);', NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that knotweed was either cultivated or \"strongly encouraged in wild stands\" as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D through 1300 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003); 2. Seeds made into flour for pancakes (AP News 4/21/2003, \"Ancient Village Located in Illinois\", Damiansville, 35 miles east of St. Louis). Village dates from 600-800 A.D. ruling out the common exotic, Polygonum cuspidatum, Japanese knotweed, an edible whose shoots are eaten much as common milkweed but introduced much later;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(176, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzo1MzQ4Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Polyporus sulfureus (Fr.) Murr./P. squamosus Fr., or Pleurotus austriacus', 'Shelf fungi (Bryad\'s saddle, P.squamosus)', 'Polyporacaea, Class: Hymenomycetes', '(waapantoowa)', '1. The species given in this entry are the most probable species being referred to in ethnographic records (Vincent 2003, pers. Comm);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: word similar to other regional tribes for mushroom or shelf fungus (Gravier ca.1700, LB 000?);', NULL, NULL, '1. Cooked Bryad\'s saddle (Polyporus squamosus) can make a very distasteful smell, like a disinfectant, and render them practically inedible (Money 2002);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(177, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwMzoyNzA5OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Populus deltoides Marhsall.', 'Cottonwood tree', 'Salicaceae (Willow)', 'maaloonseentia', NULL, '1. Occurs in lowland woods, wet prairies and riparian areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. MATERIAL: used for wood sculpture. Crane/cattail sculpture in Eiteljorg made of cottonwood by Eugene Brown (Interview with Eugene Brown, 2003); 2. TECHNOLOGY: used to make canoes,  \"The Cotton-Trees are of a prodigious height; the Savages make them hollow with Fire, to make their Pyrogues of them; and we have seen some of them all of a-piece, above an hundred Foot long\" (Thwaites 1903:212, from Joliet 1674:?); 3. MATERIAL: used to make canoes,  \". . .I have seen some canows made of those trees [\"cotton-trees\" or cottonwood trees], eighty foot long, and three foot broad, which carry thirty men. I saw 180 of those wooden-canows in one village of the savages consisting of 300 cabins\" (Thwaites 1903:622, from Joliet 1674:185-186); 4. UNKNOWN: \"wapakoza\'ndia, cottonwood tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 5. UNKNOWN: waapantoowa, \"8abant8aki\" (Gravier ca. 1700); 6. UNKNOWN: \"8apant8oki\" (LeBoullenger ca. 1725); 7. UNKNOWN: \"mar8ssintia\", cottonwood [probably P. deltoides] (Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Peoria of OK cut up the tender shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar for cattle fodder (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:23', '2017-09-19 22:48:23')
(178, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo1MDU1NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Populus nigra L.', 'Black poplar', 'Salicaceae (Willow)', 'maaloonseentia (cottonwood in dict)', NULL, '1. Native of Eurasia which is frequently planted and sometimes escaped (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"mar8sentia, liard arbre\", black poplar (LeBoullenger 1719-1744);  2. UNKNOWN: \"mar8sintia\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(179, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo5ODg3MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Populus tremuloides Michx.', 'Quaking aspen, quaking ash, poplar', 'Salicaceae (Willow)', '(siipiomeekwa)', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist upland woods and streamsides, often in areas that have been deforested or burned (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: branches used as snares for capturing beavers. \"For capturing these animals [beaver and other animals] they [tribes along Lakes Huron and Michigan, possibly Miami-Illinois peoples] use snares, in which for bait there is a branch of a tree which they call \"trembling tree;\" the animals are very fond of this, and in trying to reach the inner end of the snare, where the bait is placed, they step upon a trigger, which lets fall a heavy weight on the animal\'s back and kills it\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:110); 2. UNKNOWN: \"sipiomakwa, quaking ash, grows along rivers\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, 'bois blanc (French Canadian)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(180, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo4ODA2Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Portulaca oleracea L.', 'Purslane', 'Portulaceae (Purslane)', 'koohkoosa awiilawi', NULL, '1. Probably a native to southern Asia, occurring in many habitats as a weed (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: common weed used as hog fodder. \"kokocawilawi, purslane\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3860); 2. FOOD: Human-charred purlsane material was recoverd from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:181);', NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that purslane was utilized as a food source by indigenous peoples sometime during the period of A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450 (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(181, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo0NDg1Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Prunus americana Marshall.', 'Wild plum tree', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', 'ateehseemi≈°aahkwa', NULL, '1. They grow best \"In fence rows and the the edge of clearings\", not along the river, but on higher, well-drained areas (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 2. Occurs in moist woods, roadsides and fencerows (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: tafumeneke (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa); 2. UNKNOWN: plums (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 3. FOOD: \"Wild plums were here, they\'ve always been here. . . .My mother even made jelly out of \'em. But the old people ate them just right off the tree ripe. They\'re quite good.\"(Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:101); 4. FOOD: plums gathered and preserved. \"The savages gather quantities of wild plums and grapes . . . \" (Marquette 1673:200, from Thwaites 1903:108); 5. FOOD: made into plum wine. Jim Strack knew a lady that worked at a beauty shop near him that made wine out of wild plumbs. This woman told his wife, Mary Ellen, how to make it, calling it \"plumb dumb\" wine. \"You could get \'plum dumb\' on it real easy!\" The fruits were first collected, mashed and sugar put over them. Then water was added until it covered them mashed plums and the mixture was refrigerated. In a short while it became quite strong (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 6. MATERIAL: game played with plum stones (like those in picture). \"Sansawingee\" means bowls, which is the name of the game. A wooden bowl and six plum stones, painted black on one side, white on the other. The player scores if he turns up five of the same color, after tossing. \"This counts him half of the amount bet, and six of the same color wins it.\" Betting is often involved (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:60); 7. MATERIAL: plum stone game played at Miami Tribe of Okalahoma\'s language camps (MTO language camp, Miami, OK, June 2004); 8. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 9. MATERIAL: There is a set of Miami dice made from fruit pits (possibly wild plum) housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, Washington D.C. (see attachment: NMAI items); 9. FOOD: white plums eaten. \"We therefore landed, and entered their Cabins, where they offered us meat from wild cattle and bear\'s grease, with white plums, which are very good\" (Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:360); 10. FOOD/MATERIAL: \"tassaminia, plum\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1214); 11. FOOD/MATERIAL: \"tasaminic, peaches\" (em:479); 12. FOOD/MATERIAL: \"atassamina\" for plum (Dunn ca. 1900:3753, 3754dw); 13. FOOD: (Dunn ca. 1900); 14. FOOD: pitted, cooked and eaten. \"they\'re tart, so add extra sugar\" (Interview with Dani Tippman & Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005);', '1. For harvesting fruits, put down a tablecloth first and shake the tree (Interview with Dani Tippman & Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005);', '1. \"There aren\'t as many of these [wild plums] as their used to be--due to loss of fencerows\" (Interview with Dani Tippman & Mark Strack, 2005);', NULL, 'FALSE', 'tassamina (Gat), tasaminic (em) (rel. info)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(182, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo2MTI6Mg==', 2, 0, 1, 'Prunus avium L.', 'Cherry tree (domestic)', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', 'katoohwakimi≈°aahkwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in cultivated areas and sometimes as an escape in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 3. FOOD: \"mugalomere, cherry tree\" and \"nupekecuqu, cherry tree\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(183, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo5OTQwNzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Prunus persica (L.) Batsch.', 'Peach tree', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', '(peeweeyocaahkwa)', '1. UNKNOWN: peach, i.e. fuzzy (Dunn ca. 1900);', '1. Native of China which occurs as an escape or is planted (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"paweotcakwa, peach tree\" and \"pawiotcakatwi\", peach, i.e. fuzzy; peach stone (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. UNKNOWN: (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 3. FOOD: traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, '(fuzzy)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(184, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo0NDEzODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Prunus serotina Ehrh.', 'Wild cherry tree', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', '(mahkwawilami≈°i)', NULL, '1. Occurs in woods, along streams and abundant in roadsides and forest margins (Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: (Dunn ca. 1900:1109dw); 2. MEDICINAL: the bark of the root chewed and held a long time on the gums to cure an infection. \"Also, the bark of the root of the cherry tree chewed and held for a long time on the gums cures the falling sickness\" (Anonymous 1724:162B, from Kinietz 1965:222, \"Item l\'ecorce de la racine de Cerisier maches et tenue longtems sur la Gencive guerit du mal de Terre\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 3. MEDICINAL: inner bark from the west side of tree boiled and made into tea for cough syrup (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004, Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 4. UNKNOWN: (Marks 000?); 5. MEDICINAL: bark used as a tonic and cough syrup (Interviews with Miami elders 1977-1992, Rafert 1992:45); 6. UNKNOWN: leaves used (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 7. MEDICINAL: bark crushed or chewed used to treat wounds. \"The bark of wild cherry in cluster, chewed or crushed for wounds\" (Anonymous 1724:165A, \"De l\'ecois de merisier a grappe, machee ou pilee pour les playes\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 8. MEDICINAL: tea made by boiling \"spicnert\", horehound, comfrey, cherry bark and \"alicompain\"[spelling may not be accurate] (from Mildred Walker\'s papers, given to Myaamia Project 2004); 9. UNKNOWN: \"cacityouqui, cherry tree\" (Marks 000?); 10. MEDICINAL: fruit eaten as a laxative, \"sharp taste but good laxative . . .don\'t eat too many!\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2003); 11. UNKNOWN: (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 12. UNKNOWN: \"mugalomere, cherry tree\" and \"nupekecuqu, cherry tree\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Miami word \'neehpikicaahkwa\' was also recorded by Dunn (ca.1909) for the cherry tree, with no use mentioned (author\'s note); 2. \'neehpikicaahkwa\' and \'katoohwakimisaahkwi\' may refer to any of the other native cherry species in the Prunus genus, including, choke-cherry (Prunus virginiana), sand-cherry (Prunus pumila), and wild red cherry (Prunus pensylvanica), but Prunus serotina was the most common of these species in western (Coulter 1899, Small 1903, Steyermark 1963:distribution maps of Missouri counties) and eastern Miami territories (author\'s note); 3. The wood is reddish-brown, and resembles mahoghany, used for furniture, tool handles, musical instruments; the bark is bitter and aromatic and is used for its astringent properties in cough medicines, expectorants and sore throats; the fruit is edible. (Steyermark 1963); 4. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993); 5. Dried stem bark collected in autumn, in small doses (2 gm) acts as an astringent, tonic and sedative--and is used in cough syrups. Prussic acid is present in the bark, but normally in too small amounts to give the sedative effects (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 6. Human-charred Prunus spp. material recovered from excavations at an early 19th century Miami village site (Bush 1996:181); 7. It is unclear whether this word indicates a native cherry or cultivated cherry or both.  There are four edible native cherries. The two native cherries,  P. serotina (wild black cherry, 1cm thick black fruits), P. virginiana (choke-cherry with 8-10cm thick black fruits) occur in a variety of habitats, the former abundant as a roadside tree, throughout eastern Miami lands, and the other two natives, P. pumila (sand-cherry with 1-1.5cm thick black fruits) and P. pensylvanica (pin-cherry, with 6mm thick red fruits), occur in a variety of habitats in both eastern and western Miami lands. There are five introduced cherries, P. padus (European bird-cherry with 6-8mm thick black, inedible fruits), P. mahaleb (Mahaleb-cherry with 6mm thick dark red to black, bitter fruits), P. avium (sweet-cherry with 1.5-2.5cm thick fruit), P. cerasus (sour cherry or pie-cherry with 1.5-2cm thick tart, red fruit), and P. fruticosa (ground-cherry with 1cm thick, dark red fruits) occur in a variety of habitats as cultivated cherries and escapes within eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991) (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', 'mahkwawilami?aahkwi (Gat)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
