(189, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo3Nzc2NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Pyrus malus L.', 'Apple tree', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', 'mih≈°iimi≈°aahkwa', NULL, '1. A native of Europe and Asia, occurring as a cultivated plant throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"mici\'minjakwa, [apple] tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900:261dw); 2. UNKNOWN: (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 3. FOOD: crab apples used as a snack food when in the woods (Rafert 1996:182); 4. FOOD: modern traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 5. UNKNOWN: \"michiminja un pommier\", an apple tree (Gravier ca. 1700:286); 6. UNKNOWN: \"remezuhqu, apple tree\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa); 7. UNKNOWN: \"micimizhaxkwaki, apple trees\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1188, 1729 & 251); 8. UNKNOWN: \"michiminja\", apple (Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, '1. Related Miami words: mihsimina (apple fruit), mihsimina ahkanimina (apple seed); 2. Keller George (Oneida) described the creation of crabapple trees (Kohn 1997);', 'FALSE', 'remezuhqu (Kerr)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(190, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo1MTk3MToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Quercus alba L.', 'White oak tree', 'Fagaceae (Beech)', 'waapinkwaahkatwi', NULL, '1. Occurs in upland woods (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: the bark was soaked in water then used on burns (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy); 2. MEDICINAL: leaves, bark or root was boiled and used on wounds. \"The bark or the root of the white oak boiled for wounds; The leaf of the same wood is also perfectly good\" (Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De l\'ecorce ou de la Racine de Chesne blanc bouilly pour les playes ce feuille du meme bois est aussy parfaitement bonne\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 3. UNKNOWN: \"wawapi\'ngakatwi, white oak tree\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3523dw); 4. UNKNOWN: \"wawiyipinggotwi, oak\" (Marks 000?); 5. UNKNOWN: \"waupingwauhkautaa, white oak\" (tw 000?:148); 6. UNKNOWN: \"kaaoohkungk nonee weepingwauhkart, it has blown down that white oak\" (ts 000?:112); 7. UNKNOWN: \"wewipingwak\'ki, white oak\", weepinkwaahki (Gatschet ca. 1895:2617); 8. MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred white oak timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184); 9. UNKNOWN: \"8a8iping8kat8i\", white oak (Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', '1. Oak and hickory nuts are available in the Fall, and have irregular peak mast harvest, separated by a range of 1-4 years. This means that oak and hickory peak masts are irregular, but variation in yields in consistent from year to year, thus enabling Native Americans to plan for taking advantage of peak masts. The largest masts occur when tree crowns are exposed to maximum sun--Native Americans could also have easily thinned trees to increase size and production of remaining trees (Gardner 1997:163, 171 & 177);', NULL, '1. Talalay, Keller and Munson. 1984. Hickory nuts, ?000; 2. The Miami-Illinois term for vase of acorn, or nut, is alakaya (Gatschet ca. 1895); 3. \"The Oak is so good, that I believe it exceeds ours for building Ships.\" (Hennepin 1698, from Thwaites 1903:212)--this probably referred to the fact that the oaks encountered were so much larger than those of the British Isles, and were thought to be superior if used for building ships from them like the British were used to doing (pers. comm. George Ironstrack 2006);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(191, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDozOTM3ODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Quercus macrocarpa Michx.', 'Bur oak', 'Fagaceae (Beech)', 'mihiinkweemi≈°a', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist woods and alluvial flood plains throughout eastern and western Miami lands 1. Occurs on rich, moist soil throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: gathered and shelled acorns, then soaked in lye before boiling (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MEDICINAL: roots chewed and applied to wounds. \"miching8eminja\", \"oak whose large acorn and the chewn/mashed root are good for curing a cut\" (Costa 2004, Pinet 1696-ca.1700:38); 3. UNKNOWN: \"mishingwe mishaxkatwi . . . Bur oak, frequent out west, quercus macrocarpa\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1247); 4. FOOD: acorns [species not specified] leached in water to remove tannic acids before eating. (Interview with George Dorin, 2005, relaying something his grandmother Sarah (Lena)  E. Hale, used to say); 5. UNKNOWN: \"miching8eminja\", bur oak (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', '1. Oak and hickory nuts are available in the Fall, and have irregular peak mast harvest, separated by a range of 1-4 years. This means that oak and hickory peak masts are irregular, but variation in yields in consistent from year to year, thus enabling Native Americans to plan for taking advantage of peak masts. The largest masts occur when tree crowns are exposed to maximum sun--Native Americans could also have easily thinned trees to increase size and production of remaining trees (Gardner 1997:163, 171 & 177);', NULL, '1. Name of family lineage including Shoemaker\'s of Kokomo, IN, MNI (Baldwin 2003, pers. comm.); 2. The Miami word mihsiinkweemina is used for the burr oak fruit, or acorn; 3. Other Miami terms for bur oak include \"mihsiinkweemisaahkatwi\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1247) and \"mici\'ngwami\'nji\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 4. The Miami-Illinois term for vase of acorn, or nut, is alakaya (Gatschet ca. 1895);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
