raine de vinaigrier, et on fait boire l\'eau chaude dans la quelle ce tout a detrempe a la femme accouchee jusqu\'a entiere guerison, c\'est a dire l\'espace de deux ou trois jours chaquerjour remettre dans la chaudiere une semblable dose, et en donnant a boire a la malade un peu avant qu\'elle mange, sur le midy, sur le quatre heures et le soir avant se coucher, le s;', NULL, NULL, '1. McPherson wrote, \"The Potawatomie Indians used sumac juice for this purpose [cure for mouth sores]. . .\" (1977:139, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 2. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that sumac was utilized by indigenous peoples sometime during the period of A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450 (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(201, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo1MDc4NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ribes cynobasti L. or R. uva-crispa L.', 'Gooseberry or Dogberry bush', 'Grossulariaceae (Gooseberry)', 'akaayomis≈°aahkwi', '1. Described as \"any tree or bush with berries having a rough bark or rough-skinned berries\" (Dunn ca. 1900, Gatschet ca. 1895);', '1. R. cynobasti occurs in moist woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991), occurs in rocky woods and hillsides (Small 1903); 2. R. uva crispa is native to the Old World and occurs as an escape from cultivated areas (Gleason and Cronquist 1991), not listed in Small (1903);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: (Dunn ca. 1900:2388dw); 2. UNKNOWN: gooseberry bush, also called \"kayu-mishi\" (Gatschet ca. 1895); 3. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"Well, the gooseberry was pretty controversial, whether they ate them or not. When the gooseberry was ripe, they turned purple, and they\'re fairly good to eat. They just wouldn\'t have passed up a thing like a gooseberry,\" described as a native plant (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 4. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 5. FOOD: fruits eaten (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:101, 2ndy source Marks either read or heard about, original source unknown);', NULL, '1. Gooseberry (akaayomi?aahkwa) is commonly referred to as a shrub or bush (Daryl Baldwin, in an email message to Michael McCafferty, 12/9/2003);', '1. Miami words for gooseberry and gooseberry-like shrub mentioned by Dunn (circa 1909, in notes), with no mention of use; 2. Gooseberries (dogberries) bearing prickly fruits are consistently Ribes cynobasti, in Coulter (1899), Small (1903), Steyermark (1963) and Gleason and Cronquist (1991), making note of R. prostratum in Small, described as having a bristly hypanthium (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'rough-surfaced (bark or berry) bush', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(202, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNDo1NTg2MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ribes sp. L.', 'Currant', 'Grossulariaceae (Gooseberry)', NULL, '1. Bunches are not as large as common grapes (Gatschet ca. 1895);', '1. There are six native currant species. Five of these species (Spiny swamp-currant, R. lacustre; Skunk-currant, R. glandulosum; Western black currant, R. hudsonianum; Eastern black currant, R. americanum; Swamp red currant, R. triste) occur in wet areas including swamps, bogs, woods in the eastern Miami lands. A sixth native species (Buffalo-currant, R. odoratum) occurs on rocky cliffs and hillsides predominately in western Miami lands. Two exotic currants (Garden black currant, R. nigrum; Garden red currant, R. sativum) occur as escapes from areas where cultivated throughout eastern (Gleason and Cronquist 1991) and western Miami lands.;', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 2. UNKNOWN: \"asandapakwi\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. UNKNOWN: eehsipanimini (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. Racoon grapes, or \'coon grapes\' used a similar Miami-Illinois term to Dunn\'s word for currant, \"esepanimini\" (Dunn ca. 1900:1537). These grapes are described as \"assipana ssandepakwi, racoon grapes, a sour grape relished by racoons but not eaten by people, the bunches not solarge as of common grapes, it is preferable to call this grape assipanimina (Gatschet ca. 1895);', 'FALSE', 'asandapakwi (Dunn)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:24', '2017-09-19 22:48:24')
(203, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToyNDE1NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Robinia pseudoacacia L.', 'Black locust', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in dry upland woods, along streams, in fields, thickets and disturbed areas (Steyermark 1963) throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: cedar, black locust and mulberry tree gave the wood for the manufacture of the shorter war bows (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria); 2. MATERIAL: seeds used for necklaces, bracelets and buttons (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(204, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo3OTIxMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Rorippa nasturtium-aquaticum Scop.', 'Water cress', 'Brassicaceae (Mustard)', NULL, NULL, '1. A non-native aquatic plant established in clear, quiet waters through the U.S. and southern Canada, native of Eurasia (Gleason & Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: gathered by Barbara Mullin and mother, Julia Gamble Lankford, in Seneca, MO (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):11, 2000); 2. FOOD: greens eaten (Interview with Sharon Prescott, collective info. from a collecting trip with 3 local Cherokee and 3 Miami women, Language camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/6/03); 3. FOOD: gathered and eaten (Interview with Patty English and daughter Deena Garza, 2004); 4. FOOD: gathered for eating (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005);', '1. Barbara and her mother would go out in late March and early April with brown bags and fill them with watercress they fond in spring water, especially in branches of creeks. It doesn\'t grow in ponds with standing water (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):11, 2000);', '1. Barbara Mullin\'s recipe for watercress salad (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(1):11, 2000);', NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(205, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToxNjU1NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Rosa spp.', 'Wild rose', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: hips gathered and used to make jelly, also eaten raw if sweet. \"You have to find a good sweet patch of roses\" (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'pic8rakitiminja, pic8rakimina (Gr)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(206, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozNDA5MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Rubus allegheniensis T.C. Porter', 'Common blackberry', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', 'makiinkweemina', NULL, '1. Occurs on mostly in disturbed areas throughout eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991), with closely related or hybrids occuring in western Miami lands (author\'s note);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"makingwamina, blackberry\" (Dunn ca. 1900:629); 2. UNKNOWN: (Anonymous 1837, 2nd Wea Primer); 3. FOOD: fruits eaten (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:101); 4. FOOD: used for jelly by her grandmother Geboe [000?] (Interview with Peggy McCord, 2004); 5. FOOD: gathered early in the morning (Interview with Julie Olds, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/6/03); 6. MEDICINAL: root used to treat diarrhea (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 7. FOOD: wild blackberries picked (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 8. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 9. UNKNOWN: \"making8eminiki, meure de haye\", blackberry (Gravier ca. 1700:235); 10. UNKNOWN: \"mekexuemeneke, blackberries\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer); 11. UNKNOWN: \"okingominic, blackberries\" (Kerr 1835:237, 1st Wea Primer, from Mongosa);', NULL, NULL, '1.  Rubus taxonomy is complex, confused by hyrbridization, polyploidy and apomixis, and the group of blackberry species is even less clear (Gleason and Cronquist 1991). According to Coulter (1899), Small (1903), Steyermark (1963) and Gleason and Cronquist (1991), it is reasonable to assume that the Miami word for blackberry referred to either R. allegheniensis, which was and is very common, or one of less common species including R. orarius, R. argustus, R. canadensis, R. pensilvanicus or R. setosus, all closley resembling R. allegheniensis (nomenclature from Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark, J.E. 1993); 3. Barbara Mullin recipe used by Senecas and Quapaws and possibly other tribes used blackberries or blueberries and cornmeal to make a traditional, southern style cornbread (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 1(2):15, 1998); 3. The Miami terms \"makingwamina\" and \"makingwaminiki\" (plural form) are the words for blackberry (Dunn ca. 1900:629-630); 4. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that blackberries were utilized as a food resource by Late Woodland (800 A.D to 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003); 5. Due to lead, cadmium and zinc contamination in the Tar Creek Superfund Site\'s watershed, around Miami, Oklahoma and the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma\'s headquarters, Miami and other local tribal members worry that traditional gathering of food, medicine and other items may be contaminated. Fish, wild blackberries, sassafras, pokeweed, basket-making supplies and wild onions could have high concentrations of lead, as do the waters of nearby lakes, and it is not always successful keeping tribal members out of these areas. The Seneca-Cayuga\'s berry dance could not be held, if all the wild blackberries and strawberries in the area are found to be contaminated (Tulsa World 7/13/2003); 6. Corn and blackberries were used in a traditional Native American southern style cornbread (Aatotankiki myaamiaki 1(2):15);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(207, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo1OTkwMzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Rubus flagellaris Willd., R. enslenii Tratt.', 'Northern dewberry, Southern Dewberry bush', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', 'mankaalakiinkweemi≈°a', '1. A vining plant growing close to the ground. It looks like a blackberry, only shorter and fatter, almost round, with little seeds (Personal communication with Mary (Strack) Swenda, by Dani Tippman 2005);', '1. R. flagellaris occurs on rocky ledges, cliffs and disturbed sites in eastern Miami lands.  R. enslenii occurs oak-hickory woods in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason & Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"mangalakingwamina, dewberry, ie. big-eyed berry (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: berries picked and eaten. Sugar was put on them and they were eaten like canned fruit (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 3. FOOD: traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 4. UNKNOWN: \"managaraking8eminiki, grosses meures de haye\", big eyed berry (Gravier ca. 1700:243); 5. FOOD: harvested and used to make pies, jelly and on ice cream (Personal communication with Mary (Strack) Swenda, by Dani Tippman 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Miami name for this plant probably refers to Rubus flagellaris, northern dewberry, or R. enslenii, southern dewberry (Small 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'wide-eyed berry', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(208, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToyNzU4OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Rubus occidentalis or R. idaeus L.', 'Raspberry bush, Red or Black', 'Rosaceae (Rose)', '(neepaleeteemina)', '1. Raspberries include four species in Gleason and Cronquist (1991) (R. odoratus, flowering raspberry, R. pubescens, dwarf raspberry, R. occidentalis, black raspberry, and R. idaeus, red raspberry), two species in Small (1903) and Steyermark (1963) (R. ocidentalis and R. strigosus (idaeus));', '1. In general, both species occur in dry or moist woods, roadsides, fields and thickets (Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: fruits eaten (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:101); 2. FOOD: berries picked and eaten (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 3. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 4. UNKNOWN: \"napaletemina, raspberry\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1214); 5. UNKNOWN: \"napalatamina, raspberry\" (Dunn ca. 1900);  6. UNKNOWN: \"nepuletemeneke, raspberries\" (Kerr 1835, 1st Wea Primer,from  Mongosa);', NULL, NULL, '1. Miami word for raspberry mentioned by Dunn (circa 1909 in notes), but no mention of use; 2. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that raspberries were utilized as a food resource by Late Woodland (800 A.D to 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'half-berry', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(209, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2OTEwNjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Rudbeckia hirta L.', 'Black-eyed susan, Bachelor\'s button', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', 'mahkateewiciiphki-?', '1. \"I have not seen this plant but imagine that it is Rudbeckia hirta, as the Indian said \"the Whites call it Bachelor\'s Button, because a button grows on the top, which is in the midst of a brown flower. The stalks are from two to three feet tall.\" \"(Dunn circa 1909); 2. Gatschet describe the plant as \"a weed 2 to 3 feet high with yellow berries or buttons\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:969). Steyermark remarks that Rudbeckia hirta var. homochroma have yellow disk as well as ray flowers. The dense, compact cone of yellow disk flowers could be what Gatschet describes as a yellow \"berry\" (Steyermark 1963:1558);', '1. Occurs in many habitats, including open woods, roadsides and fields, throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Small 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991, Henn 1998);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. CUSTOMS: roots are used to protect from bad spirits. \"mak\'katewitchipkiki or makatewi tchip\'kiki\", the medicine was \"rubbed on a gun-barrel, and then fired at any strange noise which they suspected to be made by spirits . . . As a charm or amulet particles of the root are carried in the pocket and keep off spirits, witches, etc.\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MEDICINAL: used to treat coughs and sore throats (Gatschet ca. 1895:969); 3. CUSTOMS: used to protect against bad spirits or witches. \"carried in pocket as charm against spirit or witches\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:969);', NULL, NULL, '1. Rudbeckia hirta is considere R. serotina in some sources (Gleason and Conquist 1991);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'black root', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(210, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2ODAwMDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Rumex sp. L.', 'Dock, sorrel', 'Polygonaceae (Buckwheat)', '(wiikapeepiikwi) (sheep sorrel)', NULL, '1. One or a number of Rumex species could be referred to by \"slick dock\". In general, docks grow in wet areas (moist soils, wetland edges, swamps) or disturbed sites (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: young leaves called \"slick dock\" gathered and eaten as greens (Interview with Howard Walker, Judy Davis, Ken Dagenet and Mildred Walker, 2004); 2. FOOD: young leaves of \"slick dock\" eaten as greens, but not leaves of curly dock (Rumex crispus). The \"slick dock\" they gathered had narrow, slick-looking (shiny) leaves [possibly the young leaves of various Rumex species: author\'s note] where the curly had wide, tough and curled-edge leaves  (Interview with Mildred Walker, 2004, Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 3. FOOD: young leaves gathered and cooked as greens. \" It was used as a spring tonic for cleansing the body. The young leaves of poke, curly dock and lamb\'s quarter\'s were gathered near my house, mixed together and cooked with vinegar\" (Interview with Judy Davis, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/1/04); 4. UNKNOWN: (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 5. FOOD: young and mature leaves gathered, cooked and eaten with butter and salt. \"You can freeze leaves too, if the plants and patches are too big for one meal\" (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(211, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NTE5NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Sagittaria latifolia Willd.', 'Common arrowhead', 'Alismataceae (Water Plantain)', '(waakihpena)', NULL, '1. Occurs in ponds, streams and swamps throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: (McCafferty 2003:11; Le Boullenger\'s translation of wapissipena is \"oignons venant dans leau, pomme de terre blanches\", meaning \"bulbs coming in water, white potatoes\", indicating arrowhead tubers); 2. FOOD: tubers eaten. \"waukeepaaneekee, grows in bottom lands. It resembles in root and shape of the stem, the onion. It is boiled about twelve hours before it is eatable. They are not very fond of it because it produces costiveness\" (Trowbridge 1825--attributing this record to arrowhead is tenuous, since arrowhead tubers can be eaten raw, and it stems do not resemble the onion); 3. FOOD: tubers eaten. \"8abipeniki, oignons doux\" (Gravier ca. 1700); 4. FOOD: cassicassireca8aki, 8abisipiniki, p8kc8re8aki sont cordees [stringy], ne sont plus bonnes [are better], CR-type of water onions, wild lotuses??who translated this??? (Gravier ca. 1700);', '1. Village location sometimes was chosen for its nearness to an abundance of root crops that attracted vast numbers of birds in the autumn when the marshes were dry. These root crops were quite possibly arrowhead, and the Illinois probably placed their village close to the portion of the lake that had an abundance of tubers available (Pease 1934:350, Deliette 1721, \"y en a une si grande quantite dans la Riviere et principalement dans le Lac au bout duquel les Illiois sont Etablis du coste du nord a cause de la quantite de Racine qu\'il,\" translation from French to English by Pease);', '1. \"We camped near where the Shawnee hills now stand, from which point to the Indianola ferry where the bridge now spans the Kaw, was a swamp or dry lake, and in this lake the wild potatoes grew in abundance. As we laid ourselves down to sleep that night our lullaby was the crunch of the wild hog as he masticated the wild potato, of which he was very fond\" (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 1(2):2, 1998--Ely Moore 1908);', '1. \"Topeka\" means \"a place to find small or wild potatoes\" in the Kaw language (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 1(2):2, 1998--Ely Moore 1908); 2. Robert Vezina has determined that the word \'8abissipena\' is the Illinois word for an edible arrowhead (Vezina 2002, pers. comm.); 3. Gravier (ca.1700) used the Ojibwe/Algonquin term for arrowhead to translate the Illinois term, implying that historically the same word referred to Sagittaria latifolia, in both languages. In Ojibwe, the word \'waabiziipin\' appears to mean swan potato, however the word has no morpheme for \'water\' in it. There is still some discussion about the Miami word and its actual meaning (Email discussion between McCafferty, Costa and Fiero, February 21, 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(212, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo4Mjk1ODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Salix nigra Marshall.', 'Black willow', 'Salicaceae (Willow)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs abundantly in alluvial soils along streams and in meadows (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: bark use as a remedy for skin troubles (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(213, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NzQ3Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Salix spp. L.', 'Willow', 'Salicaceae (Willow)', '(nipiaahkatwi)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"nipiakki, willow (generic of kinds of willows growing along streams\" (Dunn ca. 1900:5377dw); 2. MATERIAL: willow boughs used to made wiikiaami, at 2nd annual language camp in Sunnyside, WA, held by Sammye Darling (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(2):12, 1999); 3. MATERIAL: used for bulding wikiamis. \". . . yellow willow best for wiikiaami, bends very well but hard to find now, not as much as there used to be . . .other willows good too. It seems to absorb the moisture when wet and last longer.\" (Interview with Gary Shoemaker, 2003); 4. UNKNOWN: \"nipiaxkawi (weeping) willow, generic term comprehending the willows growing near the water, same as nipiaxkwa\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1639);', NULL, NULL, '1. material use: Peoria observation of Nez Perces when they were held in Miami--\"They made a basket out of buck-husk and willow weeds, also large carved wooden jars and much beadwork.\"(Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. The \'nip\' stem of the Miami word \'nipiaahkwi\' probably refers to a number of willow species that grow along watercourses and in moist areas (Note from Daryl Baldwin); 3. MATERIAL: fibers from the black willow (Salix nigra) use to make bags, pouches, fish nets, and cordage by Menomini, Winnebago, Michigan Ottawa, and Ojibway Indians. To prepare the black willow fiber, the bark was stripped from the tree, then the inner white bast tissue removed, boiled, pounded and rubbed until the fibers were loosened for twisting. All specimens contain prepared fibers (Whitford 1941);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'tree grows in water', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(214, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDI1NToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Salvia apiana Jepson', 'White sage', 'Lamiaceae (Mint)', 'none (contemporary use only)', NULL, '1. Native to arid and semi-arid areas of western U.S.;', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. CUSTOMS/MEDICINAL: the chief smokes a sick person for healing. \"the smoking ceremony we think it kind of purifies us  . . . If you\'re sick or anything the chief will come out and smoke you which we feel like it helps you get well . . .we use to make the smoke is cedar and cedar is a cleanser . . green cedar to get more smoke, we use tobacco, tobacco is a purifier and then we use sage and its for medicinal [probably white sage, currently used by many tribes for similar purposes] . . . there was some sweetgrass mixed with the combination of sage and tobacco uh and the cedar\" (Interview with Chuck Wade by Brant Hall, MTO Headquarters, Miami, OK, 6/21/99, MTO Archives); 2. FOOD: hung dry and possibly used for cooking (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, '1. Only two plants, wild tobacco and red cedar, were used traditionally as ceremonial plants by the Miami. Contemporary uses of other plants in ceremonies, including white sage (Salvia apiana, from western U.S.) and sweetgrass (Hierochloe odorata) have been acquired often from the pan-Indian movement of modern times (author\'s note and pers. comm. with Baldwin 2005);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(215, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5MzQ3Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Sambucus canadensis L. or S. racemosa L.', 'Common elderberry or Red berried elderberry', 'Caprifoliaceae (Honeysuckle)', '(wiikooloomphsa)', NULL, '1. S. canadensis occurs in moist or rich woods, fields, and roadsides in eastern and western Miami lands, while S. racemosa occurs in rich woods in only eastern Miami territory (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"wikullumpsa\", or wiikooloomphsa, \"elder bush\" (Dunn ca. 1900, Eastern Miami); 2. FOOD: berries gathered and made into juiice (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 3. FOOD: berries gathered for making into preserves, sometimes mixed with something else to make more tart (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 4. MATERIAL: stems hollowed out using a willow branch, then a whittled down hickory stick placed inside along with a paper wad to make a \'pop-gun\' (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 5. UNKNOWN: \"papikwa\'nze, papikweze, elder-tree, probably Sambucus glauca. SW [Sarah Wadsworth] thinks the pit in it named the tree papikwanshi-wanshi is pith or marrow\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1896); 6. FOOD: berries made into jelly, flower buds and heads can be deep fried and eaten (Interview with Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005); 7. TECHNOLOGY: stem hollowed out and used as a tap for maple sugaring (Interview with Mary (Strack) Swenda 2005); 8. FOOD: wild elderberries picked and eaten as a child. Mother, Thelma Louise Baker of the Eagle Band, made elderberry wine and jelly (Interview with George Dorin 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. Flowers of Sambucus canadensis or S. nigra contain volatile oils, resins and other compounds that when given in small doses (4 gm) act as a diaphoretic 000?, diuretic, and stimulant, and are used to treat erysipelas 000?, and fevers (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 2. An undetermined source listed \"kilu..sah\" for \'alders\'  and another unlisted source listed \"peekatami?i, pacottameiz\" for \"alder bushes\" (Language database, 2004);', 'FALSE', 'papikweensi (Gat)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(216, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTozMjc4MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Sanguinaria canadensis L.', 'Bloodroot', 'Papaveraceae (Poppy)', 'oonsaalamooni', NULL, '1. Occurs on rich, moist soil throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: used to make yellow paint. \"onzalamoni, bloodroot, i.e. yellow paint\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2.TECHNOLOGY: (trade) collected and dried, then sold for pharmaceutical use (Rafert 1992:182); 3. MEDICINAL: used as a tonic (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:104);', NULL, NULL, '1. emetic, purgative and yellow paint (Peterson\'s guide?000);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(217, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NzkzMToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Sassafras albidum Nees.', 'Sassafras, Ague tree', 'Lauraceae (Laurel)', 'mankii≈°aahkwi', '1. Also known as \"Ague Tree\" (Small 1903);', '1. Occurs in disturbed woods, thickets, roadsides and oldfields (Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. Occurred in many places, especially along railroad tracks (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: root used for drink/tea. \"mangi\' cakwi\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MEDICINAL: leaves made into tea for a spring tonic. Barbara Mullin\'s grandparents, both sets, including Ethel Goodbo Gamble, believed in the health-inducing properties of sassafras tea, drunken as a spring tonic. Barbara said, \"My grandfather said on the first day of February that you had to have a cup of sassafras every day through the month of February and then you would not be ill all year . . . And he lived to be 93.\"  Her brother-in-law owns several trees and gets the roots for selling. She goes out every year to collect the roots, except this last year. \"We always knew what it looked like, at that state [without leaves]. It has a certain smell . . . You can tell.\" They would cut the gathered roots into small segments and boil. Patches need to be identified in the summer, so they could return in the winter to the right place\" (Interview with Barbara Mullin, 2003); 3. MEDICINAL: sassafras tea was considered a tonic. \"And sassafras, of course, has always been known since the earliest days of this country, in the Middle West and all the way to the coast of South Carolina.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 4. MEDICINAL: sassafras tea made from root and used as a blood thinner/conditioner (Interview with Miami elders, Rafert 1992:45); 5. MEDICINAL: tea made (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 6. MEDICINAL: used roots to make tea (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 7. MEDICINAL: root used to prevent bleeding, the pith used in treating sore eyes, and tea used in spring. \"the pulverized root is an aboriginal remedy against bleeding, its pith is helpful fore sore eyes, it is drank in spring time as we drink tea or coffee. Being considered as the best blood purifier it was called medicine bush. Sassafras officinale, it belongs to the family of the laurineae and is a native of the united states. As it furnishes one of the most important remedies to the Indians, they call it for short the medicine tree, either m., or m. tawani. They drink the decoction of the root, m. tchipki chiefly in spring time as a drug as tea and as an every day beverage and regard it as the best blood purifier. The pulverized root is their remedy against bleeding, its pith is helpful for soreness of the eyes\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1052); 8. MEDICINAL: roots harvested for making tea. \"The tea is good all year long, but especially in the spring when you get fresh root.\" For storage can make shavings and dry. (Interview with Dani Tippman and Mary (Strack) Swenda, 2005); 9. MEDICINAL: roots dug up, sliced, boiled and steeped in water to make tea. Honey added for taste. Used in the longhouse during a sweat (Interview with George Dorin, 2005); 10. UNKNOWN: \"makinjak8i\", sassafras (Pinet 1696-ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', '1. Collect roots in January. \"You need to know what it looks like without leaves. . . it has a certain smell, . . . you can tell. Pull up small trees and get roots. You have to go to different patches [so you don\'t kill all the trees in one patch].\" (Interview with Barbara Mullin, 2003); 2. Collect roots in early spring. Tie a ribbon to stems in the fall to remember which stems to dig up. The cut roots resprout usually (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2004); 3. Smaller roots (1/2 to 2 inches diameter) harvested in fall, around the end of October, when the sap is down, always offering tobacco as he harvests. Once he harvested a 3-4\" diameter root, but only took the top half of the root, and left the bottom intact so the root could still grow. He covered the exposed portion of the root with sassafras bark and packed earth back around it (Interview with George Dorin, 2005);', NULL, '1. Barbara Mullin\'s recipe for sassafras tea: boil a few pieces of sassafras roots. Simmer for about 20 minutes until tea is clear and very bright pink/red. Add sugar or honey if desired. Serve hot (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(3):14, 1999); 2. The Miami word \'mankii?aahkwaapowi\' means sassafras tea, and incorporates the Miami words for medicine, bush and drink (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(3):14, 1999); 3. Sassafras jelly recipe from Barbara Mulllin, from a Choctaw, includes sassafras tea, honey, and sassafras root bark (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(2):14, 1999); 4. Oil from roots are aromatics, stimulants, diaphoretic 000?, diuretic, aseptic and astringent. This oil is used mostly as a flavor. Large doses causes circulatory depression and respiratory paralysis. Oil is reported to cause contraction of the uterus and abortion (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 5. Due to lead, cadmium and zinc contamination in the Tar Creek Superfund Site\'s watershed, around Miami, Oklahoma and the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma\'s headquarters, Miami and other local tribal members worry that traditional gathering of food, medicine and customs items may be contaminated. Fish, wild blackberries, sassafras, pokeweed, basket-making supplies and wild onions could have high concentrations of lead, as do the waters of nearby lakes, and it is not always successful keeping tribal members out of these areas. The Seneca-Cayuga\'s berry dance could not be held, if all the wild blackberries and strawberries in the area are found to be contaminated (Tulsa World 7/13/2003); 6. Charlevoix describes use of tree sap and sassafras against palsy, dropsy and venereal diseases, by the general Great Lakes region tribes (Charlevoix 1682-1761:174, from Kellogg 1923:161-162); 7. \"Recurring ague and fever however, was a condition affecting the lands in the Miami Tribe claim as of the dates of this appraisal\" (Hoyt 1959:121)--possibly the \"ague\" tree was used in the treatment of diseases like malaria;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(218, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDQ0Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Scirpus validus Vahl.', 'Softstem bullrush', 'Cyperaceae (Sedge)', 'alaansooni', NULL, '1. Occurs in marshes and muddy shores of lakes and streams, tolerant of alkalai (Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. Occurs in marshes (Pease 1934:316, Deliette 1721);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: long mats or smaller mats, to be used as bed mats, approximately the size of settler\'s beds circa 1895. When to be used as a bed mat, it is our size of beds and laid on the ground\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1772); 2. MATERIAL: bed mat that is the length and width of settler\'s beds circa 1909, and is laid bare on the ground (Dunn ca. 1900, Peoria); 3. MATERIAL: mats made from rushes. \"At night most of the men, seated like dogs on mats of round reeds, play with straws\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:351, \"et la nuit comme des Chiens la plus part assis sur des nattes de joncs ronds jouent avec des pailles,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 4. CUSTOMS: rush mat used for dancing upon during peace-making ceremony (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:28); 5. MATERIAL: women are in charge of making the mats (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:46); 6. CUSTOMS: pre-war singing. \"they invite them to a feast and tell them that the time is approaching to go in search of men, so it is well to pay homage, according to their custom, to their birds so that these may be favorable. They all answer with a loud Ho! And after eating with great appetite they all go get their mats and spread out their birds on a skin stretched in the midle of the cabin and with the chichicoyas they sing a whole night . . . \" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:376, \"ils les invitent dans un festin Et leur disent comme Voila Le temps qui approche pour aller chercher des hommes il est bon de rendre les devoirs selon leur Coutume a leurs oyseaux afin qu\'ils leurs soient favorables, Ils repondent tous par un grand ho, Et apres avoir mange d\'un grand appetit, ils Vont querir chacun Leur nattes etendent tous Leurs oyseaux dessus une peau qui est estendue au milieu de la Cabane Et avec des Chichicoya chante une nuit entiere,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 7. MATERIAL: mat made of softstem bullrush used as a bundle for carrying herbal medicines to cure those wounded in war. \"the commander carries his mat, into which all his men have put their birds, along with a good stock of herbs for healing the wounded\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:379,  \"Le Commandant porte sa Natte dans laquelle tout son monde a mis ses oyseaux, ou il y a bonne provision d\'herbes pour panser Les Blessez,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 8. CUSTOMS: mats made from softstem bullrush are part of a funeral ceremony dance for the warrior who loved the dance. \"A large number of mats are spread outside around these forks [forked pieces of wood, with cross pieces, from which are hung gifts to deceased warrior who has loved the dance--see cultural use entry #20, for \"Wood\"], the drummer is there near by and the Chichichoirs. They seat themselves round about, usually stark naked, and tie the skin of the virile member, sometimes fastening it at the belt. One of them begins his role with war whoops, and they represent in dancing the tableaux presented when they discover the enemy, when they kills him, and when they take his scalp, or when they take him prisoner, and they do all this without losing the cadence. They call this dance the discovery. The women during this time are weeping in his cabin. When the dance is over, the nearest relative of the dead for whom they dance, pointing with a wand [to the gifts handing on the wooden rack] says: This is for you, Peoria; this is for you, Coiracoentanon, and so on\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:359-360, \"Quantites de nattes sont estendues dehors autour de ces fourches, Le tombeau est la tout press Et les chichicoir, ils s\'assisent autour ordinairement tous nuds se Lient la peau du membre Viril Et quelquefois se l\'attachent au col ou a la Ceinture Et un d\'eux commence son entr??e, par des cris de guerre et representent en dansant les figures qu\'on fait quand on decouvre L\'ennemy, qu\'on le tue et qu\'on luy leve la Chevelure, ou qu\'on le fait prisonnier, Et tout cela sans perdre la Cadance on appelle cette danse la decou;', '1. \". . . one of them went off three or four arpents into a hollow, which in spring is nothing but a sort of marsh and brought back a bundle of round reeds as thick as one fingers.\" (Pease 1934:316, Deliette 1721; \"un d\'eux fut a 3. ou 4. arpents dans un fond ou le printemps ce n\'est qu\'une maniere de marais, et apporterent une botte de Roseaux ronds qui sont gros comme les doigts,\" translation from French to English by Pease);', ')', '1. The word \'mizanikani\' means fabric, straw, or any other rushes (Scirpus spp.) that were used for the purposes listed (author\'s notes); 2. There is a coiled basket that is possibly made of softstem bullrush, housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, in Washington D.C. (see attachment, NMAI items); 3. Algonquian women, in general, made the mats for roofing or flooring of dwellings. They also carried  these mats when they traveled by foot. \"The obligations of women are to . . .make . . . mats of rushes (either flat or round, or long) to serve as roofing for the cabins or as mattresses. . . . When they are traveling, the women carry the roofing for the cabin, if there is no canoe. (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:75-76); 4. Upon the death of a man\'s brother Algonquians, neighbors to the surviving brother offer the deceased two gifts in order to remove the tears of his relatives; a mat to lie on and a piece of bark to shelter the corpse from the weather. \"In the speech which they [neighbors] accompany this gift they declare that it is made in order to wipe away the tears of his relatives; and that the mat which they give him is for him to lie on, or [that they give--Blair\'s note] a piece of bark to shelter his corpse from the injurious effects of the weather\" (1680-1718, from Blair 1911:80); 5.The Miami-Illinois term \"keentowasiki\" is used generally for rush, or bulrush. Gatschet notes that it is probably an adjective word, meaning \"sharp-cutting\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', 'TRUE', 'mizanikani (rel info 1), keentowasiki (rel info 5)', NULL, '(sharp-cutting, Gat.)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(219, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo5NDk1NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Senna obtusiflolia (L.) Irwin & Barneby and S. occidentalis (L.) Link.', 'Senna, Coffee Senna, Coffee Weed', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', NULL, NULL, '1. S. obtusifolia is a native species that is now pantropical and found in moist woods in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991), and S. occidentalis is a native of the Old World tropics but naturalized in eastern and western Miami lands in sandy and alluvial soils along streams and disturbed areas (Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: leaves made into laxative. Sugar balls infused with senna, in center, recipe by Effie Louella (pimyotahmah) Walker Brown (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(2):10, 2002); 2. MEDICINAL: senna balls rolled in sugar eaten for strengthening the blood  but too much could cause diarrhea (Interview with Letha Beam, MTO Language Camp, Longhouse, Miami, OK, 6/6/03);', NULL, NULL, '1. Referring to cultural use as a laxative by Effie--in same discussion, Watona relayed that in the Miami tradition, medicinal knowledge was passed on orally to the opposite sex child, therefore Effie and great aunt Myrtle Walker Fuller (shegoquah) were not taught the medicinal knowledge of their mother, Rebecca Stitt (Pimyotomah) Walker, a well know mid-wife and medicine woman in Lincolnville, OK at the turn of the century. Rebecca was the daughter of Mary Benjamin Stitt (Kepahkakasequah, who was relocated from Indiana to Kansas. Effie and her sister reportedly learned Miami herbal medicine by sneaking around the woods as Rebecca foraged teaching her sons (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(2):10, 2002); 2. Dried leaflets, in small doses (2 gm) has physiological action as a laxative, purgative, and cholagogue 000?, also increasing the flow of bile; 3. Leaves of Senna obtusifolia are believed to possess the purgative qualities that are associated with the pharmaceutical drug \'senna\', and leaves of Senna occidentalis are used to make an ointment used as a remedy for ringworm and other skin problems (Steyermark 1963:875);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(220, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2NDk2OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Solanum tuberosum L.', 'Potato', 'Solanaeceae (Potato)', 'ahpena (also for wild potato)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: modern traditional crop. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(221, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo0NDMyODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Solidago sp. L.', 'Goldenrod', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', NULL, NULL, '1. Common species often occur in opening in woods, prairies, oldfields, meadows and disturbed areas (author\'s note):', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: tea made for unspecified purpose. Leaves gathered and dried, before it budded or bloomed (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(222, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNTo2MzE1Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Symplocarpus foetidus (L.) Nutt.', 'Skunk cabbage', 'Araceae (Arum)', '≈°ikaakweeni≈°i≈°', NULL, '1. Occurs in swamps, and on moist low ground in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"the Miamis use cikakwai\'nji for the skunk cabbage, or swamp cabbage, Symplocarpus foetidus\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: boiled and eaten as greens, \"at the right stage when it first came up.\" It was still eaten by tribal members and others he knew when he was a young man and even at the time of the interview (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:91-92); 3. UNKNOWN: \"chingishimintchi\" (Gravier ca. 1700); 4. FOOD: gathered, cooked and eaten (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. McPherson wrote, \"The Indians [undescribed tribe] left the roots in pits with hot coals for two to three days before eating them.\" (1977:40, 2ndy source without primary source citation);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(223, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNToxNDAwOToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Tanacetum huronense Nutt. or T. vulgare L.', 'Eastern tansy', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', 'pileelikwa ansooyi', NULL, '1. Eastern tansy, T. huronense is a native, occuring in riverbanks and shores in eastern Miami lands (Common tansy, T. vulgare, is an introduced species occuring in roadsides, fields and other disturbed areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands) (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: leaves chewed or made into tea for what was called \"summer complaint\" or \"chills and fevers\" (Interviews with Miami elders, Rafert 1992:45);', NULL, NULL, '1. Translation from Miami-Illinois means \'flying squirrel\'s tail\' (Costa 2003, email)--descriptive category--morphologcal;', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'flying squirrel\'s tail', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:25', '2017-09-19 22:48:25')
(224, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzgxOToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Taraxacum officinale Weber ex Wiggers', 'Common dandelion', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in lawns and other disturbed areas throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: greens canned  (Interview of Swan Hunter and Eva Bossley, Rafert 1978); 2. FOOD: \"Before the white people came here, they was no dandelions. Dandelions were imported. But once they became acquainted with the dandelions, they used them quite a bit.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989); 3. FOOD: leaves eaten as greens (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 4. FOOD: plants gathered. \"[We] had a line of catalpa trees. And so then they\'d [the older Indian women from the Catholic church near Mildred\'s home, growing up in Miami] set down with a knife and try to cut out the dandelions\" (Interview with Mildred Walker, Olds, Olds and Tippman 1999); 5. FOOD: leaves picked and blanched, not cooked, and vinegar added and sometimes garlic for flavoring. \"Anything to make them a little different so you didn\'t think you were eating grass\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 6. UNKNOWN: (Northeastern Oklahoma Tribal Impact: Areas related to the Tar Creek Superfund Site, 9/2/2003. Report made by the Peoria, Eastern Shawnee, Wyandotte, Seneca-Cayuga, Miami and Ottawa, listing plants commonly used by the tribes, and their lead content); 7. FOOD: young leaves collected and eaten. Cooked with bacon drippings in past, or just boiled with butter and salt. Also eaten raw in a salad (Interview with Dani Tippman, Mary (Strack) Swenda and Mary Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(225, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MzUyMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Tephrosia virginiana (L.) Pers.', 'Turkey pea', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', NULL, NULL, '1. \". . . you find them in the the woodlands. The first of all the flowering plants that grows in the woods is the turkey pea . . . \"(Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: tuber eaten, \"And the way they found out they were good to eat--originally, what the story goes--is that the wild turkey nebbed them up on the leaves in the early spring. And that little tiny potato, in finding what they were eating, they tasted \'em and found out that they were edible. It took a lot of \'em to sustain you, but they were edible, and good to eat raw. They taste much like eating a raw sweet potato. . . You find them in the woodlands. The first of all the flowering plants that grows in the woods is the turkey pea or the salt and pepper\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:98-99);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(226, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo3NjI5MDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Thuja occidentalis L.', 'Northern white cedar', 'Cupressaceae (Cypress)', NULL, '1. Two species were commonly called white cedar, according to Small (1903), including Thuja occidentalis, and Chamaecyparis thoides, also known as cypress, but is found predominately on the coastal plain (Small 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', '1. Occurs in moist soils and swamps in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: used as a baseboard when hand-starting fires. \"One of the pieces of wood which they use to make a fire is of white cedar, which is the most combustible, a foot long more or less, according as they choose to make it, and as thick as two fingers. On one side, on the very edge, they make little holes, in which they make a notch. They put this bit of wood on some rotten wood or on some grass, dry and very fine, after taking care to crush it thoroughly in their hands. The other piece of wood is as thick as the little finger, it is a bit of a wood that has a black berry, which we call morette. When this wood is green it is very soft, and it is proportionately hard when it is dry. They shape the end to the size of the holes in the other piece of wood, into one of which they insert it, and by turning it in their hands without ceasing, they produce a sort of powder from which, after a very short time, one sees smoke issue, which shortly is converted into flame. This coming through the notch of which I have just spoken, falls on the rotten wood or dry grass, which is ignited\" (Pease 1934:317-318, Deliette 1721, \"un de ces morceaux  don??t on se sert pour faire du feu est de Cedre blanc qui est le p\"s combustible d\'un pied plus ou moins de long,', NULL, NULL, '1. Great Lakes tribes, in general, used the sap squeezed from the ends of well-boiled cedar branches for the treatment of bloody-flux [?] (Charlevoix 1682-1761:174, from Kellogg 1923:162);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(227, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo0MTgxNDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Tilia americana L.', 'Basswood, American linden', 'Tiliaceae (Linden)', 'wiikapimi≈°i', NULL, '1. Found in rich woods throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: cordage from inner bark of \"linn\" tree. \"For temporary use this needed no preparation. When boys went hunting with men, it was their first work to get linn bark to hobble the horses, while the men hunted. When rope was wanted for permanent use, the women boiled this bark, and twisted or braided it while it was damp\", \"fresh inside bark was used\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. TECHNOLOGY: rope, greater than 2 cm diameter was made from \"whitewood bark\" by a soldier staying in an Illinois encampment (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:351, \"elle etoit d\'ecorce de Bois blanc, traissee plus grosse que le poulce,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 3. TECHNOLOGY: cordage for fishing nets made from nettles and wild hemp. The women gather, spin and twist lengths of cordage on their bare thighs. The cords used to draw these nets are made of the bark of basswood or leather. With these nets many fish and beaver are captured. They also fish with still lines up to 90 meters long [possibly of the same cordage material] (Raudot 1904:Letter 41; secondary source for Deliette 1721); 4. MATERIAL: women \"gather reeds in which they sew a twine made of basswood to make a sort of straw mat which covers their cabins. Two, one over the other, shelters them from the greatest rain\" (Raudot 1904:Letter 59, secondary source for Deliette 1721);  5. MATERIAL: bark peeled off trees and used to cover houses, using poles. \"There was a tree they called linn trees, they would peel the bark off them and cover their houses and tie \'em down with a pole. Buckskin type\" (Interview with Rose Carver by J.W. Tyner, Miami, OK, 9/9/1968, in MTO Archives); 6. TECHNOLOGY: bark used to make cordage. In a traditional story, Wissakatchakwa was telling an old man how to catch birds. \"Peel a bunch of basswood-bark off the trees. Then dive into the lake, and tie the basswood bark to their feet. And . . . Tie them to your belt.\" He did this, then told all the ducks, geese, swans, and brants they had to leave. They flew away and carried him with them, until the bark broke . . . \" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from the traditional story Wissakatchakwa, told by George Finely, in Peoria); 7. MATERIAL: there are 2 items that are possibly made with plant fibers, which could include dogbane, nettles or basswood, among others, at the Cranbrook Institute in Michigan (see attachment, Cranbrook items); 8. TECHNOLOGY: cordage made from inner bark. \"The lesser occupations of the women and what is their common employment in their cabbins, are the making of threat from the interior pellicles of the bark of a tree, called white-wood [basswood], which they manufacture nearly as we do hemp (Charlevoix 1682-1761:125, from Kellogg 1923:116); 9. MEDICINAL: root used to treat burns. \"The root of the whitewood boiled for burns\" (Anonymous 1724:164A, \"De la racine de bois blanc bouillee pur la Bruleur\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004; the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 10. TECHNOLOGY: bark used to make rope. Akwaanaapiikatoo, climb with a rope. \"I climb by means of a cord, a vine, a long strong cord of bark from white wood\" (Gravier ca. 1700:010.12; \"je monte par une corde, une vigne, une babiche longue et forte, de l\'ecorces de bois blanc\"); 11. TECHNOLOGY: bark used, probably for rope. \"lania paxshakinanga wikapi-mizha, a man jerks off the bark from a linn-tree\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1760); 13. UNKNOWN: (sl 000?:060, 001, tb.sw 000?:011, as.sw 000?:002); 14. UNKNOWN: \"8akapimingi\", basswood (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, '1. Fibers from this tree were the most commonly used by all Eastern North American Indians in the manufacturing of many items, including a Menomini bag using carefully prepared fibers, a Potawatomi bag, a Sauk and Fox bag, and Hopewell textiles. Basswood was used in an unprocessed form, where strips were cut from the fiberous bast, and in a highly processed state, where bast was thoroughly treated and spun into fine thread (Whitford 1941); 2. Twine made from \"white wood\", probably Basswood, was used to tie together reeds, about 10-12 bands of these twines at 6 inch intervals along the reeds, to make coverings for their \"cabins\"  that were about 20 meters (\"10 fathoms\") in length. They call them apacoya, a word which serves not merely to designate these, but which is a generic term for all sorts of coverings. They use the same term for bark boards, and two of these apacoyas, one on top of the other, protect one from the rain as well as the best blanket. These are the cabins which they use in autumn and winter; even if they leave their canoes, the women carry these on their backs (Pease 1934:340-341, Deliette 1721, \"quelques jours apres ces femmes qui restent s\'en vont dans des pirogues don??t elles ont jusqu\'a trois dans chaques cabanes, couper des joncs don??t ils Couvrent leurs Cabannes, ce sont de ceux qui croissent dans leurs marais qui apportent des quenouilles lesquelles pres avoir oste une peau qui envelope plusieurs brins ensembles ils les font secher au soleil et passent une ficelle qu\'ils font de bois Blanc de l\'un a l\'autre, a dix ou douze endroits de distance d\'environ demy pieds, ils en font qui ont jusqu\'a dix brasses de longueur, ils appellent cela apacoya, ce n\'est pas que ce mot servent seulement a cela, c\'est un mot qui est generique pour toutes sortes de couvertures, ils disent de mesme pour des planches, et deux de ces apacoya L\'un sur l\'autre, metent aussi bien a la pluye que la meilleure couverture, se sont les Cabanes dont ils se servent l\'automne et l\'hiver, quoy quils quittent leurs pirogues, les femmes les portent sur leurs dos,\"ranslation from French to English by Pease); 3. Algonquians play a game called crosse, played with a wooden ball and racket with a netted end, like a tennis racket. \"There is among them a certain game, called crosse, which has much likenes to our game of long tennis . . . You will see them all equipped with the crosse--which is a light club, having at one end a broad flat part that is netted like a racket [possibly dogbane, basswood, nettles, or another strong fiber\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:93);ii', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(228, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjoxNzI1OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Trifolium pratense L.', 'Red clover', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', '(nihsopakati) (generic for clover)', NULL, '1. A native of Europe occurring in oldfields, roadsides and disturbed areas as an escape from cultivation (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: this clover was planted (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'eensewatoonki', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(229, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1MzE5NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Trifolium repens L.', 'White clover', 'Fabaceae (Pea or Bean)', '(nihsopakati) (generic for clover)', NULL, '1. A native of Eurasia occurring in roadsides and disturbed areas as an escape from cultivation (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"nasopaki, clover\" and \"nasopaki anewatungi, red [clover]\" (Dunn ca. 1900:1232-3dw);', NULL, NULL, '1. The word \'neehsopaki\' refers to both white clover and other clover species (Dunn circa 1909);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(230, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMjM3OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Typha latifolia L.', 'Cattail', 'Typhaceae (Cattail)', 'apahkwaya', NULL, '1. Occurs in ponds, marshes, and many other wet areas throughout eastern (Gleason and Cronquist 1991) and western Miami lands (?); 2. \"Along any of the slower moving streams you\'d find the cattail. There were a lot of wetlands, a lot of \'em in this country, especially around old burns and where old villages had been. The cattail seed was carried in there by birds and flourished there\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: mats, roof thatching. \"The Peorias made a long mat, lasuni, from scirpus [sic] growing in these parts. One of these is a flat scirpus, pakwayaki, used for thatching lodges\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. MATERIAL: mats made from cattail leaves are called \"lansuni\" and are used for covering lodges. \"these mats lansuni serve for thatching lodges. After made into mats, these are called lansuni\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1753); 3. MATERIAL: used for making walls and roofs of cabins, easily carried in a bundle while hunting. \"As Bark for making cabins is scarce in this county, They use Rushes [sic]; these serve Them for making walls and Roofs, but do not afford them much protection against the winds, and still less against the rains when they fall abundantly. The Advantage of Cabins of this kind is, that they make packages of Them, and easily transport them wherever they wish, while they are hunting\" (Marquette 1673, from Thwaites 1966:103, \"Comme le Escorces a faire des Cabbanes sont rares en ce pays la, Ils se seruent de Joncs qui Leur tiennent lieu de murailles et de Couuertures, mais qui ne les deffendent pas beaucoup des vents, et bien moins des pluyes quand elles tombent en abondance. La Commodite de ces sortes de Cabbanes est qu\'ils Les mettent en pacquetz et les portent aisement ou ils veulent pendant Le temps de leur chasse,\" translation from French to English by Thwaites); 4. MATERIAL: coverings for dwellings made from cattails. \"Some days after this [after the village sets out on the buffalo hunt, after hilling up their corn at the beginning of June] the women who remain go off in canoes, of which they have as many as three in each cabin, to cut reeds with which they cover their cabins. These are a kind that grow in their marshes. They procure bundles of them, which, after removing a skin that encloses several blades conjointly, they dry in the sun and tie together with twine which they make of white wood, with ten or twelve bands at intervals of about six inches. They make these up to ten fathoms [approximately 20 meters] in length. They call them apacoya, a word which serves not merely to designate these, but which is a generic term for all sorts of coverings. They use the same term for bark boards, and two of these apacoyas, one on top of the other, protect one from the rain as well as the best blanket. These are the cabins which they use in autumn and winter, even if they leave their canoes, the women carry these on their backs\" (Deliette 1721, from Pease 1934:340-341, \"quelques jours apres ces femmes qui restent s\'en vont dans des pirogues don??t elles ont jusqu\'a trois dans chaques cabanes, couper des joncs don??t ils Couvrent leurs Cabannes, ce sont de ceux qui croissent dans leurs marais qui apportent des quenouilles lesquelles pres avoir oste une peau qui envelope plusieurs brins ensembles ils les font secher au soleil et passent une ficelle qu\'ils font de bois Blanc de l\'un a l\'autre, a dix ou douze endroits de distance d\'environ demy pieds, ils en font qui ont jusqu\'a dix brasses de longueur, ils appellent cela apacoya, ce n\'est pas que ce mot servent seulement a cela, c\'est un mot qui est generique pour toutes sortes de couvertures, ils disent de mesme pour des planches, et deux de ces apacoya L\'un sur l\'autre, metent aussi bien a la pluye que la meilleure couverture, se sont les Cabanes dont ils se servent l\'automne et l\'hiver, quoy quils quittent leurs pirogues, les femmes les portent sur leurs dos,\"ranslation from French to English by Pease); 5. FOOD: \"They ate the cattail root, and the shoot. The shoot of the cattail mostly. The early shoots coming up, they ate \'em raw and they ate them cooked, both [including people of Marks\' generation],\" \"I suppose most of the people ate the cattail shoot as cooked. Although they can eat it raw. Its edible raw\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:99); 6. MATERIAL: to use, peel off leaves and split the thick base of the leaves widthwise and place either side on a si;;;', '1. Collected in August, when leaves are longer, collect green (Interview with Gary and Scott Shoemaker, and Phyllis Miley, 2003); 2. In early spring, can harvest early shoots and cook like asparagus, \"very good, sweet\". Make sure to only get the shoots that are white with a green tip. In late spring can harvest roots, \"some as big as your wrist, long as your forearm\", cut up, fry, bake or eat raw. In winter roots can be dug up, \"but by then they\'re old and tend to be wormy\" (Interview with George Dorin, 2004);', NULL, '1. Mats made out of cattail stems, which are stood upright to cover wiikiaami, 250-300 stems used for a six foot long mat, stems wrapped together with cordage (Norm Trundall and Andrew at Woodland Village at Mihsiihkanaakwa Pow Wow, Carolyn Knopf and husband, 2003); 2. Apaquois, Pottowatomi word for rush (000); 3. Rush used for mats, the common cat-tail (Ojibwe 000); 4. Hapkwa, Shawnee word for cattail (000); apahkwaya, Fox word for cattail reed and cattail reed mat (000); 5. The Delawares of the past built and lived in little houses out of reeds [cattails] that grow in the lakes. The women would gather them and built the houses, and overlap them so they wouldn\'t leak (Kohn 1997:237, Interview with Edward Leonard Thompson, Delaware); 6. McPherson wrote, \"The Miami and Potawatomie Indians padded cradles and dressed wounds with cattail down, and used the sturdy leaves to roof the rounded tops of their wigwams\" (1977:27, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 7. Algonquian women, in general, made the mats for roofing or flooring of dwellings. They also carried  these mats when they traveled by foot. \"The obligations of women are to . . .make . . . mats of rushes (either flat or round, or long) to serve as roofing for the cabins or as mattresses. . . . When they are traveling, the women carry the roofing for the cabin, if there is no canoe. (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:75-76); 8. Gatschet (ca. 1895:1777) lists the term \"pakwansi\" or \'apahkweenhsa [modern Miami] as indicating a \"small or young reed of the pakwaya reed or flag species; 9. The Miami term \"mazaanikaani\" means tent (Gatschet ca. 1895:1147); 10. The Miami word \"mizanikani\" means fabric of straw or rushes used sometimes to make a tent (Dunn ca. 1900);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(231, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMTc1Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ulmus americana L.', 'American elm tree', 'Ulmaceae (Elm)', 'pahkokwani≈°i', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist, rich soils throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: young shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar fed to livestock during hard times (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938, possibly a different species in this genus); 2. MATERIAL: there is one item made from elm bark, a miniature sap trough, housed at the Cranbrook Institute in Michigan (see attachment, Cranbrook items); 3. MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred American elm timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184); 4. TECHNOLOGY: bark used for making canoes. \"The Miamis did not use birch-bark canoes, which the Algonquians usually called tci-maun, but they sometimes made canoes of hickory or elm bark. The name for these is la-kik-kwi-mis-so-li or bark canoe\" (Dunn 1908:manuscript 1701); 5. UNKNOWN: \"pakac8eningi\", american elm (Pinet ca. 1700:38-39, from Costa 2005:116-117);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(232, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1MDkzOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Ulmus rubra Muhl.', 'Slippery elm, or Red Elm, Piss elm', 'Ulmaceae (Elm)', 'a≈°aah≈°ikopa', '1. Scabrous leaves, inner bark of twigs red/rust colored, sightly fragrant and mucilaginous; facultative wetland species (NRCS database, 2006);', '1. Occurs in moist woods in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. UNKNOWN: slippery or white elm, refering to the bark (Gatschet ca. 1895); 2. UNKNOWN: used for something (Interview with Phyllis Miley, 2003); 3. MEDICINAL: a poultice of leaves made for rattlesnake bites (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy, 2ndy source of info.); 4. TECHNOLOGY: fishnet baskets were made for use at weirs in historic times. \"Before the commerical nets they made a basket net, which was out of bark, mostly elm bark. It was the inner bark of the elm tree, the slippery elm tree, which was the red elm tree, and it was a type of net, more in the shape of a basket. That\'s what they used at the weir\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:47), and \"Now you could be surprised what a thin net you can make out of elm bark. Elm bark, that was a basket maker, as well as hickory and white oak. But they made a real fine net out of elm bark . . . I\'ve heard the old people talk about it. It was flexible. The elm bark can be ripped down and pared down until its quite thin, it\'s almost like a cloth, see, when they get through withit. And they wasn\'t as open as a woven net would be, but it was fairly so, enough that water would pass throughit, or whatever, see\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:53, Lamoine remembers old Miami relatives and friends talking about these nets); 5. TECHNOLOGY: pigeon trap made from a wooden frame with bark nets (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:74-75, 2ndy source, either heard or read by Lamoine, original source unknown); 6. MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred Slippery elm timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184); 7. TECHNOLOGY: bark used to cover lodges, wigwams, houses. The word for roof is \'paxkwani\', very similar (Gatschet ca. 1895:1766); 8. UNKNOWN: \"cacikopa, slippery elm tree, i.e. slimy\" (Dunn ca. 1900:1952dw);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Peoria of OK cut up the tender shoots of hackberry, elm and poplar for cattle fodder (Interview with Edward Peckham, Burns 1938); 2. Fibers used to make woven fabrics by the Hopewell (Whitford 1941); 3. An ancient fishing weir dam still exists on the Wabash River, northeast of Peru, Indiana and was and is known to most Miami fishermen. Lamoine Marks was told about it when he was a boy, by his father Charlie, and last saw it while fishing in winter in 1953.  Rafert and Marks rediscovered it in July, 1988. This weir dam is described in Outdoor Indiana, July/August 1989 (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:47); 4. The Miami term \"pakkokwaniji\" refers to the common upland elm and \"pakkokwaninji sipiomakwi\" to the water elm (Dunn ca. 1900:1953, 1954);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(233, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjoxMTYxNDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Ulmus thomasii Sarg.', 'Rock elm', 'Ulmaceae (Elm)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in rich upland woods in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991) and low wet woods or floodplains of western Miami lands (Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MATERIAL: used in construction. Human-charred Rock elm timbers were recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 1996:184);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(234, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1MzU4Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Umbilicaria dillenii', 'Lichen or Tripe du Roche', 'Lichen', 'nipoopi minosakayi (words listed sep in dict)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: nipopi minosakayi (Gatschet ca. 1895); 2. UNKNOWN: minosakai (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. Umbilicaria dillenii, called \"tripe de roche\" by Perrot, was eaten by the Algonquians  that do not cultivate the ground, but are nomadic. \"They consider themselves very fortunate in their hunting expeditions when they encounter some rabbits, martens, or partridges, from which to make a soup; and without what we call tripe de roche--which you would say is a species of gray moss, dry, and resembling oublies [wafers used to stick papers together], and which of itself has only an earthy taste, and the flavor of the soup in which it is cooked--most of their families would perish of hunger\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:102-103); 2. \"It is used for food only as a last resort; and Father Andre well says of it: \"It is necessary to close one\'s eyes when one begins to eat it\" (Dunn 1919, from Jesuit Relations, Vol. 55, p. 151); 3. A flat-\'leafed\' lichen was eaten by the Ottawas. \"When hunger is added to these discomforts [excessive heat and cold], it is a severe hardship, but one that soon teaches a man to find a relish in the bitterest roots and the most putrid meat. We were forced to accustom ourselves to eat a certain moss growing upon the rocks. It is a sort of shell-shaped leaf which is always covered with catepillars and spiders, and which, on being boiled, furnishes an insipid soup, black and viscous, that rather serves to ward off death than to impart life\" (Allouez 1666-1667, from Kenton 1925:318); 4. Trippe de Roches also mentioned as a food source by Charlevoix, referring to wandering Indians of the midwest that do not cultivate the ground (Charlevoix 1682-1761:124, from Kellogg 1923:115);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'tripe soup', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(235, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2MzY3Njoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Urtica chamaedryoides Pursh.', 'Stinging nettle', 'Urticaceae', '(asossawia)', '1. Urtica chamaedryoides is the only stinging nettle within Miami territory that is about 1 foot tall (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', '1. Occurs in moist woods and thickets in the southern portions of eastern Miami lands and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"ashushuwia, nettle, or species of weed, the leaves of which produce a burning or itching juice and are hence regarded as poisonous. They bear no flower, the stalk is about 1 foot tall\" (Gatschet ca. 1895);', NULL, NULL, '1. Although no use is mentioned by Dunn or Gatschet for this species, the fact that a word was recorded leaves open the question if this nettle was also used for fiber. It is possible, but it would be a less desirable species due to its short stature and hence, shorter fibers (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'stinger', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(236, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo4NTY0Mjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Urtica dioica L. and/or U. chamaedryoides Pursh.', 'Stinging nettle', 'Urticaceae (Nettle)', '(aa≈°oo≈°iwia) (species of nettle)', '1. Urtica dioica is a much larger, perennial nettle than U. chamaedryoides, an annual (Steyermark 1963); 2. Gatschet: \"a week, the leaves of which produce a burning or sitching sap, and hence regarded as poisonous; no flowers, stalk about one foot\" (ca. 1895);', '1. Found in many habitats throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: cordage for fishing nets made from nettles and wild hemp. The women gather, spin and twist lengths of cordage on their bare thighs. The cords used to draw these nets are made of the bark of basswood or leather. With these nets many fish and beaver are captured. They also fish with still lines up to 90 meters long [possibly of the same cordage material] (Raudot 1904:Letter 41, secondary source for Deliette 1721); 2. MATERIAL: cordage. \"Before their knowledge of the whites they used belts made of the small bones found in the legs of swans and other large birds, which were attached by means of a cord composed of the fibres of the wild nettle. These were made with much labour, and were said to be admirably wrought. They soon exchanged them however for the wampum . . .\" (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:10); 3. MATERIAL: cordage fiber attaching history belts (000? info got cut off due to data transfer); 4. MATERIAL: there are Miami items made of \'hemp\', possibly dogbane or nettles, including a sack, medicine pouch and necklace cordage, all housed at the National Museum of the American Indian, in Washington D.C. (see attachment, NMAI items); 5. MATERIAL: there are 2 items that are possibly made with plant fibers, which could include dogbane, nettles or basswood, among others, at the Cranbrook Institute in Michigan (see attachment, Cranbrook items);', NULL, NULL, '1. One of the most important sources of fibers for Eastern North American Indians, where the plant tissues were almost always treated before fiber use. Many tribes simply peeled the bark from the plant and twisted it. Museum artifacts made with nettle fibers include a Delaware wampum string and burden strap, Micmac cordage to hold a knife blade to its handle, an Ojibway bow string, twelve Hopewell specimens, and other uses by Ohio cave and rock-shelter dwellers (Whitford 1941); 2. Documented as used by local Indians in the Kentucky area, the Shawnee, in a letter from Col. Nathan Boone, son of Daniel Boone, to Dr. Lyman Draper: \"Used to gather nettles, a sort of hemp, towards spring when it became rotted by the wet weather, and spin them, very strong--in rich lands grows four feet high: nettles the warp, and buffalo wool spun the filling--both spun. For socks buffalo wool alone was used--quite soft and wears very well.\" (Eckert 1967:595, Notes); 3. Algonquians play a game called crosse, played with a wooden ball and racket with a netted end, like a tennis racket. \"There is among them a certain game, called crosse, which has much likenes to our game of long tennis . . . You will see them all equipped with the crosse--which is a light club, having at one end a broad flat part that is netted like a racket [possibly dogbane, basswood, nettles, or another strong fiber\" (Perrot 1680-1718, from Blair 1911:93); 4. La Salle was one of the first to note the name of a tributary to the upper portion of Illinois River, called \'masaana [rope] siipiiwi\', which is the present day Kankakee River, so named for the surrounding land (present day Mazon, McCafferty 2004, pers. Comm.) where he noted a \'great quantity\' of hemp growing, possibly referring to fiber-producing plants like the nettle (Margry 1974:174, reprint 2, La Salle, between 1680-1693); 5. Gravier provided the term \"waapahsapiiki\" as plural for \'hemp cord\'; \"espece de chamvre don??t on fait des cordes asses blanches\" Pinet says \"corde dorties\" (Provided by Costa, per. Comm., 2006);i', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'stinger', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(237, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo1NzIzMToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Vaccineum stamineum L.', 'Deerberry', 'Ericaceae (Heath)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in dry woods (Small 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that deerberries were utilized as a food source by indigenous peoples sometime during the period of A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450 (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(238, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjozMzkzMjoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Vaccinium macrocarpon Aiton.', 'Cranberry', 'Ericaceae (Heath)', 'neehpikica', NULL, '1. Occurs in swamps/bogs in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. \"This area, northern part of the country [i.e. northern Wabash County, which still has several lakes and marshy areas] had wild cranberries, and huckleberries. But this area didn\'t have \'em. They had to be around a swampy area, around these buckbrush swamp wetlands. . . That\'s a spot in the woods where the bracken grows, and the edge of where the bracken grows is where you\'ll find the cranberries, in the marshy area.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: \"napikitca, cranberry\" (Dunn ca. 1900:1445dw); 2. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"Grandpa [Abraham Marks] canned cranberries.\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:103);', NULL, NULL, '1. Miami word probably refers to either Vaccinium macrocarpon, cranberry, or V. oxycoccus, small cranberry, the latter the only species listed in Small (1903) and only these two listed in Coulter (1899). Both these species plus V. vitis-idaea, mountain cranberry, are listed in Gleason and Cronquist (1991). V. macrocarpon is the one most commonly listed and was chosen as the probable representative of \'neehpikica\' (author\'s note);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(239, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo3MDYxNzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Vaccinium spp. L.', 'Blueberry', 'Ericaceae (Heath)', 'wiipinkwamini', '1. The blueberries referenced by Kenton could be any number of species, including V. angustifolium (common lowbush-blueberry), V. pallidum (hillside-blueberry), V. myrtilloides (velvetleaf blueberry),  V. corymbosum (highbush-blueberry), and V. stamineum (Squaw huckleberry), according to blueberry species listed in Coulter (1899) and using nomenclature from Gleason and Cronquist (1991)(author\'s note);', '1. All possible species occur in dry uplands soils, and all but V. stamineum occur in moist or swamp/bogs as well. V. angustifolium and V. myrtilloides occur only in portions of eastern Miami lands, while the remaining three species occur in both eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: blueberries brought to missionaries for eating (Kenton 1925:372, The Jesuit Relations, from 000); 2. FOOD: \"wipi\'ngwami\'ni, blueberry, same as huckelberry\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 3. FOOD: wild blueberries picked and eaten while growing up (Interview with George Dorin, 2005);', NULL, NULL, '1. Pow Wow by Pokagon band of Potawatomi tribe held on Labor Day in St. Patrick\'s Park near South Bend, Indiana, celebrates the end of blueberry season, and important ritual to this band who were farmers, hunters and gatherers (Schuckel, Kathleen. 2002. Travels among the Woodland tribes. May/June); 2. Dunn quotes Perrot who compares the Illinois/Miami with the \"Algonkins (i.e. the Canada tribe), the former who cultivate corn and other crops and the latter who primariy hunt. Of these people he states that \"they gather there [northern country] plenty of blueberries in the months of August and September, which they are careful to dry and keep for a time of need\" (Dunn 1919, from Blair\'s Indian Tribes, Vol. 1, p. 102); 3. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that blueberries were utilized as a food source by indigenous peoples sometime during the period of A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450 (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(240, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo2NjY1NDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Verbascum thapsus L.', 'Common mullein', 'Scrophulariaceae (Figwort)', NULL, NULL, '1. Native of Europe occurring in disturbed sites throughout eastern and western Miami lands and the U.S. (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: medicinal plant. \"It was also used in the case of wounds, or something like that\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:94-95); 2. MEDICINAL: mullein leaves used for bee stings (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy); 3. MEDICINAL: leaves used to treat sores, infections. The leaves were used on sores to draw out the poison and infection. \"Used more than poultices [for infections]\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 4. MEDICINAL: leaves gathered, cut into strips and boiled in water to make vapor for treating kids with a strong cough. Adults can roll dried leaves and smoke to cure strong cough (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(241, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjoyNzk2OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Verbena hastata L.', 'Common Vervain', 'Verbenaceae (Verbena)', NULL, NULL, '1. Occurs in moist fields, meadows, prairies and swamps throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: human-charred Vervain material was recovered from an early 19th century Miami village site at the forks of the Wabash River (Bush 996:181);', NULL, NULL, '1. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that verbena was utilized as a food source by indigenous peoples sometime during the period of A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450 (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(242, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNjo4NTU2Nzoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Vernonia spp. Shreber', 'Ironweed', 'Asteraceae (Aster or Sunflower)', '(ki≈°iinkwia)', '1. Shoe-string or iron-weed, (tepprosia?-Gatschet\'s notes), has stalks 3-4 feet high, with purple colored flowers (Gatschet ca. 1895); 2. V. fasciculata, V. baldwinii, V. drummondii,  or V. gigantea were all common in Oklahoma  in 1903 and could be the species for this Miami plant (Small 1903);', '1. Smooth ironweed (V. fasciculata Michx.), western ironweed (V. baldwinii Torr.), tall ironweed (V. gigantea Trel.), and ? (V. drummondii ?--see Small) all occur in prairies and woods in both eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: leaves made into poultices for sores. \"kishingwia . . . iron weed . . . leaves are used for poultices on sores\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:800); 2. MEDICINAL: the word \'takwakia\' may have referred to an ironweed used tea cleanse the blood (000?);', NULL, NULL, '1. \"Takwakia\" is the Miami word for another plant species called ironweed. (Gatschet ca. 1895);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:26', '2017-09-19 22:48:26')
(243, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozOTQwOjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Viburnum prunifolium L.', 'Blackhaw tree', 'Caprifoliaceae (Honeysuckle)', 'papakimi≈°aahkwi', '1. \"Papakimini tawani, black haw tree or bush. There are several bushes called so in the west, but this is either Crataegus tomentosa L. or Viburnum prunifolium L. and grows to a height of 15 to 20 feet\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1866);', '1. Occurs in woods, thickets and roadsides throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: traditional food. In the traditional story of Young Thunder (William Pecongah), he describes the crops he had growing on his land (160 acres of reserve) in central Indiana. \"There I planted corn, wheat, potatoes, peas, tobacco, beans, apple trees, pumpkins, watermelons, cucumbers, onions, hay, straw, gooseberries, raspberries, blackberries, currants, turnips, tomatoes, pawpaws, cherries, strawberries, plums, blackhaws, peaches, walnut trees, pecans, hickory nuts, barley and rye.\" (Gatschet ca. 1895, from William Pekongah, Indiana Miami, reworked by Dunn 1909); 2. FOOD: \"papakimina des alizes\" or \"papakiminja alizier\", blackhaw berries (Gravier ca. 1700:430.??); 3. FOOD: fruits eaten.  \"papakimini, papakimina, fruit or berry of the black haw, sweet tiny and of a black color, lit. flat berry, grows on holy bushes, blackhaw trees grow to a height of 15 to 20 feet\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:1844, 1225);', NULL, NULL, '1. Dried bark of Viburnum opulus var. americanum, cramp bark, in small doses (1-3 gm) is an antispasmodic, astringent, diuretic, and a tonic and sedative for the uterus (Coulter 1932, Published by Eli Lilly & Co.); 2. Blackhaw usually indicates Viburnum, whereas redhaw, or hawthorn or even black hawthorn indicate Crategeus spp. Blackhaw uses included Cherokee (drug/root-bark), Delaware (drug/root-bark), Micmac (drug), and Meskwaki (food/berry);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(244, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzoxNzU5OToy', 2, 0, 1, 'Vitis aestivalis Michx.', 'Wild grape', 'Vitaceae (Grape)', '(kiisiipitoonisinki assandepakwe)', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist or dry soil in roadsides, thickets, and open forests in eastern and western Miami lands (Steyermark 1903, Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. FOOD: fruits eaten. The blue-fall grape that ripens first, and \"tickling or itching the mouth\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:816); 2. FOOD: grapes gathered and preserved (Thwaites 1903:108, from Marquette 1673:200); 3. MEDICINAL: dried and used for boils and skin disorders (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy, 2ndy source); 4. FOOD: grapes (wild or domestic not distinguished) used for grape dumplings by tribes in 8 Tribes area (Miami, OK) (Interview of Judy Davis by Zach Kunkle, Miami, OK, 6/11/96, in MTO Archives); 5. FOOD: gathered and used to make grape cobbler. \"possum [coon] grapes were gathered growing up in trees for making grape cobbler, layered thick in a big rectangular pan\" (Interview with Eugene Brown, 2004a); 6. FOOD: wild grapes gathered and eaten. \"Made some beer . . . Not much luck with wine, though\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 7. TECHNOLOGY: vines used to make fish weirs. Gabriel Godfroy said that the Miamis used not nets or seines for fishing, but used spears, bows and arrows instead, and sometimes used movable weirs made of \"wattled brush\" and grape vines when fishing in a party, which they would force the fish to the shore (Dunn 1908:manuscript 1701); 8. FOOD: fruits eaten. \"the wild grape that ripens first, i.e. tickles the mouth when eaten\" (Dunn ca. 1900:2402); 9. FOOD: \"I pick grapes/I remove the skin from grapes\" (Gravier ca.1700:253.13, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter);', NULL, NULL, '1. The Shawnee collected this plant (Clark 1993); 2. Fruits ripen beginning in July, as opposed to V. labrusca, whose fruits ripen beginning in August/September (Author\'s note); 2. McPherson wrote \"We have read reports that the Indians [undescribed tribe] dried the grapes, ground them (seed and all), and used them to thicken soups\" (1977:151, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 3. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that grapes were utilized as a food resource by Late Woodland (800 A.D to 1450 A.D.) indigenous peoples of central and southern Indiana (Bush 2003); 4. Archaeological studies in central and south-central Indiana revealed that grapes were utilized as a food source by indigenous peoples sometime during the period of A.D. 1000 to A.D. 1450 (Bush 2003);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'tickling/itching mouth grape', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(245, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzo0NjI5OjI=', 2, 0, 1, 'Vitis labrusca L.', 'Fox grape', 'Vitaceae (Grape)', '(waawiipinkwaki)', NULL, '1. Occurs in woods, roadsides and thickets throughout eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. UNKNOWN: \"The fox grapes are as dark as Concord grapes, are sweet and grow east and west of Spring River, in Indian Territory.The Peorias call them wawipingwaki assandepakwa\" (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. UNKNOWN: \"asandapakwi wawipingwaki, fox grapes\" (Dunn ca. 1900:2401); 3. FOOD: wine grapes, called wawaepingwaki assandepakwa, for plural (Gatshet 1895); 4. FOOD: \"I pick grapes/I remove the skin from grapes\" (Gravier ca.1700:253.13, translation from French to English by Masthay/Suter 2003); 5. UNKNOWN: \"wawepingwaki assandepakwa, fox grapes\" (Gatschet ca. 1895:2566); 6. MEDICINAL: dried and used for boils and skin disorders (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy, 2ndy source); 7. FOOD: grapes (wild or domestic not distinguished) used for grape dumplings by tribes in 8 Tribes area (Miami, OK) (Interview of Judy Davis by Zach Kunkle, Miami, OK, 6/11/96, in MTO Archives); 8. FOOD: gathered and used to make grape cobbler. \"possum [coon] grapes were gathered growing up in trees for making grape cobbler, layered thick in a big rectangular pan\" (Interview with Eugene Brown, 2004a); 9. FOOD: wild grapes gathered and eaten. \"Made some beer . . . Not much luck with wine, though\" (Interview with Jim Strack, Tippman 1999); 10. TECHNOLOGY: vines used to make fish weirs. Gabriel Godfroy said that the Miamis used not nets or seines for fishing, but used spears, bows and arrows instead, and sometimes used movable weirs made of \"wattled brush\" and grape vines when fishing in a party, which they would force the fish to the shore (Dunn 1908:manuscript 1701);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, 'greyish grapes', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(246, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzoyNjU0ODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Xanthium sp. L. (X. spinosum L., probably)', 'Cocklebur', 'Asteraceae (Aster)', '(sakinteepwa)', NULL, '1. Both common cocklebur (X. strumarium) and spiny cocklebur (X. spinosum) occur as weeds throughout eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. UNKNOWN: sakindapwa (Gatschet ca. 1895); 2. UNKNOWN: saki\'ndapwa (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, '1. Gatschet listed the Miami term \"sakindapwa\" as the generic term for a bur, pine cone, or specific term for cocklebur (Gatschet ca. 1895:2066); 2. Dunn also listed the Miami term \"saki\'napwa\" for cocklebur (Dunn ca. 1900);', 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(247, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzo5MjIyODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Yucca filamentosa L.', 'Yucca, Soap-plant', 'Liliaceae (Lily)', NULL, NULL, '1. Native to southern areas of the U.S. and escaped northward to Miami lands. Occurring in roadsides and human-disturbed dry areas in western and some portion of eastern Miami lands (Illinois) with naturalization in greater portion of eastern Miami lands (Henn 1998);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: dried flowering stalk used to start fires (Interview with Eugene Brown, 2004a, use of Yucca he has learned as an adult, not necessarily from a Miami tradition);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(248, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzozMTA3ODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Zanthoxylum americanum Mill.', 'Common prickly ash', 'Rutaceae (Rue)', 'seenanka≈°ia', NULL, '1. Occurs in moist woods and thickets in eastern and western Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991);', NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. MEDICINAL: leaves used for mosquito bites and infections (Lamb and Shultz 1964:38, information in publication from Clarence Godfroy); 2. MEDICINAL: bark used to draw off pus. \"The bark of the prickly wood type of ash to draw off pus\" (Anonymous 1724:165A, \"De l\'ecoise de Bois piquant maniere de fresne pour attire Le pus\", translation from French to English by Poirier 2004, the author is describing tribal customs from the upper Midwest, probably including some of the Miami-Illlinois tribal groups); 3. UNKNOWN: \"sanangacia, prickly ash\" (Dunn ca. 1900);', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'FALSE', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(249, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzo2MDEyMDoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Zea mays L.', 'Corn, Maize (numerous varieties)', 'Poaceae (Grass)', 'miincipi (generic)', '1. Miami white corn--has very starchy consistency when in milk stage, will make your fingers white with milk when kernel\'s are crushed, unique appearance with deep red roots and red silks, long ear of only eight rows so it looks skinny (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 3(3):9, 2000); 2. \"a soft white corn. It was a dull white corn. It had a large grain and a very small cob--the cob was a long, slender cob. A full ear of corn wouldn\'t be that long, and the cob wouldn\'t be any bigger than my finger here. The grains were like that and rounded, they were rounded. And sometimes there\'d be a purple grain here and there\" \"we called it squaw corn\"(Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:69); 3. \"they [the Miamis] have a finer maize\", (Dunn 1919); 4. \"It is whiter, of the same size as the other [corn], the skin much finer, and the meal much whiter.\" This is probably what the Miamis called no-kin\'-gwa-mi-ni, or soft corn, because it ground easily (Dunn 1919, quote from N.Y. Col. Docs., Vol. 9, p. 891);', '1. Occurring as a cultivated species and occasionally as an escape throughout eastsern and western Miami lands (Steyermark 1963, Gleason and Cronquist 1991); 2. Miami corn was and is unique to the Great Lakes Region (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki 3(1):9, 2000);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'TRUE', '1. TECHNOLOGY: fodder (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. TECHNOLOGY): (trade) white corn a prized trade item (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki (2ndy source) 3(3):9, 2000); 3. FOOD: popcorn, peenkiteeki miincipi, lit. corn that explodes by heat (email from Costa 2006, Dunn?); 4. FOOD: white corn meal makes corn mush, a traditional dish in Barbara Mullin\'s household (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(2):14, 1999); 5. FOOD: corn dried on a rack. \"She started in drying it on racks. What\'d he call it?--he called it a \"scaffel\". It was built with four poles sunk in the round and leveled up level, and then cross sections nailed across the top, way up off the ground, maybe as much as six feet off the ground, or more. Then he made that solid, solid board. And he covered it with paper, newspapers in those days, and my mother got mosquito netting. She\'d put the corn on this paper or oilcloth--later in years she used oilcloth. Then over this whole thing she put rock on each corner and in the middle like this here (motions)--and a higher one in the middle, and the mosquito netting was tucked underneath that to keep the flies off of it, and birds.\" Its size: \"I\'d say . . .six by five would be about it. They dried apples up there, they dried corn up there, different seasons, of course\". Probably a mixture of a traditional drying structure and white influence (Dunn mentions tables for drying corn in field notebook 4), He didn\'t know anyone that ground it.(Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:69-71); 6. FOOD: Barbara Mullin\'s grandmother, Ethel Goodbo Gamble made hominy (in their Commerce home), by putting wood ashes into a bucket, filling it with water, and letting it sit. The water became lye-water, as they called it. Corn would then be placed into the bucket and the water would do its work--loosening the hull from the corn and swelling the corn up. Then the corn was rinsed in clear water many times. This was used to make edible dried corn (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 1(3):14, 1999); 7. FOOD: Miami corn dishes: kitasakani (parched corn), mahtohkatwi (cooked hominy), mihtohkatoopowi (corn soup), and corn bread (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 2(4):1, 1999); 8. FOOD: \"The kinds of food which the savages [Miami\'s] like best, and which they make the most effort to obtain, are the Indian corn, the kidney bean, and the squash. If they are without these they think they are fasting, no matter what abundance of meat and fish they may have in their stores, the Indian corn being to them what bread is to Frenchmen\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translated from French to English by Blair 1911:102); 9. FOOD: prepared with milk. \"They have in especial a certain method of preparing squashes with the Indian corn cooked while in its milk, which they mix and cook together and then dry, which has a very sweet taste. Finally, melons grow there which have a juice no less agreeable than refreshing\" (Perrot 1680-1718, translation from French to English by Blair 1911:113); 10. FOOD: corn made into hominy. \"It [soft corn, see entry 4, description] was used for lye hominy [see Rel. Info. #19, for Miami term], and was the favorite corn for parching, as it was easily chewed. Parched corn, not ground, is called kit\'-sa-min\'-gi, when ground, as it usually was when carried for food, it is called ki-ta\'-sa-ka-ni. Corn in the milk was preserved by boiling and then drying it. This is called min-dji\'-pi co-ko\'-sa-min\'-gi. The favorite corn of the Miamis of recent times is what the whites call \"squaw corn\", and they call ik-ki\'-pa-kin\'-gwa-mi\'-ni (blue corn), or sometimes to-sa\'-ni-a min-dji\'-pi (Indian corn), or Mi-a\'mi min-dji\'-pi (Miami corn). This is an early variety, and sweeter than ordinary corn. The Indians are very fond of a soup made of scraped green corn, which is called min-dji\'-pi n\'po\'-pi, or corn soup.\" (Dunn 1919); 11. FOOD: parched corn. \"The indians sustained themselves on a long hunt or a war party with parched corn. They could carry that with them in a buckskin pouch, and eat it;', '1. White corn is open pollinated and must be protected from cross pollination with other varieties/hybrids, when characterisitcs other than those of the traditional white corn are noticed (e.g. dents), those seeds are not kept for planting (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(1):9, 2002); 2. soldiers reported marching through five miles of Miami corn fields--being able to see Miami cornfields on both sides of the Maumee River for as far as one could see (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki (2ndy source) 5(3)2, 2002, Rogers); 3. Fish, small suckers that were bony, were put with hills of corn, one per hill (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:68; 2ndy source Lamoine probably read about, original source unknown); 4. \"To return to the occupations of the women, at the end of July they begin to mix or dry the corn. They make two kinds. That which they roast gives them more trouble than that which they boil, for they have to make large griddles and exercise particular care to turn the ears from time to time to prevent their burning too much on one side, and afterwards they have to shell off the kernels. They therefore make very little of this kind. The kind which they boil they gather just as tender as the corn for roasting, and with shells, which they find more convenient than knives, they cut all the kernels, throwing away the cobs, until they have about the quantity they wish to cook for that day. They never keep any for the next day because of the excessive care needed to prevent it from turning sour. After this, as soon as it has boiled for a few minutes, they spread it on reed mats, which they also make in the same manner as those that serve for their cabins. The drying process usually takes two days. They make a great store of this kind. As regards the large ears which are ripe at the end of August, after they have gathered it they husk the ears and spread them on mats. In the evening they gather them into a heap and cover them well, when the sun has risen they spread them again, and they keep this up for a week, then they thresh it with big sticks six or seven feet long, in a place which they surround with matting to prevent the flying kernels from getting lost (Pease 1934:343-344, Deliette 1721, \"Pour revenir aux occupations des femmes, a la fin de juillet elles commencent a faire mesler ou secher du bled, elles en font de deux manieres, celuy quelles font Rostir leurs donne plus de peine que celuy quelles sont bouillir, car il faut quelles fassent de un soin rands Grils, et quelles ayent tout particulier de retourner de temps en temps, les espics crainte qu\'ils ne se bruslent trop d\'un coste, et apres il faut qu\'elle l\'egraine c\'est pourquoy elles en font tres peu, celuy qu\'elles font bouillir elles le cueillent aussi tendre que celuy quelles font rostir, et avec des Coquilles qui leurs sont plus commodes que des couteaux elles coupent tous les grains, jetant le conston jusqu\'a ce qu\'elles en ayent la quantite a peu pres qu\'elles en veulent faire cuire dans la meme journee, elles n\'en gardent jamais pour le Lendemain, a cause du trop grand soin qu\'il faudroit prendre pour l\'empescher d\'airgrir, apres quoysitot qu\'il a bouilly un demy quart d\'heure, elles l\'etendent sur des nattes de jonc qu\'elles font aussi de la meme maniere, que ceux don??t elles se servent pour leurs Cabanes, Il faut ordinairement deux jours pour le faire secher, ils en font de grosses provisions. A L\'Egard du gros Bled qui est mure a la fin d\'aoust apres quelles l\'ont cueillis, elles ostent les Robes des Epics et les Estendent sur des nattes, le soir elles le ramassent a un tas et les couvrent bien, quand le soleil est leve elles le retendent et cela pendant huit jours et apres elles le Battent avec de gros bastons de six ou sept pieds de Long, dans un endroit qu\'elles entourent de leurs nattes pour empescher que les grains qui sautent ne se perdent,\"translation from French to English by Pease); 5. General Anthony Wayne wrote: \"The very extensive and highly-cultivated fie;;', NULL, '1. The Shawnee have a dance called the Bread Dance, held in April. Dance preceded by a ball game played etween the men and women, and the twenty kernels used in scoring were planted by one of the women chiefs, after which all the corn could be planted (Clark, Jerry E. 1993); 2. Miami white corn was planted in the spring 2001 by Mildred Walker and other tribal members at Tribal farm outside Commerce, OK (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 4(2):1, 2001); 3. On April 12, 2002 and May 7th, 2002, the annual planting of white corn took place at the Tribal farm outside Commerce, OK (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki, 5(1):5, 2002); 3. Miami white corn was grown by Anna Marks (Lora Sider\'s parents), sister of Joe Mongosa and other Mongosa\'s, and LaMoine\'s parents. This corn stopped being grown when the sweet corn came along. His brother made hominy out of it, called it squaw corn. \"Of course, I\'m sure that Lora\'s folks did [grow white corn]. My folks did. Oh, I think most all of \'em--Mongosas did, I\'m sure. It ended when the sweet corn come on. My brother, after my folks died, they made hominy out of it. They raised it for hominy. It was a soft corn, soft white\" (Interview with Lamoine Marks, Rafert 1989:68-69); 4. There were some Miami men that assumed the dress and character of women, associated with other women, and took equal share in planting, hoeing and gathering of corn, and in other domestic activities. (Trowbridge 1825, from Kinietz 1938:68); 5. Corn preparation: The Delaware would bring the corn in by the wagon loads, and drop it into boiling water for about three minutes, then dumped onto clean wagon sheets and husked and cut by young folks. They would take a spoon and with the handle down, press down right between the rows, resulting in whole kernel corn. They would do this all day long, and if the got a whole row out without it breaking, then they got to go around and get a kiss from whoever we wanted. The Delawares did it differently, cutting their corn and then scraping the cob, as did the Potawatomies, but just for certain dishes.The regular everyday corn was always whole kernel (Kohn 1997: Joanna J. Nichol, Elder, Delaware Tribe of Indians); 6. The Delaware have a number of types of corn, for different uses, including dried, hard corn for corn soup, corn that is scraped off and let set for bread (Kohn 1997, Michael Pace, Delaware); 7. Billie Smith\'s (Shawnee) father raised corn, and would harvest the corn stalks in the fall. He would fashion a bird\'s body out of corn stalks and make it so wings came out of the center (Kohn 1997:199, Interview with Billie Smith); 8. Women helped tend the corn, which could be used as a focus of attack of enemy tribes: \"Several women complained that their corn had been cut, and others that they had found Iroquois moccasins in their fields. . . .if it was true, as their women said, that enemies had cut their corn, they would surprise the enemy scouts, who doubtless were waiting for the crop to ripen before attacking them. They approved of my idea . . . Four days later brought in two Iroquois who had cut corn for the last time.\" (Pease 1934:325, Deliette 1721; \"Plusieurs femmes se plaignirent qu\'on avoit coupe de leur Bled, et d\'autres qu\'elles avoient trouve des souliers d\'Iruqouis dans leurs Champs,\" translation from French to English by Pease); 9. Traditional story regarding origin of Miami white corn. \"The tradition said that probably white corn came from someone who took a trip somewhere to the south and to the west to some unknown location to get the white corn, but no one knows\" (Interview with Chief Floyd Leonard by Kerri Carlson, Chief\'s Office, Miami, OK, 6/6/96, MTO Archives); 10. There are numerous phrases relating to corn use, harvesting and preparation in St. Jerome (ca.1692, translation from French to English by Costa 2004)(see attachment); 11. Archaeological studies have demonstrated that corn was cultivated as a food resource by Late Woodland (prior to 700 A.D through 1450 A.D.) indigenous people;', 'TRUE', '(see attachmt.: Pinet\'s Corn Terms)', NULL, 'corn', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')
(250, 'MTUwNTg2MTMwNzo0ODgwODoy', 2, 0, 1, 'Zizania aquatica L.', 'Wild rice, Indian wheat, Maggot Soup', 'Poaceae (Grass)', 'nalomina (Miami)', NULL, '1. Occurs on shores and associated wetland areas in eastern Miami lands (Gleason and Cronquist 1991) and occurs in swamps and borders of ponds and stream in southeastern Missouri (western Miami lands) (Steyermark 1963);', NULL, NULL, 'TRUE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', 'FALSE', '1. FOOD: \"maggot \" soup made of wild rice (Dunn ca. 1900); 2. FOOD: eaten \"nalomini, rice (wild)\" (Dunn ca. 1900:3953dw); 3. FOOD: \" . . .and the river upon which we row\'d, to find the place we were to land and carry our canow into the other, was so full of wild-oats, that it lookt [sic] rather like a corn-field than a river, insomuch that we cou\'d hardly discover its channel. As the Miamis frequented this place [somewhere in southern Wisconsin], they conducted us to the usual place of portage . . .\" (Marquette 1673:201, from Thwaites 1903:643); 4. UNKNOWN: a plant called \"indian wheat\" by Joutel (?) (Aatotankiki Myaamiaki (2ndy source) 3(1):3, 2000); 5. FOOD: wild rice probably traded and harvested in Miami territory, since it grows in the area (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', NULL, '1. Wild rice used to grow in the Fort Wayne area, approximately in the 1980s and before, but the certain type of wet area it needs are diminishing (Interview with Dani Tippman, 2005);', '1. McPherson wrote that wild rice, \"was a favorite food of the Potawatomie Indians because it could be kept for use in the winter when other vegetable foods and meat were scarce or difficult to obtain\" (1977:37, 2ndy source without primary source citation); 2. Louis Joliet described the Menominees gathering and use of wild rice in 1673: \"The Wild Oats, from which they have got their name, is a sort of corn which grows naturally in the small rivers, the bottom whereof is Owzie [oozy or slimy], as also in marshy grounds. It is much like our European oats; the stem is knotted, and grows about two foot above the surface of the water. The corn is not bigger than ours, but it is twice as long, and therefore it yields much more meal. It grows above the water in June, and the savages gather it about September in this manner: They go in their canows into those rivers, and as they go they shake the ears of corn in their canows, which easily falls, if it be ripe: They dry it upon the fire; and when it is very dry, they put it into a kind of sack made with the skin of beasts; and having made a hole in the ground, they put their sack therein, and tread on it till they see the chaff is separated from the corn, which they winnow afterwards. They pound it in a mortar to reduce it into meal, or else boil it in water, and season it with grease, which makes it near as good as our rice\" (Joliet 1674:196-197, from Thwaites 1903:636-637; also described by Marquette 1674, from Kenton 1925:336); 3. The Miami-Illinois name for the Menominee is \'naloomina\', which means people of the wild rice (Costa 2000:41);', 'FALSE', 'malomina (Peoria)', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, '2017-09-19 22:48:27', '2017-09-19 22:48:27')